(52, 'The warm-up question was &quot;What questions do you have about making a concept map?&quot;, which is a tool we discussed on Monday.  After clarifying the process of making a concept map and showing an example of a map, we talked about the big ideas and essential questions for the unit (The Internal Environment).  Students then did a quick write to communicate what they currently know and understand about balance and balance in organisms.  Students then worked on their own concept maps until the end of the period.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(53, 'Students turned in their lab safety contract and completed a NSTA survey for warm-up.  We then (briefly) discussed Class Connect.  I reiterated the importance of motion in our daily lives, and we reviewed how to calculate speed and the materials available to conduct the first experiment.  Students then worked in their groups to complete the first two sections of their science writing heuristic (the question being investigated and how they were attemping to answer the question--that is, designing an experiment using the format of an experimental design diagram).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(54, 'We began class by describing a couple of pieces of artwork (&quot;The Future of Times Square&quot; and &quot;Manifest Destiny&quot; by Alexis Rockman) and discussing what the artist may have been attempting to communicate.  After mentioning the &quot;earth 2100&quot; class forum and explicitly discussing class expectations, we then watched the rest of the &quot;earth 2100&quot; video.  After the video, students were asked to reconsider and revise their original quick write (08/20) about stability (in light of any new understandings/knowledge).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(55, 'The warm-up asked two questions about the speed of light (describe what 300,000,000 m/s actually means and what it means to say the universe has a speed limit).  After discussing the warm-up, students worked on completing their lab and their science writing heuristic, which was due before the end of the period.  Students then began working on the &quot;Is there a (human) speed limit?&quot; worksheet.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(56, 'Today, students either worked on the virtual biome assignment (completing the table that outline the characteristics of 6 major biomes) or began completing the information sheets for the Great Environment Debate.  The biome assignment is due next Mon. and the Great Debate info. sheets are due at the beginning of class tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(57, 'After an insightful discussion about the warm-up question (if decision-making should continue as is or if the precautionary principle should be employed), students began working on the biome tour assignment.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(58, 'The warm-up took longer than usual because we read a description of an experiment and attempted to identify the different parts of that experiment (independent variable, dependent variable, constants, etc.).  We then worked on completing section 2 (tests) and 3 (observations) of the science writing heuristic (SWH).  Groups who completed sections 1 - 3 of the SWH and had those sections checked by me for any major errors and then began conducting their experiment.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(59, 'I just posted a link to &quot;The Story of Stuff&quot;.  If you were interested in &quot;earth 2100&quot;, you might find this 10-min. animated documentary about the life cycle of material goods interesting.  After watching, you may even reconsider your current purchasing habits.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(60, 'I began class by reviewing my expectations for nuisance devices in class (e.g. cell phones, MP3 players).  For the warm-up, students looked at an example Science Writing Heuristic (SWH) from the last lab and identified something done well and something that could be improved.  Students used the remainder of class time to work on &quot;The (Human) Speed Limit&quot; worksheet, which is due on Mon. and is also posted in Shared Content.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(61, 'Today...we argued.  Monday...we''ll argue some more.  Hopefully, the arguments will be even more heated after a couple days rest.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(62, 'It is important that you check our ClassConnect site every day for schedule changes, notices, and to stay on top of deadlines for your QUIA quizzes. Please use the &quot;forums&quot; section to leave me suggestions for class and to socialize with each other. This wall is reserved for class related Q and A. Thanks! ;-)', 89, 1, 241, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(63, 'Today we began by discussing the rubric that will be used to evaluate the life skills portion of your grade.  We also discussed the score/percent/letter grade conversion chart so that you know how to interpret your scores.  During the rest of class, we used dry-erase boards to practiced the problem-solving strategy for solving motion problems involving speed, distance and time.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(64, 'Today we began by discussing the rubric that will be used to evaluate the life skills portion of your grade.  We also discussed the (homework) late policy and the score/percent/letter grade conversion chart so that students know how to interpret their scores.  Students received their senior year Biozone workbooks and I briefly talked about why we use this particular resource, which does cost $20 (please pay at your earliest convenience).  During the remainder of the class, we debated about what is the single greatest threat to biodiversity.  At the end of class, students were asked to stop and reflect upon the 2-day debate by writing a brief reflection (no more than 5 sentences) to 1 of 4 different prompts.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(65, 'Today, students used the University of Colorado''s PhET simulation &quot;The Moving Man&quot; to explore the meaning and concepts of position, velocity and acceleration.  The Moving Man assignment is posted in Shared Content and is due by the end of class on Weds. (09/01).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(66, 'The warm-up question was to describe the function or role of the Colorado Division of Wildlife. After talking about student responses, we went over the most important vocabulary words and word roots for this unit, which is Option G: Ecology &amp; Conservation.   (Note: The order we did things today was a little awkward.  My bad.).  I then discussed the meaning of the objective levels in the red book and the way I would prefer students to take their notes.  (Note: A rubric for evaluating the notes has been posted in the class folder within Shared Content). Students then read the article &quot;Lynx Links&quot; to deepen their understanding of the DOW''s role and to acquire background information about the role of active management techniques in wildlife conservation.  Since students took their own notes for learning objective G.4.4, we also &quot;unpacked&quot; this objective to help focus the note-taking efforts.  The following are learning objectives that were &quot;unpacked&quot; from G.4.4 and should be addressed in those notes:\r<br />1) Define “wildlife management” and list some wildlife mgt. techniques\r<br />2) Define basic wildlife mgt. terms by inferring meaning from the context in which the term is used.\r<br />3) Distinguish between state and federal wildlife management agencies and the responsibilities of each.\r<br />4) Define “threatened” , “endangered” and “extinct” as applied to wildlife and state and federal law.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(67, 'We warmed up today by answering the following question: What makes an energy source renewable vs. nonrenewable?  What are examples of each type?  Students shared their responses as we completed a Venn diagram as a class to compare the two sources.  We looked at a description of both energy soures on some PowerPoint slides and then watched a brief Schoolhouse Rock vide (&quot;The Energy Blues&quot;).  Afterwards, students began doing research for The Great Energy debate by individually completing information sheet for each of hte 10 sources of energy (To do this, students read the statements about the energy source and marked if the statement was a neutral fact or was either an advantage or disadvantage of that particular energy source).  These sheets must be completed by the beginning of class on Mon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(68, 'Students continued working on the &quot;Introduction to the Moving Man&quot; assignment.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(69, 'We began the period by discussing questions about yesterday''s class.  We then read a brief article about the intensive process of wildlife reintroduction efforts and identified some important questions that need to be answered before such efforts are even considered.  We then talked about what we will do in class tomorrow, which is to use the Colorado DOW''s website to research the factors contributing to the extirpation or endangerment of a specific species in Colorado, the management techniques taken to reestablish viable populations of those species, and the effectiveness of those techniques.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(70, 'Today, we discussed the potential changes in students class schedules that will take affect next Tues.  Students were given approximately 40 min. to complete the &quot;Introducing the Moving Man&quot; assignment.  This assignment must be completed and saved in the Student Save-in folder no later than Tues. (09/07/10).  We ended class by answering a couple review questions and comparing scalar and vector quantities.  Today''s exit ticket was a 1 question quiz about the material students have been learning.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(71, 'The zoo has a lot of &quot;cheetahs&quot;...get it?\r<br />Anyways, today we used the Colorado DOW''s website to investigate one species that was reintroduced to the state.  Our main focus was on the reasons why that species'' population declined so dramatically, the efforts conservation biologists used to reestablish a viable population, and the effectiveness of those (active) management strategies.  Students should expect to give brief presentations about what they learned on Tues.  Enjoy your 4-day weekend!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(72, 'FYI, the addition of new class sections and the hiring of a new science teacher did not affect your schedule EXCEPT that all periods of physics will meet in room 415 (room 404 is no longer available).  Show up to all of your classes as usual, and come to 415 during your usual Physics period.  I will see you on Tues. and we will continue as planned.  Thank you for your patience and understanding and enjoy the extended weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(73, 'FYI, the addition of new class sections and the hiring of the new science teacher will not affect any of your schedules.  Thank you for your patience and understanding and I''ll see you on Tues.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(74, 'Today, we used dry-erase boards to practice solving physics problems involving speed, velocity and acceleration.  The most common problem seemed to be correctly identifying units of measurement (e.g. meters is a measure of distance, meters per second measures speed, etc).\r<br />\r<br />A few students seemed to struggle with the calculations themselves.  If you are are struggling with solving these types of problems, get help ASAP!  Come and see me before school, after school or during office hours or ask a friend, classmate, relative or another teacher to explain how they solve these types of problems.  The math and concepts will become progressively more difficult, so be proactive and take the initiative to seek help as soon as you begin feeling lost.  Attacking these problems is a skill and the best way to learn and refine a skill is with practice and feedback.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(75, 'Well I thought today was an excellent day in class I really don''t know if I''m the only one here reviewing today in class but I thought today was really easy in class at the beginning of class but going towards the end of class it got really confusing with the problems and different types of equations well I''m on my way to do something like homework\r<br />\r<br />-Darian', 1339, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(76, 'After the fire drill, Saleel, Kyle and Juhi presented what they learned from their research into the reintroduction efforts of a native species back into Colorado.  Each presenter gave background information about their animal, reasons for the animal''s population decline, an explanation of active wildlife techniques used to re-establish the species back into the state, and an evaluation of the effectiveness of those efforts.  The remaining class time was spent mapping the historic distribution of lynx in the West, which is an essential piece of information when attempting to reintroduce a species back into its native range.  \r<br />\r<br />Remember to bring your graphing calculators tomorrow and Thursday!  We''ll use them one, if not both, of those days!\r<br />\r<br />*By the way, what is going on Friday?  Several students mentioned that they may be absent from class that day.  If a lot of you will be absent, I''ll do my best to re-arrange plans so that those who are absent won''t be at a complete loss when returning.\r<br />\r<br />Thank you and enjoy your night.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(77, 'I don''t think you are alone Darian.  We''ll continue practicing the problems in class, and, if you continue working hard, this will probably seem very easy by the time we take the test.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(78, 'We began class by sorting different units of measurement (e.g. m/s, m/s2) into their appropriate categories (distance, time, velocity and acceleration).  We discussed a student''s role in learning and watched a commercial about two people being stuck on an escalator.  We also talked about how this commercial was a metaphor for life and for some students in class.  We ended the period by beginning the next assignment (Graphing the Moving Man), in which you will learn how to analyze and interpret motion graphs.  We will continue working on this assignment tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(79, 'We began class today by practicing answering questions that checked our understanding of biomes.  After several questions, we connected the concept of biomes to ecoregions and discussed how mapping the historic distribution of lynx can help us to identify the preferred habitat of this species.  Students responded to 8 paper two-type questions that analyzed the geographic distribution of lynx and data presented in graph form.  After students turned in their assignment, they received a brief article to read at their leisure.  No assignment, but I suggest adding some of the information from the text to your notes--focus on the relevant information (&quot;relevant&quot; is determined by the learning objectives listed in your red book).\r<br />\r<br />Don''t forget to bring your graphing calculator tomorrow and your Biozone book Fri.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(80, 'The warm-up question was to calculate the final velocity of an object at rest that began accelerating -2 m/s2 for 5 seconds.  After students had time to complete this problem, I shared 3 different strategies for attacking this problem, all of which utilized the V.I.P. that we''ve been using during practice.  Students used the rest of the period to complete the &quot;Graphing the Moving Man&quot; assignment.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(81, 'Today''s warm-up question was as follows: List the trophic levels found in ecosystems.  Which trophic level is the MOST important?  Why?  After discussing responses and fact that some organisms, like omnivores and decomposers, are difficult to categorize, we talked about how trophic interactions between species must be considered in reintroduction efforts.  We then began contructing a mathematical model to describe the populatoin dynamics between lynx and their primary prey, the snowshoe hare.  Since students were on-task and having very productive conversations about the models, the due date for the assignment was extended.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(82, 'The questions for the Chinwag next Thurs. are as follows:\r<br />1) Which is a better conservation strategy, targeting the producers of an ecosystem OR the top consumers? Why?\r<br />2) What role does public perception play in conservation efforts?\r<br />3) How might research on the starfish Pisaster apply to the management of lynx in Colorado?\r<br />4) How does this text relate to the BIG ideas of this unit?', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(83, 'Today was a work day.  Students used the period to either 1) take notes, 2) work on their Biozone assignment, 3) complete &quot;Hare Today, Gone Tommorow&quot; (assignment we started yesterday), or 4) read the prologue and chapter 1 from &quot;Where the Wild Things Were&quot;.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(84, 'Today, we started by looking at an abstract piece of art and attempted to make connections between the art and what we are currently learning.  After discussing the warm-up responses, we did some motion graph calisthenics, where students used their bodies to represent motion graphs for different scenarios of objects in motion.  Finally, students became familiar with the hardware and software we will use for the next lab and most groups actually completed part 1 of the lab (testing their predictions).  We will finish the lab (parts 2 and 3) on Mon.  Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(85, 'Create a goal and schedule for completing both the notes and the Biozone assignment.  Time management will play a significant role in this course (e.g. future labs, G4, studying for the test in May) and college next year.  Don''t let Oct. 1st creep up on you.  Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(86, 'FYI, I made phone calls home today about attendance issues.  Remember, the expectation is that you go to every class, every day on time.  If students continue struggling with either coming to class or arriving on time, the next step is to communicate that issue to the administration.  If we fix the problem now, you''re more likely to be successful in the future.  Don''t be stuck on an escalator.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(87, 'MMMMMMMMMMMMMM I LOVEIE THIS CLASS LETS ALL PLAY A LOVEGAME &lt;3', 1899, 1, 249, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(88, 'The last exorcist was freaking horrible', 1919, 1, 249, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(89, 'We began the period by discussing the difference between instantaneous velocity and average velocity and how to calculate these values from motion graphs.  Students then worked on the lab we began on Fri., which was using the motion detectors to predict, create, interpret and anlalyze motion graphs.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(90, 'We began by completing a graphic organizer that required students to identify and describe the 5 major components of a scientific experiment.  We then discussed how to complete an experimental design diagram, which is a good method for communicating the design of an experiment and for checking to ensure all the essential aspects of an experiment were included and clearly defined (Note: An experimental design diagram is NOT the same as a data table).  We also discussed how hypotheses should be written in an &quot;If-and-then&quot; format (NOT &quot;If-then-because&quot;) and  digressed to talk about how hypotheses do NOT progress into theories and theories do NOT progress into laws (see above posting for clarification).  We also talked about the &quot;ethics&quot; of animal experiments.  We didn''t accomplish everything planned and some of us may have walked away slightly confused, but plans are just plans and sometimes confusion is good.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(91, 'Common Misconception: If evidence supports a hypothesis, it is upgraded to a theory. If the theory then garners even more support, it may be upgraded to a law. \r<br />\r<br />This misconception may be reinforced by introductory science courses that treat hypotheses as &quot;things we''re not sure about yet&quot; and that only explore established and accepted theories. In fact, hypotheses, theories, and laws are rather like apples, oranges, and kumquats: one cannot grow into another, no matter how much fertilizer and water are offered. Hypotheses, theories, and laws are all scientific explanations that differ in breadth — not in level of support. Hypotheses are explanations that are limited in scope, applying to fairly narrow range of phenomena. The term law is sometimes used to refer to an idea about how observable phenomena are related — but the term is also used in other ways within science. Theories are deep explanations that apply to a broad range of phenomena and that may integrate many hypotheses and laws.\r<br />\r<br />(Taken from the University of California Berkeley''s Understanding Science website undsci.berkeley.edu/teaching/misconceptions.php#b12)', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(92, 'I haven''t found a definitive explanation about why fish infected w/ whirling disease have black tails, but did find a possible explanation.  It seems that the parasite, which feeds on cartilage, may induce an inflammatory response in the host.  This inflammation constricts the spinal cord, brain stem, and caudal nerves.  The constriction induces the erratic swimming behavior (whirling) and results in tissue damage that causes the tail to turn black (necrosis).  I found this info the following source: Rose JD, Marrs GS, Lewis C, Schisler G. Whirling disease behavior and its relation to pathology of brain stem and spinal cord in rainbow trout. Journal of Aquatic Animal Health. 2000;12:107–118.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(93, 'The warm-up question today was to compare the graphs obtained from using &quot;The Moving Man&quot; simulation with graphs obtained using the probeware (motion detector).  Two differences we discussed were that negative position values could not be graphed using the motion detector and the increase in &quot;noise&quot; (squiggles in the motion graph).  Students used the rest of the period to recreate position-time and velocity-time graphs.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(94, 'For the warm-up question, students practiced completing an experimental design diagram for a given scenario and compared their responses to an acceptable example.  Students then worked in groups to design a possible experiment that was used to gather information in several different data tables.  Most everyone appears to be skilled at describing the essential components of an experiment, but identifying those variables from tables seems to be challenging.  It''s OK for students to be struggling with completing experimental design diagrams at this point in time, but everyone should continue practicing this skill.  In addition to being assessed on your ability to complete an experimental design diagrams on internal assessments, these diagrams are a great tool for thinking about experiments and identifying both assumptions and limitations of data that are being presented, which is a skill you will need to use in both Papers 2 and3.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(95, 'Students had a substitute teacher today.  During the period, students should have worked on taking notes, writing summaries and answering questions about position-time graphs.  The information and an interactive version of the worksheet can be obtained from the website Physics Lab Online at the following url: http://dev.physicslab.org/Document.aspx?doctype=3&amp;filename=Kinematics_PositionTimeGraphs.xml.  We''ll review the answers to the problems tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(96, 'Students had a substitute teacher today and worked on either taking notes for Option G, completing their Biozone assignment or reading the text for tomorrow''s chinwag.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(97, 'Mr. kern! can we turn in the moving man assignment in late? let me know so i can get it done because i totally forgot i didnt turn it in', 1338, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(98, 'and one more thing, we got notes done yester day but did not have time for questions can we have some time to get this done?\r<br />', 1338, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(99, 'Kern! \r<br />ok obvously the questions got answered and assuming you take late work i turned in my m oving mann assignment its in the student save in folder i would appreciate it if you could get a grade in their for me thank you\r<br />', 1338, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(100, 'Today we had an excellent discussion about the readings from &quot;Where the Wild Things Were&quot;.  We wrapped up class with a brief (written) reflection.  Students made some very thoughtful and insightful remarks during the discussion and I''m sure students still had a lot of opinions and questions that went unstated.  Overall, it was an excellent discourse, I learned a lot and am impressed by your preparation and sophistication of thinking.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(101, 'Tim,\r<br />Thanks for letting me know about the assignment.  I will look at it and provide feedback as soon as I have an opportunity.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(102, 'The warm-up question today was to calculate the speed and velocity of an athlete who ran 400-m around a track in 54 seconds.  We followed with a discussion of displacment and compared displacement to distance.  We then discussed position-time graphs for objects with a constant velocity and reviewed the correct answers to the questions from the worksheet you received yesterday.  The exit ticket today was to write down one concept you feel like you really understand and one concept that you are struggling with understanding.\r<br />\r<br />If you would like to finish answering the questions on the worksheet or would like more practice answering these types of questions, to the the Physics Lab Online website (see the link posted in shared content or go the the following url: http://dev.physicslab.org/Document.aspx?doctype=3&amp;filename=Kinematics_PositionTimeGraphs.xml).  Using this resource, you can submit your answers electronically and recieve immediate feedback about those answers.  Remember, being able to answer these types of questions will earn you at least a C (2.0) on the test.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(103, 'Oh yeah, in regards to Tim''s earlier question, you will have some time during class on another day to take notes on these concepts.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your evening.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(104, 'Hello Mr.Kern its zayda from 4th hour and i didnt go to school today, i was wondering what we did today in class, and if we had any homework. \r<br />if you could please send me that, that would be great.\r<br />Thanks', 1337, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(105, 'During class today, we used the clickers to practice reading, interpreting and responding to test questions about the vocabulary of motion, the units of measurement for displacement, velocity, and acceleration, and position-time graphs.\r<br />\r<br />If you missed class today, I highly recommend you go to the online physics lab website (see link in shared content or the postings from yesterday and the day below) and practice the same skills by doing the interactive worksheets for constant velocity position-time graphs (see Table of Contents and click on Kinematics: Graphs).  Next week we''ll focus again on calculation and velocity-time graphs.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(106, 'After the fire drill that many of you celebrated--I am hurt, by the way, and am known to hold grudges--students compared the experimental design diagrams they completed from the lynx/snowshoe hare data they received on Tues to an example of a digram made for the same data set. Students also wrote evaluative remarks on their diagrams based on their comparison. With the 15 - 20 minutes that remained, we used the clickers to practice reading, interpreting and responding to typical IB-style test questions and to evaluate our current understanding of biomes, populations, and conservation biology.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(107, 'Today we explored the concept of a niche by reading descriptions of several different species of birds.  We came to understand that, while different species may have overlapping niches, their niches are not identical.  We also looked at how species can be described as &quot;generalists&quot; or &quot;specialists&quot;, depending on the breadth of certain aspects of their niche.  We also discussed the fact that species tend to occupy &quot;realized&quot; niches as opposed to &quot;fundamental&quot; niches due to factors including competition.  At the end of the period, students were given their first summative assessment (use the concepts we are currently learning about, including niche, to explain the evolution of Darwin''s finches).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(108, 'Today, students read problems and used dry-erase boards to practice analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs.  The type of questions we focused on were those that were commonly missed by students last Friday on the clicker assessment (e.g calculating acceleration, average and instantaneous velocity from s-t graphs).  After ~30 min., we transitioned to another area that students demonstrated they needed more practice...vocabulary.  We discuss how to complete vocabulary word diagrams and then students completed these diagrams as they defined, illustrated and wrote sentences for each of the 7 vocab words this unit (acceleration, displacement, distance, position, scalar quantity, vector quantity, and velocity).  Students will have time in class tomorrow to complete these diagrams.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(109, 'Today''s warm-up question was as follows: A car begins at a position of +3 m and travels until it reaches position -7 m.  What is the car''s total displacement?  Why?\r<br />\r<br />After discussing responses to the warm-up question, we discussed the scores student earned on their vocab word cards they completed yesterday and how those scores could be improved before the test.  Students then received and filled out an equation reference sheet, which they can use on the test next Tues.  For the remainder of the period, students completed the reamaining vocab word cards and then chose to either:\r<br />(1) Meet w/ a partner or Mr. Kern to ask clarifying questions about what we''ve been learning,\r<br />(2) Go to the website Online Physics Lab (physicslab.org) and finish taking notes on position-time graphs,\r<br />(3) Go to the Online Physics lab website and practice answering questions about position-time graphs using their interactive worksheets, or\r<br />(4) Go to the Online Physics lab website and begin learning about and taking notes on position-time graphs that show objects with accelerated motion.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(110, 'Note: I posted the vocab word card document in shared content.  If you need to complete this assignment but don''t have the word cards, just download the document and print.  Alternatively, you could complete each card in electronic form (in the Word document) and print them later.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(111, 'After a debate about how to pronouce &quot;niche&quot;, students described their own niche* for the warm-up question.  I attempted to explain the &quot;Darwin''s Finches&quot; assessment and then moved on to highlight the basic aspects of the &quot;Tale of 2 Species&quot; assignment, before students were given time to work.\r<br />\r<br />*Note: Point of clarification in case the warm-up was misleading, in ecology only species have niches...not individuals.  In a colloquial sense, we all have our own niche.  The same is true for evolution.  According to the biological definition, only populations can evolve.  In common parlance, individuals are able to evolve.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(112, 'Today, students had the option of working on either\r<br />(1) the Darwin''s Finches assessment that is due tomorrow,\r<br />(2) the &quot;Tale of 2 Species&quot; assignment that is due on Mon.,\r<br />(3) taking notes for Opt. G, or\r<br />(4) working on their Biozone assignment.\r<br />Most students were on-task and very productive.  Tomorrow is a work day as well.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(113, 'im here XD', 1982, 1, 291, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(114, 'At the beginning of the period, students sketched a position-time graph for an object that showed 4 different types of movements (resting for 2 seconds, traveling at +1 m/s for 5 seconds, traveling at -1 m/s for 5 seconds, and having a final displacement of -4).  Students then worked on their vocab word cards, their notes for this unit, or practiced responding to sample test questions on the Online Physics Lab website.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(115, 'At the beginning of the period, students used a rubric to evaluate their first summative assessment (Darwin''s Finches).  Students used the remainder of the period to work on either (1) taking notes for this unit (Option G), (2) completing their Biozone assignment, (3) finishing their &quot;Tale of 2 Species&quot; Assignment, or (4) asking me clarifying questions about the aforementioned assignments.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy the 3-day weekend and see you Mon.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(116, 'We began class by analyzing a position-time graph that showed the motion of an object with constant velocity and the motion of an object that was accelerating. After cmoparing the the graphs, we discussed the concept of acceleration and compared position-time graphs that were showing different types of acceleration. I attempted to emphasize that &quot;As the slope goes, so does the velocity.&quot; \r<br />\r<br />Students were then given the task of constructing a concept map that synthesized what they understand about motion. This map is due at the beginning of class on Tues. and will be included as part of their summative grade.  Students used the rest of the perioid to work on their concept map or complete their notes and vocab word cards for this unit, which they turned in before they left class.\r<br />', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(117, 'Grades for the Darwin''s Finches assessment have been posted.  Your &quot;P&quot; has now been replaced with a percent and letter grade.  When I hand back your assignment on Mon., you will have the choice of keeping your grade as is or revising your respose in attempt to provide evidence that you do understand the concepts/objectives being assessed (esp. those in topic 5.4, and options D2 and G1).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(118, 'test', 2019, 1, 295, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(119, 'During today''s warm up, students completed a self reflection by evaluating their current understanding of 5 separate skills that will be assessed by tomorrow''s test.  I handed back student''s notes and vocab word cards and gave students who turned in their notes example notes to compare and use as a study tool.  Students used the rest of class to 1) practice matching units of measurement to the quantities they describe using an Excel spreadsheet, 2) practice responding to sample test questions by completing interactive worksheets on physicslab.or, and/or 3) completing their concept map.\r<br />\r<br />CONCEPT MAP DUE (BEGINNNIG OF PERIOD) AND TEST TOMORROW!  STUDY!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(120, 'We began the period by self-evaluating the Darwin''s Finches assessment using the rubric and comments written on their paper.  I discussed the importance of using language precisely to accurately communicate ideas and highlighted common errors made on the assessment (e.g. implying preadaptation is possible).  Students were then given the option of either keeping the score they earned on the assessment or revising their assessment to demonstrate a higher level of understanding of the topics being assessed (several objectives listed within topic 5.1 and Options D and G).  We used the rest of the period to discuss different types of ecological interactions and watched video clips to observe if the predicted relationship among species was accurate.  We''ll continue exploring species interactions tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(121, 'Today, students got to show off how much they knew by taking a test over analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs for the position, velocity and acceleration of moving objects.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(122, 'Today, we finished watching a series of video clips to identify the type of ecological interactions being illustrated between species.  We concluded with students writing analogies of ecological relationships using their own life experiences as a reference.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(123, 'Today''s warm-up question was to describe an anologous ecological relationship to describe the interaction between me and you.  We discussed responses to the warm up and to the ecological interactions activity we completed yesterday.  Then, we began exploring the effect of zebra mussels by reading and answering several questions about the species.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08');
INSERT INTO `class_wall` (`comment_id`, `body`, `userID`, `level`, `classID`, `schoolID`, `date_posted`) VALUES
(124, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;How doyou think you did on yesterday''s test (A, B, C, D, F)?  What can you do to improve your score next time?&quot;  I discussed the make-up schedule for students who had an excused absence yesterday and asked students to sign up for a specific time before leaving.  I also explained that students who did not turn in their concept map before the test did not submit enough evidence of understanding to pass the exam.  Students who think they could demonstrate a deeper understanding of the material may retake the test after submitting evidence that they worked to improve their weak areas.  The retake will be offered during class either at the end of next week or the beginning of the following week.  During the rest of class, students created a velocity-time graph using a position-time graph from an earlier activity.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(125, 'We began class, as usual, by discussing the warm-up question (What exactly are &quot;attending skill&quot;?) and reviewing the process and reasoning for redirects.  I turned back the tests and we discussed how the tests were scored and errors made on the test, so that students understood why they earned the grade they did and how to improve their responses in the future.  Students also compared their initial assessments of what they thought they knew to what they actually earned on the test.\r<br />\r<br />Students can retake the test on Oct. 12th for a grade replacement; BUT, to be eligible for the retake students must submit evidence that they worked to learn or better understand the areas they missed on the test.  For example, if students did not score at a proficient level on Part 1 of the test (+ or 80%), they could submit revised vocab word cards, index (flash) cards, or a revised concept map as evdidence they tried to learn the material better.  For Part 2, students could practice answering questions on the online websites, revise their notes, or create their own graphs and practice answering questions.  The online websites I recommend are Online Physics Lab (dev.physicslab.org) and The Physics Classroom (www.physicsclassroom.com/).  Remember, when searching for review material, the topic we are learning about is kinematics graphs (particularly, position-time graphs).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(126, 'I''ve posted 2 websites (shared content) that may help you take notes on objectives G.3.4 - G.3.6.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(127, 'I began the period by reminding students to cite any sources they use to complete assignments (e.g. If you''re using a definition from a website, either write the definition in your own words OR cite the source from which the defn. was taken).  If you do not cite your sources, you''ve committed plagiarism.  After this, students worked in groups to read information and discuss the impacts of zebra mussels on the Great Lakes ecosystem.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(128, 'I just posted 3 different worksheets (shared content) that you can complete and submit as evidence of practice for analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs. Remember, you must submit evidence of improving your understanding of this knowledge and skill before you can retake the test on Oct. 12th. You can also access the websites for Physics Lab Online, The Physics Classroom, GCSE Bitesize and Motion Vocabulary Flashcards to help you study.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(129, 'Questions for Thursday''s (10/07/10) Chinwag.\r<br />\r<br />1) What factors contributed to the extinction of the dodo?\r<br />\r<br />2) Does it matter that the dodo is extinct?  Why or why not? \r<br />\r<br />3) What is the take-away message from this text?  In what ways does the story of the dodo apply to us now?\r<br />\r<br />4) How does this reading relate to the BIG ideas of this unit? (Equilibrium is a physical state in which forces and changes occur in opposite and off-setting directions. A system is an organized group of related objects or components that form a whole.  Systems have boundaries, resource flow, feedback, and components.  These components are often interconnected &amp; interdependent.)\r<br />\r<br />5) How does this reading help to answer the essential questions of this unit? (How is stability maintained in living systems and what are the consequences of disrupting this stability?\r<br />How do my actions affect myself as well as others?  What are the costs and benefits of these actions?)', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(130, 'Today, students finished describing the effects of zebra mussels on the Great Lakes ecosystem.  When all of the questions were answered, students then received the reading for next Thursday''s chinwag (a few chapters from from &quot;The Song of the Dodo&quot;) and their next assignment, which is due Wednesday.  Students will be given time in class on Monday, and maybe Tuesday, to work on this assignment.  Have a great weekend!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(131, 'The warm-up question reviewed how to calculate the velocity of an object from a position-time graph (calculate the slope of the line).  Students then transformed two position-time graphs into velocity-time graphs, which is a skill they will need for the next test.  Students who finished their graphs and were given feedback by me will begin the velocity graph matching activity on Monday.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(132, 'Those of you who did not come in to make up your test yesterday or today will be able to take the test retake during class on Oct. 12th.  Like everyone else, you MUST submit evidence before Oct. 12th that you have been studying vocabulary terms and practicing analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs.  I described what that evidence may look like on one of yesterday''s posts.  If you do not submit evidence that you have been preparing, you will be given the opportunity to re-take that test and will need to demonstrate your understanding by completing a project.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(133, 'After clarifying &quot;muddy points&quot; (things students are still struggling to understand) about how to transform position-time graphs into velocity-time graphs, students practiced this skill by transforming 2 position time graphs on the computer into velocity-time graphs on graph paper.  Students corrected their graphs until they were no errors and, when those graphs were approved by me, students then began the velocity graph matching assignment.  We''ll continue working on this assignment tomorrow. \r<br />\r<br />Reminder: Work on completing your evidence of studying so that you can retake last week''s test on analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(134, 'Students who hadn''t yet completed their zebra mussel worksheets continued discussing the problems and writing responses to the questions until all of the questions were answered and reviewed by me.  Students who finally completed this in-class assignment then worked as teams to complete their ecological assessment, which will be graded as part of Fri.''s test on community ecology.  We will continue working on this assignment tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(135, 'We began class by comparing position-time and velocity-time graphs (similarities and differences).  After discussing student responses, students completed transforming their position-time graphs into velocity-time graphs and/or began using motion detectors to recreate velocity-time graphs.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(136, 'We began the period by discussing how grading works in this class (standards-referenced), the format for the upcoming test on community ecology, and my observations and feedback on the notes that students turned in for this unit.  Students used the rest of the time in class to work on their environmental assessment report, which is due tomorrow and will be scored as part of the community ecology summative assessment.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(137, 'Today was an early-release day.  We continued working on the velocity graph matching activity to understand (1) how velocity-time graphs are different from position-time graphs and (2) how we can predict position-time graphs from velocity-time graphs.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(138, 'Today, students played the role of moderator and evaluated a selection of another student''s Biozone responses using model answers as a reference.  One of the goals for this activity was to gain a better understanding of how to clearly and concisely communicate scientific knowledge.  We''ll spend the first 10 min. of class tomorrow completing the grading and then we''ll move on to the chinwag.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(139, 'kern my vocab. cards are showing up missing on the infinate campus link.... you have a grade on the paper though? what can we do about this?\r<br />', 1338, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(140, 'Today''s warm-up question was as follows: What have you completed, so far, that you can turn in as evidence of studying vocab words?  Evidence for analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs?  REMEMBER, ANYONE WHO WOULD LIKE TO TAKE THE TEST RE-TAKE MUST TURN IN CONVINCING EVIDENCE OF STUDYING.\r<br />\r<br />After students wrote a response to the warm-up question, we reviewed position-time graphs by reading a description of an object in motion and, with the help of a partner, matched that description to one or more position-time graphs.  The first 2 teams to correctly identify graphs for all 8 descriptions won a small prize.  After this, students worked on transforming position-time graphs into both velocity- and acceleration-time graphs, a skill they will need for the next test.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(141, 'Tim,\r<br />If you have your graded vocab cards, just turn them in tomorrow (Fri) and I''ll look at IC and see why they were marked as missing.  If it''s an error on my part, I''ll fix it before the end of the day.  \r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your evening.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(142, 'We used the first 15 min. of class to finish grading the Biozone workbooks. We then discussed &quot;chapters&quot; 71 - 76 from &quot;The Song of the Dodo&quot;. Students had some very interesting thoughts about the reading and, while I can''t say I agree with everything that was said, it was a productive discussion and I did learn a lot. For the post-chinwag reflection, I asked students to consider what our responsibility is as a human species. For example, should we practice biological imperialism and manipulate the environment as necessary to achieve our goals? Is there a moral, ethical, or religious obligation to be good stewards of the biosphere?, etc. This brief reflection should be completed by the beginning of class tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(143, 'Today, students got an opportunity to show off how much they knew about community ecology.  Woo hoo!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(144, '<br />At the beginning of class, students had an opportunity to ask questions about the 21 motion graphs we discussed during class yesterday. After reviewing those graphs, students sketched motion graphs using written descriptions of how those objects were moving. Students also discussed their sketches with a partner and, if necessary, revised their sketches based on those conversations. The assignment (Worksheet: Conceptual Motion Graphs) is posted in shared content.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(145, 'It is important that you check our ClassConnect site every day for schedule changes, notices, and to stay on top of deadlines for your QUIA quizzes. Please use the &quot;forums&quot; section to leave me suggestions for class and to socialize with each other. This wall is reserved for class related Q and A. Thanks! ;-)', 89, 1, 240, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(146, 'New QUIA policy: Homework quizzes will all only allow you 3 tries before your final grade is recorded. Quizzes will be open for 3-4 days, so be sure to check the calendar for deadlines as these cannot be extended. Study Guides give you unlimted tries, and you are expected to retake them until you score 85% or better.', 89, 1, 243, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(147, 'FREE Chemistry Tutoring Available: Every morning at 7:00 in Room 320 with Mr. Brown and rotating lunch hours in the Academic Center (Room 117) with Mr. Olandese. I am in Room 324 for power review and practice M, W, Th mornings from 7:00 and after school W by appointment.', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(148, 'It is important that you check our ClassConnect site every day for schedule changes, notices, and to stay on top of deadlines for your QUIA quizzes. Please use the &quot;forums&quot; section to leave me suggestions for class and to socialize with each other. This wall is reserved for class related Q and A. Thanks! ;-)', 89, 1, 243, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(149, 'QUIA secret words never change! Study Guides are always &quot;study,&quot; quizzes are always &quot;quiz.&quot;', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(150, 'Kern! i turned in part of my evidence to the student save in folder  under physics, let me know you got', 1338, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(151, 'Tim, \r<br />I found the interactive Excel worksheet we worked on during class and assume you worked on this again outside of class to review the units of measurement. Should I be looking for anything else on the P drive (e.g. vocab, practice w/ s-t graphs)? \r<br />Thanks.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(152, 'For the warm-up quetions, students (1) predicted the grade they earned on last Friday''s test and (2) had an opportunity to ask questions about the scoring chart I used to determine the score they earned on the test.  We discussed answers to the test, comparing them to &quot;model&quot; answers, and I did my best to clarify any common misunderstandings or omissions.\r<br />\r<br />After discussing the test, we listed to the song &quot;Dodo&quot; by Dave Matthews and students recorded their &quot;wanderings and wonderings&quot; about the lyrics and any connections they recognized between the song and what we are currently learning.  We finished the period by discussing how to synthesize information using a concept map and began watching the film &quot;The End of the Line&quot;.  Students will need to turn in a concept map with all of the words in the Wordle after watching the movie to demonstrate their understanding of learning objectives G5.4 - G.5.6.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(153, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What questions do you have about tomorrow''s test re-take?&quot; Students who did not turn in evidence of studying for the test today, that is, evidence of doing something outside of class to prepare for the retake (in addition to what you have already did to prepare for the first test), are not eligible to take the test retake and will need to complete an out-of-class project to demonstrate a deeper understanding of interpreting and analyzing position-time graphs. \r<br />\r<br />After discussing student questions to the warm up, students matched the definition, picture, equation and examples to the motion vocabulary terms using a vocab word card template. After correctly matching each piece, students practiced analyzing and interpreting position-time graphs. \r<br />\r<br />Note: I am much more interested and impressed by your efforts than your excuses. If you did not turn in evidence of studying the vocabulary terms and position-time graphs, I assume that something else in your life had a higher priority. That is your choice and is fine with me, but since your physics grade is not a priority you will not have the opportunity to earn a higher grade in this class by retaking the test. While you may be upset, please remember that I reminded you everyday since returning your test about the evidence required for a retake, had warm-up questions about the evidence, posted the information about the evidence on this website, provided examples of evidence in the postings and shared content, and recorded the due date for the evidence on the calendar.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(154, 'We began the period by discussing the following question: &quot;How might someone determine what is a priority in your life?  How would they know what''s important to you without having to ask you?&quot;  After discussing this, students who were eligible (those who either missed the first test OR students who took the first test and submitted evidence of studying) took the retake test on the vocabulary of motion and interpreting and analyzing position-time graphs.  Students who did not take hte test went to physicslab.org and took notes and practiced answering questions about velocity-time graphs (physicslab.org, table of contents, kinematics: graphs, B. constant velocity: velocity-time graphs).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(155, 'Today, students continued watching the film &quot;The End of the Line&quot; and adding information to their concept map, which is due Fri. (10/15/10).  The concept map will be used to assess student understanding of learning objectives G.5.4 - G.5.6 and, consequently, will be recorded as a summative grade.   \r<br />\r<br />Note: A new assignment (Primary Productivity) was posted in shared content.  This assignment is due next Mon. (10/18/10) and requires you to use the CD that came with your textbook.  Responses to the questions should be emailed to me by the beginning of class on that Mon.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(156, 'I just posted a video in shared content entitled &quot;Graphs of Motion&quot;.  If you are struggling to understand position-time and velocity-time graphs or would like to review these graphs, you may benefit from watching this 5 min. video.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(157, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;How do you know an object is at rest in a position-time graph?  Velocity-time graph?  Acceleration-time graph?&quot;  We discussed the answer to these questions as we reviewed what the graphs that students sketched last Friday (If you remember, you were given six different scenarios of moving objects and were asked to sketch the position-, velocity- and acceleration-time graphs for each scenario).  Creating motion graphs from descriptions of moving objects is skill you should be able to do for the next test.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(158, 'During class today, we finished watching the film &quot;The End of the Line&quot;.  Students will have an opportunity tomorrow to finish their concepts maps that synthesize what they learned (from watching the movie) about techniques for estimating commercial fish stocks, the concept of maximum sustainable yield, and strategies promoting the conservation of fish.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(159, 'Yesterday (Thursday, 10/14/10), students had a substitute teacher.  Students received some fisheries fact sheets from Australia and used this information, along with what they learned while watching &quot;The End of the Line&quot;, to work on their concept maps.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(160, 'Yesterday (Thursday, 10/14/10), students had a substitute teacher and watched an episode of &quot;The Universe&quot; and were asked to write responses to 4 questions/prompts, including what the video had to do with what we are currently learning.  The responses were due at the end of the period.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(161, 'At the beginning of the period, I asked students to describe something they learned from yesterday''s video that has to do with what we are currently learning.  During the rest of the period, we used clickers to respond to questions about motion graphs and discussed, as a class, the correct responses to those questions.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy homecoming this weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(162, 'Today, we explored the interactions between biotic and abiotic parts of the environment by playing a succession-themed board game.  Before the period ended, students turned in sketches of the two communities they created while playing the game and their responses to three questions that asked them to reflect on the game itself.  Students also received the text (&quot;Prehistoric Zoo&quot;, from the book &quot;The DNA Detectives&quot;) and discussion questions for next Friday''s chinwag.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy homecoming weekend!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(163, 'Yesterday (10/18/10), students had a substitute teacher and watched &quot;Cosmic Phenomena&quot;, which is an episode of The History Channel''s program &quot;The Universe&quot;.  Before leaving class, students were asked to turn in a 3-2-1 assignment based on the video (3 = 3 things that really interested me, 2 = 2 things I''d like to learn more about, and 1 = big idea from the video).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(164, 'Yesterday (10/18/10), students had a substitute teacher and watched the &quot;Jungle&quot; episode of &quot;Planet Earth&quot;.  As students watched the video, they were asked to record ethical, ecological, economic, and aesthetic reasons for conserving biodiversity within rainforests.  Students turned this assignment into the sub before leaving class.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(165, 'Today, students practiced analyzing and interpreting velocity-time graphs by responding to questions on dry-erase boards.  The next test is planned for Tues. (10/25/10).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(166, 'The warm-up question today was to complete the following analogy by finding an appropriate word for the blank AND describing the relationship between the words: Speed is to velocity as distance is to _____ because...  Students will need to complete similar analogies for their upcoming test.  We then listened to a song and watched a video about speed and velocity by They Might Be Giants.  I posted a link to this video in shared content.  The rest of the period was spent practicing analyzing and interpreting velocity-time graphs by responding to questions on a worksheet printed from the website Physics Lab Online (http://dev.physicslab.org/Document.aspx?doctype=5&amp;filename=Kinematics_ConstantVelocityVelocityTimeGraphs1.xml).  Whatever problems students did not complete during class was assigned as homework.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(167, 'During class today, students continued working with their partners on creating an in situ and an ex situ conservation plan for an endangered species.  Students also voted unanimously to move the test on Topic G2 to Friday and move the chinwag on the &quot;Prehistoric Zoo&quot; text to tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(168, 'We began the period by discussing the difference between observations, claims and evidence, which are listed as separate sections on the science writing heuristic (SWH) (Note: the SWH is a note catcher that students are completing as they are conducting their lab).  Students then designed and conducted a lab to determine how mass affects the acceleration of an object moving down a ramp.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(169, 'Today we discussed the chapter &quot;Prehistoric Zoo&quot; from the book &quot;The DNA Detectives&quot;. Many interesting opinions were expressed and, in some cases, some very offensive statements were made--although, the people who made those statements clarified they were simply playing devil''s advocate and didn''t necessarily believe such ideas. From what I have heard in the last two discussions, I sincerely hope that paradigm shifts about our role within and responsibility to the environment occur for some people before May.  I hate to imagine the future if those paradigms and worldviews are not shifted. \r<br />\r<br />Note: The next chingwag will have a slightly different look. I have provided questions for you about the reading up until now. Next time, a student will be randomly chosen to lead our discussion. That student must have prepared questions, based on the text and its relation to the learning objectives in the syllabus, to lead the discussion and promote conversation. Thus, this individual will need to prepare ahead of time and not be able to simply respond to other people''s opinions about the reading.  I played that game a couple of times in school and, although I was never &quot;busted&quot;, understand it wasn''t a very effective approach for learning.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(170, 'Today''s warm-up was to complete the following analogy by finding an appropriate word for the blank AND describing the relationship between the words: meters/second is to velocity as _____ is to acceleration because... This is the second warm-up question in a row asking you to complete an analogy so that you become comfortable answering these types of questions before the test. \r<br />\r<br />After discussing responses to the warm-up question, students were given a homework assignment. The assignment was to record 15 - 20 measurements of speed (using a speedometer) during a trip in a car or bus. Additionally, students were asked to record the total distance traveled during the same trip (using the odometer). The 15-20 speed measurements and the measurement of the total distance traveled during the trip are due at the beginning of the period on Mon. (10/25/10), when we will analyze the data.\r<br />\r<br />After answering questions about the assignment, students were asked &quot;Which would accelerate faster down a hill, a semi-truck, a car or a motorcycle?&quot; Students were then asked to design and conduct an experiment to test their question/prediction. Students wrote their testable question in the first row of their science writing heuristic (SWH). The question must have included the word &quot;acceleration&quot; and should have begun with the word &quot;what&quot; or &quot;how&quot;. Students then designed an experiment and described their experiment in the second row of their SWH. In this row, students also drew their predictions for the position-time, velocity-time and acceleration-time graph for the objects they were testing. Students began conducting their experiment in groups and will be given time to finish their experiments during class tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(171, 'Today, students got an opportunity to show off how much they know about ecosystem ecology and biomes by taking a test. Oh yeah!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(172, 'It is important that you check our ClassConnect site every day for schedule changes, notices, and to stay on top of deadlines for your QUIA quizzes. Please use the &quot;forums&quot; section to leave Ms. Wedam suggestions for class and to socialize with each other. This wall is reserved for class related Q and A. Thanks! ;-)', 89, 1, 239, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(173, 'It is important that you check our ClassConnect site every day for schedule changes, notices, and to stay on top of deadlines for your QUIA quizzes. Please use the &quot;forums&quot; section to leave Ms. Wedam suggestions for class and to socialize with each other. This wall is reserved for class related Q and A. Thanks! ;-)', 89, 1, 238, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(174, 'New QUIA policy: Homework quizzes will all only allow you 3 tries before your final grade is recorded. Quizzes will be open for 3-4 days, so be sure to check the calendar for deadlines as these cannot be extended. Study Guides give you unlimted tries, and you are expected to retake them until you score 85% or better.', 89, 1, 240, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(175, 'New QUIA policy: Homework quizzes will all only allow you 3 tries before your final grade is recorded. Quizzes will be open for 3-4 days, so be sure to check the calendar for deadlines as these cannot be extended. Study Guides give you unlimted tries, and you are expected to retake them until you score 85% or better.', 89, 1, 241, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(176, 'Hey kids - Your schedule is now posted for the REST OF THE SEMESTER!!! Yes, now you know the dates of all the major quizzes and tests and you know the daily homework schedule. We will continue to do QUIA quizzes and short in-class quizzes that I will announce in class as they come up. Enjoy, and be sure to log onto ClassConnect every day  to check assignments and find extra tutorials.', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(177, 'Hey kids - Your schedule is now posted for the REST OF THE SEMESTER!!! Yes, now you know the dates of all the major quizzes and tests and you know the daily homework schedule. We will continue to do QUIA quizzes and short in-class quizzes that I will announce in class as they come up. Enjoy, and be sure to log onto ClassConnect every day  to check assignments and find extra tutorials.', 89, 1, 313, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(178, 'Today, we completed parts 3 - 7 of the science writing heuristic (SWH).  Students used data I collected from an experiment, which is also stored as a Word document in Shared Content (mass and acceleration data).  Students wrote what they observed from the graph (section 3 of the SWH), made their claim about how mass affects acceleration (section 4), used the data in the graphs to support their claim (section 5), read a website (www.physicsclassroom.com/Class/1DKin/U1L5e.cfm) to record what scientists currently understand about the relationship between mass and acceleration (section 6), and reflected on how their ideas about the question have changed since beginning the experiment.  \r<br />\r<br />After turning in their completed SWH, students constructed a speed-time graph of the data they collected for homework.  Students who forgot to turn in their homework graphed the speed data stored in an Excel file, which is also posted this file in Shared Content.  We will work on analyzing the graph more tomorrow tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(179, 'Today, we used a citizen monitoring chart (posted in Shared Content as &quot;Biotic Index Chart&quot; and a virtual stream diversity simulation (virtualbiologylab.org/StreamDiversity.htm) to understand how ecologists use indicator species and biotic indices to assess the health of the environment.  After collecting data and calculating indices for streams with no pollution, streams with moderate pollution AND streams with severe pollution, students wrote a brief summary explaining how biotic indices and indicator species are used in monitoring environmental change.  This summary should have included specific data collected from the simulation to assist in the explanation.\r<br />\r<br />Note: Students also received their concept maps back from &quot;The End of the Line&quot; documentary. This was graded as a summative assessment for Topic G5 and may be revised and resubmitted for regrading.  Students should use the feedback on the rubric and the exemplars posted in the classroom to improve their maps.  If you would like additional feedback about your concept map, you can meet with me at a prearranged time outside of class.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(180, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What is your plan to prepare for the test on velocity- and acceleration-time graphs?&quot; We will take this test on Friday (10/29/10). \r<br />\r<br />After students wrote their responses, we discussed the alternative assessment for demonstrating understanding of position-time graphs. This is posted in shared content and any student who would like to replace the grade they earned on the position-time graph test or retake may complete the project for a replacement grade. This project is due no later than Dec. 10th. \r<br />\r<br />Students then practiced predicting the position-, velocity- and acceleration-time graphs for objects using written descriptions of those objects'' movements. After sketching predictions for the red and black car, we then watched animations of those cars and compared the predictions to the actual motion graphs. This activity can be found in shared content by clicking on the &quot;Motion Graph Predict and Observe&quot; link. \r<br />\r<br />We used the rest of the time to either work on constructing and analyzing speed-time graph for data obtained from a car trip (period 1) or completing a table that compared the three types of motion graphs we''ve been learning about in class (periods 4 and 8). This graphic organizer is also posted in shared content (Table Comparing Motion Graphs).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(181, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What questions do you have about the &quot;in situ vs. ex situ?&quot; project?  After answering some questions (e.g. Is a bibliography necessary?  Do we need to turn anything in on Nov. 1st?), we discussed the role of feedback and the type of feedback I am willing to give you to improve your assessments.  Just to reiterate, I have been providing rubrics, exemplars, verbal comments and some written comments (often as guiding questions).  I also offered to meet with students outside of class if they desired more feedback.  I am willing to offer help and guidance, but will not provide a formulaic procedure of how to earn an A in this class.  I want you to think, self-evaluate and compare your work to the exemplars.  Your grade is also not about seat time or the amount of work completed.  Your grade, at least 95% of it, is based on your ability to demonstrate your understanding of the learning objectives.  The concept map was an assessment and, much like an essay on a test, I will not tell you exactly what you need to write to earn full credit.  Otherwise, you map represents knowledge you''re regurgitating and not knowledge you are applying and synthesizing.  If you have clarifying questions or concerns, please let me know on an individual basis outside of class so we can converse.  I digress.\r<br />\r<br />Most, and I emphasize &quot;most&quot;, students used the remaining time in class to be productive and either read the Ozzy Ozone comic (posted in shared content) and add information from the comic to their notes on ozone depletion and/or work with their partner on the ex situ vs. in situ project.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(182, 'During class today, students practiced analyzing and interpreting velocity-time graphs by responding to questions on a dry-erase board.  We also discussed solutions to those problems as a class.  We will review again tomorrow for Friday''s test.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(183, 'During class today, we discussed the meaning of &quot;biodiversity&quot; and methods for quantifying the biodiversity of communities.  This included comparing between species richness and evenness and talking about how to both calculate and interpret Simpson''s Diversity Index.  I highlighted that the equation in the IB syllabus is actually the reciprocal of this index, which is calculated and interpreted much differently.  At the end of class, students began collecting data from two communities of pipe cleaners to calculate Simpson''s Diversity Index for those two communities.  We will finish and discuss the results of this exercise tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(184, 'We began class by discussing the &quot;muddiest points&quot; about understanding motion graphs (i.e. what students are still struggling to understand about position-, velocity- and acceleration-time graphs).  After discussing students'' questions, students had the 3 following options:\r<br />\r<br />Option 1: Continue completing the 3-column table comparing position-, velocity- and acceleration-time graphs.\r<br />\r<br />Option 2: Practice analyzing and interpret motion graphs by reading, taking notes, writing summaries and/or responding to example questions using the internet (physicslab.org or physicsclassroom.com)\r<br />\r<br />Option 3: Discuss questions and strategies for solving problems with me in a small group (max. of 6 students) for 15-20 min.\r<br />\r<br />Hopefully, students will continue studying tonight in preparation for the test tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(185, 'where is the stuff to help study for acceleration/velocity-time graphs??', 2103, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(186, 'During the first 15 min. of class, students completed their Simpson''s Diversity Index calculations and then interpreted and analyzed the values they calculated.  Students also wrote a brief paragraph that compared the biodiversity of the two communities they sampled to show they could accurately describe the meaning of the index.  We then discussed the scores students earned on the last test (G2) and the &quot;correct&quot; responses to the exam questions.  During the last 15 min. of class, students were given some resources for their next lab experiment, which will investigate the diversity of mold.  Students were randomly assigned to groups of 4-5 and will have an opportunity to design their experiment and/or work on their &quot;in situ vs. ex situ&quot; project during class tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(187, 'All resources for studying (e.g. links to websites, videos, worksheets, etc.) are stored in Shared Content (look to the right).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(188, 'Today, students demonstrated their ability to analyze and interpret motion graphs by taking a test.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(189, 'Today, students either (1) worked in groups to designing an experiment that investigates the diversity of mold or (2) worked in pairs on designing an &quot;in situ&quot; and &quot;ex situ&quot; conservation plan for an endangered species.  The conservation plans are due Mon.  The experimental design diagrams are due Tues.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(190, 'Scouring the internet I found a website for a company that specializes in mold.  If you go to  www.environex.com, click on the &quot;What is IAQ?&quot; tab, it discusses indoor air quality and, on the left, includes a link to a mold library that provides information, including pictures, about common indoor molds (many of which are on your id key).  This may help you with your experiment.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(191, 'The warm-up question today asked &quot;What is the scientific explanation for the formation of the universe?  What evidence supports this explanation?&quot;  After briefly discussing responses, students drew a 3-column table with the following headings: Scientific Explanation, Direct Evidence and Indirect Evidence.  I explained how to complete the table and we discussed the difference between direct and indirect evidence.  We then watched &quot;Beyond the Big Bang&quot;, an episode of The History Channel''s series &quot;The Universe&quot;, to understand how the scientific understanding of the origin of the universe has changed over time due to the invention of new technologies and consequent discovery of new evidence.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(192, 'Today''s warm-up question asked &quot;How has your understanding of in situ and ex situ conservation strategies changed since beginning the project 3 weeks ago?&quot;  We didn''t discuss responses to this question, but I did ask some students this question after they presented their project to the class.  We may finish presentations tomorrow after a peer review of the experimental designs for the diversity of mold lab.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(193, 'Reminder Test Make Ups:\r<br />Test make-ups will be held today before school, during period 5, period 6 or after school.  Test make-ups will also be held tomorrow before school or during periods 5 or 6.  Anyone who doesn''t make up the test due to an absence on Fri. will have an opportunity to take the retake.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(194, 'Today, we finished watching &quot;Beyond the Big Bang&quot; and completing the 3-column table explaining the Big Bang theory and both the direct and indirect evidence for this theory.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(195, 'During the first 40 minutes of class, we used a rubric and &quot;canned&quot; questions to evaluate and provide feedback to groups on their experimental design diagrams for the mold diversity investigation.  Groups should use this feedback to improve upon the design of their experiment.  During the last 10 minutes, we listened to a presentation regarding the in situ and ex situ conservation strategies for conserving the grey wolf.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your day off tomorrow!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(196, 'No school for you.  Enjoy your day and see you tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(197, 'No class today (Juniors had pre-ACT and Seniors had the day off).  Enjoy your afternoon and see you tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(198, 'Today''s warm up was as follows: What are 3 things that you are thankful for?  Some of you thought this was a completely random and irrelevant question, but I know that I find it valuable to periodically ask myself this question (especially just before you embark on the G4 project).  We didn''t discuss responses to the warm-up question, although I am interested in your responses, but instead moved on to talking about the purpose of, topic, expectations, and groups for the G4 project.  Mrs. Robertson and I heard some good conversations during the period and were encouraged by some of the ideas you generated.  Please pay special attention to the deadlines (posted on the calendar) and try to avoid procrastination, as this can make a decisive factor in you having either a positive or negative experience.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(199, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: &quot;Predict the score you earned on the test.  Name one thing you could do to possiblly improve the score you earned on this test.&quot;  As students were writing their responses to this questions, I distributed the tests.  We then spent most of the period discussing the correct responses to test questions as a class to understand how to improve.  Before leaving, we briefly discussed the Big Bang theory and students completed a formative assessment to show what they currently understand about scientific theories.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(200, 'If anyone is interested in tutoring an IB junior biology student, please let me know ASAP. This may be a good opportunity to review for the exam in May.  Not only will you have someone to hold you accountable for studying/reviewing last year''s material, you''ll be able to earn some extra money for something you will need to do anyways.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(201, 'Today, as usual, we began class by discussing the warm-up question &quot;What is a scientific law?  How are laws similar to and different than scientific theories?&quot;  We listed and discussed student preconceptions (what the students thought they knew) as a class and then compared scientific hypotheses, theories and laws using a graphic organizer and the website Understanding Science (undsci.berkeley.edu/).  After 20 min., students turned in their graphic organizers and shared what they learned from their reading and how their initial ideas changed.  We then discussed Newton''s 1st law of motion and the next learning opportunity to learn more about this law (design a 60 sec &quot;Minute to Win It&quot; challenge that illustrates the concept of inertia).  Students will continue researching and designing their challenge during class on Mon. so that they can turn in a description of their challenge and how inertia applies before they leave class.  We''ll plan on doing the challenges Tues.  \r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(202, 'We began the period by discussing any lingering questions people had regarding the G4 project (e.g. Will any future class time be dedicated to working on this project?  Ans. NO).  We then reflected on the effectiveness of each class activity for learning the content from last unit.  Students also communicated their understanding of vocabulary from the upcoming unit by completing a Science Terminology Inventory Probe.  I handed out the notes and Biozone learning opportunities for the next unit on homeostasis (due the Tues. before Thanksgiving break) and students read a comic book (&quot;The Science of Life&quot;) and answered some questions to gain a better understanding of physiology.  I posted the comic book in Shared Content.  The questions should be completed by Mon.  Our test on Topic G.3 (Human impacts on ecosystems) is scheduled for Tues.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(203, 'Today''s warm-up was to answer several multiple choice questions about digestion.  We then played a board game to learn more about the structure and function of the digestive system.  Tomorrow is a work day so bring your Biozone workbook and notes.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(204, 'New QUIA quiz policy: All quizzes will now allow you unlimited tries so even if your computer locks up or you accidentally hit submit early you still have plenty of tries to work that out. Because of the extra number of tries, we will not be able to extend deadlines. so please keep checking daily assignments to make sure you''re keeping up with all due dates!', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(205, 'New QUIA quiz policy: All quizzes will now allow you 10 tries so even if your computer locks up or you accidentally hit submit early you still have plenty of tries to work that out. Because of the extra number of tries, we will not be able to extend deadlines. so please keep checking daily assignments to make sure you''re keeping up with all due dates!', 89, 1, 313, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(206, 'We began the period today by discussing concerns about G4.  After this, students had the a &quot;work period&quot; with the option of either writing notes for Topic 6.1, completing their Biozone assignment or working on their G4 project.  I must say that the new G4 directions/experiments that I have been hearing about are a drastic improvement over what was initially contrived.  Good work on that aspect. \r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(207, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: You and your dog are riding in the car when you slam on the brakes.  Rover, who was in the back seat, is now in the front seat licking your face.  Why?\r<br />\r<br />After discussing the answer to the question, we discussed the assignment students were given last Fri., to design a 60 sec. &quot;Minute to Win It&quot; challenge that illustrates the concept of inertia.  Students used the remaining class time to research the gameshow, ideas for challenges, and to type a description their their challenge that included...\r<br />1) a list of required supplies for challenge,\r<br />2) the game blueprint (description of/directions for challenge), and\r<br />3) a description of how inertia is illustrated in the challenge.\r<br />We will perform the challenges tomorrow during class.\r<br />\r<br />If students finished this assignment, they could go to physicsclassroom.com (Physics Tutorial, Newton''s Laws, Lesson 1 a thru d), read the information on these tutorial, watch the animations, respond to the questions, and take notes (incl. writing a brief summary) to better understand Newton''s 1st law of motion.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(208, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: Compare behavioral and physiological strategies for maintaining homeostasis.  We discussed appropriate responses to this question as a class, using distance running as a situation.  The framework for the next topic was then introduced by discussing the big ideas and essential questions for the homesotasis unit.  Incidentally, these are remarkably similar to big ideas and essential questions from the previous unit.  Students also recorded the essential vocabulary for the unit and the word roots, prefixes and suffixes that would be beneficial to learn.  We then watched a brief video introducing the human body systems and their functions for maintaining homeostasis.  This was followed by students using a computer simulation in which they comandeered a virtual body to understand the role of physiological responses in maintaining homeostasis and how responses are often interconnected and interdependent.  With about 10 min. of class reminaing, students received an article about homeostasis in which all the figures  from the article had been deleted.  The goal of hte assignment was for students to create their own illustrations based on the clues in the text.  These pictures (and their captions) are due Weds.  \r<br />\r<br />P.S. Test on Option G3 tomorrow!\r<br />P.S.S. We will continue our biodiversity of mold lab when the agar arrives.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(209, 'Today, we played the inertia version of &quot;Minute to Win it&quot;.  Students set up the 60 second inertia challenges they designed and contestants competed to earn a prize.  We also described each challenge, identified the object(s) that were showing inertia in each challenge and evaluated each challenge based on its creativity and illustration of inertia.  We will probably finish the challenges tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08');
INSERT INTO `class_wall` (`comment_id`, `body`, `userID`, `level`, `classID`, `schoolID`, `date_posted`) VALUES
(210, 'Today, students had an opportunity to show off everything they knew and understood about Topic G3 (the impacts of humans on ecosystems).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(211, 'Today, students were asked &quot;How could you cure (not just treat) diabetes?&quot;  for their warm up.  We discussed a couple of suggestions and then watched a video from &quot;Secrets of the Sequence&quot; that showed a potential cure for this disease.  We clarified some terminology from the video (e.g. pancreatic islets) and then summarized the method described in the video.  Next, we looked at a couple of drawings created by elementary school children from Taiwan who have diabetes and talked about how these pictures represent a different way of understanding (knowing) diabetes than the scientific understanding we''ve gained during class.  Since we''ve been learning about blood sugar regulation and thermoregulation for maintaining homeostasis, we then began talking about osmoregulation.  To gain an appreciation for the organ that performs osmoregulation and to begin learning about its structure, we broke up into pairs and dissected a sheep''s kidney.  Before leaving class, students should have picked up a copy of a kidney article and reading guide that should be completed by Fri.  We''ll have an opportunity to either work on the reading guide during class tomorrow or completing the guide as homework and condinuing the mold biodiversity lab during tomorrow''s class.  Note: This lab is due no later than Dec. 13th.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(212, 'When students came to class today, they saw a picture of how the experiment we discused yesterday could be set up and then answered the following question for their warm-up: &quot;What question(s) do you have about the experimental materials/equipment?&quot;  (pulley, cart, masses, etc.)  I clarified any questions students had about the experiment, re-explained the purpose of conducting the experiment, and handed back the experimental designs created by students the previous day.  Students then worked in their groups to set up and, in some cases, began collecting data.  This lab should be rather challenging, as students are actually involved in doing science (designing and conducting their own lab) as opposed to following a set of instructions where everything is flawless.  We''ll continue working on this lab tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(213, 'Remember, if you''re absent it is your responsibility to read/learn what we did in class. I am posting video tutorials of how to solve problems, so please check those out first, then go see Mr. Brown or Mr. Olandese for help if you are confused. You can''t afford to fall behind at this point in the year! Answer keys for the homework problems are also posted online.', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(214, 'For today''s warm up, students identified systems from a list and then wrote their own definition for a &quot;system&quot;.  We will discuss the concept of systems more on Fri.  Students then either worked on comparing negative and positive feedback loops using articles and a graphic organizer or completed the test they started yesterday.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great Veteran''s Day.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(215, 'The warm up today was to complete the following simile: &quot;Inertia is like _____ because...&quot;  We watched an old &quot;Eureka&quot; animation that explained inertia and provided a possible response to the warm-up question.  We also discussed how mass is a measure of an object''s inertia.  Periods 1 and 4 then continued the &quot;Minute to Win It&quot; inertia challenges, while students in period 8 were given several other options to pursue, as the majority of the class was absent due to the social tensions project.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy Veteran''s Day.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(216, 'Today''s warm up was to copy down this unit''s word root table on a separate sheet of paper.  Students should complete and submit this table as part of their portfolio before the next test.  I will also assess your knowledge of  these prefixes and suffixes in part 1 of the next exam.  Students then used the rest of the period to take 2-column notes (What I read/What it reminds me of) from the Vision Learning website (visionlearning.com; general science - energy) and write a brief (2 sentence) summary of what they learned (due at the end of class) and to complete the information source sheets for the debate on Mon.  I will check at the beginning of the period on Mon. to see if these have been completed.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(217, 'New Hours for Help: Because Mr. Brown offers chemistry tutoring from 7:00-7:30 every morning, I am changing my hours to after school on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 3:15 to 4:00. Please remember Mr. Olandese also offers tutoring during lunch hours in the Academic Center. :-)', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(218, 'New Hours for Help: For scheduling reasons I am changing my hours for help to after school on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 3:15 to 4:00. Please remember Mr. Olandese also offers science tutoring during lunch hours in the Academic Center. :-)', 89, 1, 313, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(219, 'We began the period by discussing how we can measure inertia.  Students then completed a vocab word card for &quot;inertia&quot; and wrote their own notes and summaries for Newton''s 1st law using the Physics Classroom website (physicsclassroom.com) and the sample notes and rubrics on the public (P) drive.  The vocab card and notes were turned in at the end of class.  If students finished early, they used the time to study for the velocity- and acceleration-time graph test re-take.  Most students chose to study by reading the tutorials and practicing answering the questions using the interactive worksheets at Online Physics Lab (physicslab.org).  Evidence of studying for the test retake is due Mon. \r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(220, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What did you learn about ''systems'' during the last unit on Ecology &amp; Conservation Biology&quot;?  After several students shared their responses, we discussed last Weds. formative assessment on systems, the definition of a &quot;system&quot; and how to analyze homeostasis using a systems approach.  We then discussed the 3 components of a homeostatic mechanism and compared both positive and negative feedback feedback loops.  Students began working on part 1 of a case study and will continue working on the case study during class on Mon.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(221, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What''s the difference between ''friction'' and ''gravity''?&quot;  After reading some responses and having students share responses, we used the computers to read, watch and listen to animations and simulations compare these two forces and the effects they both have on moving objects.  Tables 1, 2 and 3, where students recorded what they learned fom the activity, were turned in as evidence of learning and productivity at the end of class.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(222, 'Students began the period by predicting the scores they earned on the 1) in situ vs. ex situ project and 2) the test on G3.  I handed back the projects and tests and then we discussed the test questions and model answers to those questions in order to identify errors made on the test and to understand how to improve future scores.  After this, students used the netbooks to continue working on their case study regarding (human) thermoregulation.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(223, 'Students who either did not take the first test on velocity- and acceleration-time graphs OR who turned in evidence of studying took the re-take test during class today.  Those students who didn not take the test began working on a lab that investigated the factors affecting static friction.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(224, 'We began class today by discussing mechanisms of heat exchange between organisms and their environment.  Students then continued working on their case studies.\r<br />\r<br />Note: Tomorrow and Thursday we will set up and conduct the lab in which you investigate the biodiversity of mold.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(225, 'We spent our short period preparing agar plates for the biodiversity of mold investigation.  Some students were also shown how to operate the incubator in the store room.  You will have time tomorrow to collect data for your experiment, but should bring your notes and Biozone book to class just in case you do have some down time.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(226, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;How can understanding friction and/or learning how to collect and analyze information (like we do during labs) benefit you?&quot;  After discussing some connections students made between class and their own lives, I re-explained the purpose of the lab, the concept of friction and the 3 separate questions the lab investigates (Does surface area affect static friction?  Does the surface an object is on affect static friction?  Does the mass of an object affect static friction?).  Students then continued working on the static friction lab they started yesterday.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(227, 'Today''s warm-up question was 1) Take out your (completed) energy source info sheets.  2)  &quot;What is one fact that surprised you the MOST?  Why did you find that fact surprising?&quot;  We didn''t discuss responses to the warm-up, but did use the rest of the period to debate which energy source is the best.  If you were not in class, then you can earn the points by completing the info sheets and writing a reflection on the following questions:\r<br />\r<br />1) Why isn''t there an obvious winner in this game?\r<br />\r<br />2) Even if the game continued, would there be a winner?  Why or why not?\r<br />\r<br />3) Why do we use energy sources that have negative impacts on the environment?\r<br />\r<br />4) What are some other factors that we need to consider in our choice of energy sources?', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(228, 'Hey Kern hope you had a great break and good weekend :D', 1339, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(229, 'Congratulations! Your class average on the Chemical Reactions test were OUTSTANDING! 6th hour = 81%, 7th hour = 91%, 8th hour = 82%. To reward your hard work I have re-opened ALL the old QUIA quizzes and study guides until Friday, December 3rd so you can redeem those missed points without relying on your classmates to take all the current QUIA quizzes on time. Just think of how awesome your grade will look once those &quot;0''s disappear! :-)', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(230, 'Yesterday (Nov. 18, 2010), students had a substitute teacher and watched an episode of MythBusters (&quot;Tablecloth Chaos&quot;), which discussed the concepts of inertia and friction.  After viewing the video, students responded to the following 3-2-1 writing prompt:\r<br />3 = Describe 3 things you learned from watching this video.\r<br />2 = What are 2 myths that would be interesting to investigate? \r<br />1 = What question do you have about the episode you just watched?\r<br />Students turned in their completed 3-2-1 responses at the end of class.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(231, 'Today, students began by writing a response to the following warm-up question: What is one thing you learned about physics yesterday (from watching the video?  If you weren''t here yesterday, than what is one thing you learned this week?\r<br />\r<br />After discussing some responses to the warm-up question, I recapped what we have learned since beginning the unit and then began discussing force- (free-)body diagrams (FBD).  We discussed what a FBD is, why it is called an FBD, how to draw FBDs and how to determine/calculate net force using an FBD.  We drew two FBDs as a class from written descriptions of objects, and then students worked on drawing the next 10 FBDs with a partner.  If the FBDs were not completed by the end of class, they were assigned as homework to be turned in at the beginning of class on Mon.\r<br />\r<br />Note: This assignment is also posted in Shared Content.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(232, 'Yesterday, students had a substitute teacher and worked on collecting data for their mold diversity experiments.  Any &quot;down time&quot; was used to work on taking notes &amp; writing summaries for Topic 6.5 or completing the Biozone assignment.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(233, 'We began class today by responding to questions that required students to analyze data about thermoregulation in the form of tables and graphs.  We followed this with completing a graphic organizer by separating actions based on their ability to either increase or decrease our internal body temperature.  We briefly talked about how the endocrine system is involved in thermoregulation and watched a video to better understand the structure and function of the endocrine system as well as the role hormones play in our bodies.  Next, we watched an animation to understand how the endocrine system interacts with organs from other systems to maintain stable levels of blood sugar.  We also completed a graphic organizer to illustrate the process of controlling blood sugar and used a word  bank to finish a closed-paragraph that summarized this process.  Whew!  We were busy today.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(234, 'Yesterday (11/22/10), students had a substitute teacher.  Students reviewed how to construct force-body diagrams (FBDs) by watching an animation (You can watch this animation at http://www.wisc-online.com/Objects/ViewObject.aspx?ID=tp1502 ).  Next, students reviewed the correct responess to the FBD practice problems they worked on Friday during class.  The rest of the period was spent completing a worksheet about FBDs and friction.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(235, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What is the ''normal'' force?&quot;  After discussing the normal force (including how &quot;normal&quot; means perpendicular to the surface an object is in contact with), we watched a BrainPop animation about forces and took an informal quiz about the concepts discussed within the animation.  Next, we reviewed the correct responses to the FBD practice problems students worked on last Fri. (From the feedback I received from students, the sub didn''t review the answers thoroughly or at all, in the case of one class).  Students then used the remaining time in class to complete the practice problems on the FBD and friction worksheet that they received yesterday.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great Thanksgiving break!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(236, 'Yesterday (11/22/10), students had a substitute teacher.  Students warmed up by analyzing a series of stacked graphs to determine how the duration of exercise affects blood glucose concentration.  The substitute teacher was suppose to share a model response with students, but I''m not sure this happened.  Next, students reviewed an MSDS sheet for the lactophenol cotton blue stain we can use to stain fungi and a procedure for using the stain to examine the fungi that are collected.  Students then worked in groups to conduct their experiment.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(237, 'Today, all senior IB science students (Biology and Chemistry) met in 403 to participate in a gallery walk where G4 teams evaluated the experimental designs of at least 3 other groups using a rubric and a list of question stems.  Mrs. Robertson and I heard very good discussions during the rotations and hope those discussions and the constructive feedback each team received from their peers are translated into improved G4 projects.  As a side note, students also received a text for our chinwag next Thurs.  A person will be chosen at random on that day to lead the discussion. \r<br />\r<br />Have a great Thanksgiving break!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(238, 'Welcome back!\r<br />The warm-up question today was &quot;(For you) What is the most difficult part of designing an experiment?&quot;  Some students shared what they struggled most with (e.g. identifying independent and dependent variables, control) and that guided our discussion about experimental design.  To practice, we completed an experimental design diagram for a experiment that could be conducted to determine if the amount of turkey eaten affects the amount of time someone sleeps.  Students were then instructed to design an experiment (using the format of an experimental design diagram) to answer the following question: What is the relationship between force, mass and acceleration?  I highlighted some materials and equipment available for the lab and a potential experimental set-up using motion carts, pulleys and either a motion detector and/or photogates.  Students were assigned a lab group, a role and worked together to complete and turn in parts 1 and 2 (guiding question for experiment and experimental design) of their science writing heuristic before the end of the period.  We''ll conduct the experiments tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(239, 'The warm-up question yesterday (11/29/10) was &quot;What questions do you have about diabetes?&quot;  Before discussing the question, we watched a brief, animated video from BrainPop about diabetes.  We then discussed any questions that weren''t answered by the video and took an informal, impromptu quiz about diabetes.  Next, we performed a &quot;mini-lab&quot; where we predicted the blood sugar levels for a diabetic throughout the day and measured artificial blood samples from the diabetic patient to compare to our initial predictions.  Any time remaining was spent working on the mold biodiversity lab.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(240, 'Note: I have posted the answer key for the last test in shared content (re-take test for motion graphs).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(241, 'Today was an early-release day and students set up their experiments as a warm up.  The remaining time was spent conducting those experiments and recording data.  Remember that the data recorder in your group should be saving all of the data in an Excel spreadsheet on the P drive.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(242, 'During class today, students were given the option to either 1) read the chapter from &quot;Survival of the Sickest&quot; for tomorrow''s chinwag, 2) read the kidney article and complete the associated reading guide (due Fri.), OR 3) continue working on the mold biodiversity lab.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(243, 'FYI, I posted (1) an Excel spreadsheet that can be used to calculate Simpson''s diversity index and (2) a checklist to assist you with writing your lab report.  I''m not saying you MUST use these resources, but please know that they''re available.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(244, 'Today, we discussed Ch. 2 (&quot;A Spoonful of Sugar Helps the Temperature go Down&quot;) of the book &quot;Survival of the Sickest&quot;.  It was an interesting discussion and made me wonder your thoughts about the following questions:\r<br />1) Do you think humans are more evolutionarily advanced than other species and why?\r<br />2) Is the evolution of humans at a stand-still (has evolution in our species ceased) and why?\r<br />From the discussion, and I could be wrong, I sensed some misperceptions in regards to these questions so I would like you to reconsider them.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(245, 'what were the objectives today? i need them to answer my warm-up :)', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(246, 'Don''t worry about writing the objectives for the warm up.  I won''t count that against you.\r<br />Have a great weekend!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(247, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;How could you know if your experimental results are reliable and/or expected?&quot;  After discussing the warm-up question, students worked with their partners on their labs.  At the end of the period, students were expected to turn in 1) their completed science writing heuristic (sections 1 - 7 completed), 2) an Excel spreadsheet showing the data they collected and a graph of the data, and 3) 2 force-body diagrams (one for the cart and one for the hanging mass).  We''ll discuss the lab more on Mon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(248, 'The warm up today was to turn in the reading guide from the kidney article.  While students were doing this, I handed back homeostasis notes and Biozone workbooks, with their associated rubrics and comments, and re-explained the purpose of doing the work and the meaning of the grades.  Students were then broken up into groups of 3 and charged with the task of planning and constructing a physical, 3-D model of a nephron.  The written (2-D) plan and 3-D model are due Tues. at the beginning of class and I would prefer that, other than some research, you only work on this project during class (Fri. and next Mon.).\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy the weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(249, 'thank u! :) have a great weekend too!', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(250, 'Yesterday''s (12/07/10) warm-up question was &quot;Describe one thing you learned about either (1) the relationship between force, mass and acceleration OR (2) the process of science from doing the cart lab last week?  After sharing some things learned from the lab, we discussed data obtained from conducting the lab and determined that force is directly related to mass and acceleration while mass and acceleration are indirectly related to each other.  We looked at this relationship conceptually, only using the size of letters to represent value, discussed how 1 Newton = 1 kg m/s2 and practiced solving problems about Newton''s 2nd law using dry-erase boards.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(251, 'Today''s warm up was as follows: &quot;If you double (&times;2) the acceleration of an object moving, what happens to the force created by that object? Be specific.&quot; After a brief review of concepts we discussed yesterday, students practiced solving problems like the warm-up question for 15 min. We then discussed the answers to those problems and how those problems could be solved. We then began discussing how to solve related problems that involved force-body diagrams. Any problems not completed by the end of the period were assigned as homework.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(252, 'Yesterday''s (12/06/10) warm-up question was to (1) read the essential questions for the kidney unit and then (2) write down any clarifying questions about the essential questions.  We briefly discussed key vocabulary terms and word roots for the unit and I handed out a rubric for the nephron model and the notes and Bizone assignment for this unit (due Mon.).  Students used the rest of the period to construct their nephron models, which are due at the beginning of class on 12/07/10.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(253, 'We began class today by setting up the nephron models.  Students then spent approx. 15 min. evaluating the overall accuracy and creativity of each model and writing constructive feedback to each group in re. to their model.  Prizes were awarded for ea. of the following categories: 1) Mr. Kern''s selection for best overall, 2) class selection for best overall, 3) most creative model, and 4) group that demonstrated the best overall teamwork.  Students used the remaining time to work on Activities A - C (Chapter 25) from the Campbell Biology textbook CD-rom and the &quot;Thinking as a Scientist Thinks&quot; activity from the same chapter.  I recommended using the activities to review and as a source of material for notes.  Questions and results from the &quot;Thinking as a Scientist Thinks&quot; activity should be emailed to me (Mr. Kern) by the beginning of class on Thurs. (12/09/10), and your kidney notes w/ Biozone worksheets should be completed by Mon. (12/13/10).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(254, 'Today, students continued working on activities A - C and the &quot;Thinking Like a Scientist Thinks&quot; virtual lab using the CD that came with their Biology textbook (Ch. 25).  Answers from the lab should be emailed to me (Mr. Kern) by the beginning of the period Thurs.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(255, 'The warm-up question today asked students to calculate the acceleration of a cart with a mass of 0.72 kg that was attached to a 0.1-kg hanging mass.  After discussing how to solve the problem and calculating the answers, students were asked to try and solve a similar problem.   We walked through how to solve this problem as well, and then reviewed the answers to the homework problems assigned yesterday.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(256, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What makes you unique?&quot;  After discussing some responses to this question, we began exploring variation among people''s senses...especially the ability to taste.  We listened to an explanation of taste, how we are able to taste and the benefits of tasting (even bitter food).  We also began exploring whether the ability to taste bitter compounds is genetic and tried to gather scientific evidence to support this claim.  Before leaving, students attempted to assign genotypes to individuals in a pedigree to see if the ability to taste PTC may be inherited and, if it is inherited, what kind of inheritance pattern it may display.  We''ll continue this tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(257, 'Chemistry Study Guide: HIGHLY recommended but not required. However, I will not consider rounding your semester grade up at  the &quot;.5&quot; iParent cut-off (i.e. 89.5 to 90) if you do not complete at least 90% of your study guide.', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(258, 'We warmed up today by watching an animation and describing the motion of the person and a canoe in that animation.  The warm-up was an illustration of Newton''s 3rd law, which we then discussed as a class.  We looked at different scenarios of action-reaction pairs and students then identified reaction pairs from scenarios listed on a worksheet.  We then practiced communicating the concepts of this law by selecting the best words to complete sentences (other side of worksheet).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(259, 'The warm-up today was to summarize, in one sentence, the illustrations being projected, which both involved water and the human body.  After sharing some summaries, we discussed the importance of osmoregulation and the possible consequences of disrupting this process.  Next, students were given options of how to use the remaining time in class.  The majority chose to have a lecture/discussion about the kidney, so we used the rest of the time to discuss the structure of a kidney and emphasized the process of ultrafiltration.  We''ll highlight some additional details tomorrow, and then begin reviewing for the final exams on Tues and Weds.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(260, 'Today''s warm-up question was: What questions do you have about yesterday''s discussion on Newton''s 3rd law?  After answering some questions, we then discussed how to predict the effects of action-reaction force pairs on the motions of 2 objects with different masses.  We accomplished this by calculating the acceleration of the earth due to a person''s gravity (remember, the reaction force to earth''s gravity pulling you down is you pulling the earth up).  We then watched a couple of brief videos.  One video reviewed Newton''s 3 laws of motion, and the other video was filled with misconceptions (wrong ideas) about Newton''s laws that I asked students to identify.  After discussing the problems with the second video, students worked on either (1) taking 3-column notes (What I Read/What it Means (in my own words)/Why it is Important) about Newton''s 3 laws from physicsclassroom.com, The Manga Guide to Physics, or The Cartoon Guide to Physics, (2) completing vocab word cards for the unit, and/or (3)  practicing solving problems on worksheets.  I am asking students to turn in a &quot;portfolio&quot; of work they completed this unit to show their understanding of the material.  This could include notes, vocab word cards, completed worksheets, etc. and will be used, along with the final exam, to calculate the final grade for the semester.  Thus, the more (quality) work completed the better.  We will continue individual reviews on Mon.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(261, 'Today''s warm-up question was to state and explain your opinion about FDA regulation of labeling common over-the-counter drugs that may cause kidney damage.  After discussing questions about yesterday''s discussion on ultrafiltration, we then continued talking about reabsorption, secretion and excretion.  We then played a review game as a class to begin preparing for next week''s cumulative exam.  Good job X''s.  I still have many crossword puzzles left over for homeostasis and osmoregulation and additional crossword puzzles are available in the Shared Content, along with an Excel spreadsheet entitled &quot;Biology Challenge!&quot; that may help you to review.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(262, 'I just posted some Power Point slides w/ figures some of you requested (and a couple of data tables that no one requested, but are still worth looking at and understanding).  It''s titled &quot;Excretion Pics&quot; in Shared Content.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(263, 'Thank you, Mr. Kern for all of the study material!! I''m sure I''m speaking for the whole class when I say that', 587, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(264, 'Thank you for the thank you Kyla.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(265, 'When students came in they were invited to take a sample Paper 1 and Paper 3.  After discussing some formatting suggestions for the IA, we then reviewed for Paper 1 by using the clickers to respond to questions from previous IB tests.  Best of luck studying.  Come and see me if you have any questions.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(266, 'We began class today by solving a practice test question about the experiment we conducted a couple of weeks ago that involved a cart and a hanging mass.  Students then used their time to study (either independently or with me) and accumulate evidence for their portfolio, which is due the day of the test.  Studying included, but was not limited to, reading and taking notes on Newton''s laws of motion and completing worksheets with sample problems.  Please come see me if you have any questions.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(267, 'Today, we took standard level Paper 3 from 2009 as the first part of your final exam.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(268, 'The warm-up question today was to predict/calculate the effect of a 200-kg mass and a 50-kg mass colliding with a force of 100N.  After discussing how to calculate the answer to this question, we then reviewed for the final exam using clickers in a game-style format.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(269, 'Yes Virginia, there IS a study guide for the Stoichiometry test! Go thee to QUIA and take it. It will help you on Thursday''s test. Promise! -Bennett Out.', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(270, 'Welcome back!  I hope you enjoyed your break and have returned refreshed and ready to learn.\r<br />\r<br />Today, semester 1 exams were returned and we reviewed the correct answers to the test questions so that students could recognize errors made on the exam and understand how to correct and/or improve their responses.  \r<br />\r<br />Next, we began the next unit of study (Energy) by doing an activity.  Students were randomly assigned to a group and one energy source.  With their group members, students then read 10 sets of clues and chose which set described their energy source.  After 3 min., the groups who selected the set of clues that matched their energy source won a prize.  We then repeated this with progressively less time in each round until all groups had correctly matched their energy source to the clues describing their energy source.  Groups then chose 3 clues that revealed the least about their energy source and took turns reading those clues to the rest of the class.  The other groups were responsible for listening to the clues being read and writing down the appropriate energy source to match each set of clues.  These &quot;quizzes&quot; were turned in before leaving class.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(271, 'Welcome back! I hope you enjoyed your break and have returned refreshed and ready to learn. \r<br />\r<br />Today, semester 1 final exams (Papers 1 &amp; 3) were returned and we reviewed the correct answers to the test questions so that students could recognize errors made on the exam and understand how to correct and/or improve their responses.\r<br />\r<br />We then began our next unit of study, which is the digestive system, by completing a brief formative assessment about the function of this system.  After these were collected, we discussed the big ideas, essential questions, key vocab words and word roots for this unit.  We then watched a Schoolhouse Rocks video (&quot;The Body Machine&quot;) as an introduction to this system, identified and correctly placed the components of the digestive system onto a virtual body and watched a trip through the digestive system.\r<br />\r<br />Tomorrow, you will have about 20 or so min. to begin taking notes and working on your Biozone assigment for this unit.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(272, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What, exactly, is energy?  (How would you define energy?)  We discussed possible definitions of energy and chose one that is most appropriate for our class.  Students then took a pre-test on different sources of energy.  We watched a brief BrainPop! video about sources of energy (link posted in shared content) and then students revised the answers to their quiz before turning them in.  Before the end of class, we reviewed the answers to the quiz, which can also be accessed from the BrainPop! link.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(273, 'Today''s warm-up question was to describe how a cartoon picture represented the process of digestion.  We also discussed the components (structures) of the digestive system that were represented in the cartoon and some errors in the cartoon that could lead to misconceptions.  We then watched a video about anorexia and discussed 1) the medical complications resulting from anorexia, 2) the molecular mechanisms that make anorexia so deadly and 3) how adding fat to diet can actually result in a loss of weight.  Everyone received the notes and Biozone assignment for the digestion unit before leaving class. We may have time to work on this assignment Fri., but there are no guarantees.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(274, 'FYI, I posted the answer key to the semester 1 exam (Newton''s laws) in shared content.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(275, 'in our info sheets we have uranium, but during the class it was different what was it?', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(276, 'Doyca,\r<br />Uranium is the source of energy and the form of energy that comes from uranium is nuclear.  Hope that helps.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(277, 'Today''s warm-up activity was to describe the difference between a &quot;source&quot; energy and a &quot;form&quot; of energy and to then sort different energy types into the appropriate &quot;source&quot; OR &quot;form&quot; category.  We discussed student responses and then watched a brief BrainPop! video describing different forms of energy.  Next, we did a demo where we measured the temperatures of 2 containers of sand, one that was full and one that was only one-third full, before and then after shaking.  We discussed the observed differences, explained why there were differences and talked about how energy was transformed to cause the change.  We also used a graphic organizer to describe energy forms and provide examples of each form on a note-holder.  We finished class by identifying the forms of energy that are obtained from energy sources and using a data table to analyze the percent of energy for each form that is used by the U.S.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(278, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;Do you think our ancient ancestors would have liked coffee?  Why or why not?&quot;  After discussing several student responses that did an exceptional job of tying yesterday''s learning to the question, we reviewed how to analyze and interpret pedigrees.  Students then re-analyzed their pedigrees and used a handout to infer if the pedigree indicates that the ability to taste PTC is genetic and, if so, what type of inheritance pattern is indicated (the evidence suggested autosomal dominant inheritance).  From here, we tried to gather other evidence that this trait is genetic by analyzing DNA sequences from a non-taster, taster and supertaster and found 3 differences.  We then connected these differences to the &quot;central dogma&quot; of molecular biology.  Due to technical difficulties, we skipped the closing video, but students were asked to complete a 4-Choice Processing diagram to reflect on the genetics of taste.  The 4-choice processing responses are due on Thurs.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(279, 'thank you mr. kern  :)', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(280, 'Today''s class began with the following warm-up question: &quot;What has MORE energy, a baketball at the top of it''s trajectory (arc) or a falling basketball just before it hits the floor?  Why?&quot;  We discussed the answer, reviewed the forms of energy and discussed the energy transformations occuring when using a hand-powered flashlight.  Students then broke off into assigned groups to become oriented with the lab at their station.  Tomorrow, groups will conduct their lab and plan how they will teach the energy concepts in their lab to their classmates.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(281, 'We began class today by discussing the warm-up question &quot;What questions do you have about the last 2 days of class (genetics of taste)?&quot;  Students then received an article from Science News (&quot;Stomach''s Sweet Tooth&quot;) to read.  I changed the original assignment so that students can either 1) turn in a 4-Choice Processing for the article and what we learned in class Mon. &amp; Tues. OR 2) write a brief (1-pg summary) of the key findings/concept in the article and what we learned in class Mon. &amp; Tues.  Regardless, the assignment is due at the beginning of class on Fri.  Come to class tomorrow with any questions you have about Topic 6.1 (digestion), as I will attempt to clarify any nebulous objectives and/or confusions you may have after working on your notes and Biozone assignment.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(282, 'what up classes', 2288, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(283, 'hiiiiiiiiiiii', 2281, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(284, 'Yes you can Doyca.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(285, 'Yesterday (01/18/11), you had a substitute teacher and were supposed to use the period to rehearse your presentations, which will be graded as a summative assessment (test).  We have been working on these lab stations since last Weds. so my expectations, in terms of your ability to discuss energy and energy transformations, are high.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(286, 'Today, groups began presenting their energy demonstrations to their classmates in small groups.  We only made it through 2 demonstrations and will continue tomorrow using the same format.  Any students who are not evaluated during small group presentations on Thurs. will need to present their demos to the entire class next Mon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(287, 'Mr. Kern,\r<br />I dont know if i will be in school tomorrow, ive been really sick. what should i do to keep up with the class?', 1337, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(288, 'Zayda,\r<br />\r<br />We are currently conducting labs in class.  Students are learning about and preparing to teach their particular lab activities to their classmates.  We will probably continue reading about the relevant science behind each lab and rehearsing the presentation tomorrow so that we can conduct the labs next Tues. and Weds.  As such, there isn''t a lot that you can do to keep up with the class at home other than get some rest and eat well so that you have a quick recovery and return in the near future.  Take care and I hope you feel better soon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(289, 'We began class today by reading the safety rules for the lab.  We discussed any clarifying questions students had about the safety rules and I highlighted some of the most essential rules for this lab.  Students then worked in their assigned groups to conduct the lab and plan their demonstrations and presentations regarding forms of energy and their transformations.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(290, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: Compare ingestion, digestion, absorption, assimilation and elimination.  After discussing each of these terms, we spent the remaining class time discussing clarifying questions of students and reviewing the structure and function of the digestive system.  Remember, notes and Biozone are due tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(291, 'Please note that I have yet to receive the mold biodiversity labs (IAs) from 3 of you (You know, the ones that were due before winter break).  These labs are v. important and not submitting them could result in not earning your diploma.  Please don''t put yourself or me in that position.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(292, 'Today, we began class by identifying organisms that use (cellular) respiration and explaining those choices.  We briefly discussed the link between digestion and respiration and we began reviewing cellular respiration by completing an activity on Molecular Workbench (MW).  Directions to sign up for a MW account and a link to the MW website are posted in shared content. \r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your 3-day weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(293, 'Today''s warm up was &quot;What are the possible consequences of you not adequately preparing to teach your classmates?&quot;  We briefly discussed responses and then students continued completing their lab data sheets and planning to teach their classmates about the forms of energy and energy formations that are seen in the demos at their lab station.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your 3-day weekend and come prepared to teach on Tues.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(294, 'Trouble finding the QUIA quizzes?\r<br />\r<br />1. Choose &quot;6-Chemistry&quot; from the &quot;my classes&quot; drop down.\r<br />2) At the lower-right click the &quot;shared content&quot; link.\r<br />3) Click on the QUIA: 6th Hour Chemistry link\r<br />\r<br />The first quiz due is: &quot;Reading Quiz: KMT and Pressure&quot;', 89, 1, 240, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(295, 'Trouble finding the QUIA quizzes?\r<br />\r<br />1) Choose &quot;7-Chemistry&quot; from the &quot;my classes&quot; drop down.\r<br />2) At the lower-right click the &quot;shared content&quot; link. \r<br />3) Click on the QUIA: 7th Hour Chemistry link\r<br />\r<br />The first quiz due is: &quot;Reading Quiz: KMT and Pressure&quot;\r<br />', 89, 1, 241, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(296, 'Trouble finding the QUIA quizzes?\r<br />\r<br />1) Choose &quot;8-Chemistry&quot; from the &quot;my classes&quot; drop down.\r<br />2) At the lower-right click the &quot;shared content&quot; link. \r<br />3) Click on the QUIA: 7th Hour Chemistry link\r<br />\r<br />The first quiz due is: &quot;Reading Quiz: KMT and Pressure&quot;\r<br />', 89, 1, 243, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(297, 'mr. kern can we use index cards on tuesday, instead the whole article? :)', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(298, 'mr. kern can we use index cards on tuesday, instead the whole article? :)', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(299, 'Yesterday (01/18/11), you had a substitute teacher.  You should have collected your graded notes and Biozone workbooks and picked up model answers for the digestion questions.  Students should have used the class period to read an article (&quot;Lungs and the Control of Breathing), write 15-word summaries for ea. section of that article, and illustrate any missing firgures from the text.  This assignment is due Thurs. and I posted an electronic copy in shared content.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(300, 'Today, we continued reviewing by discussing a case study that highlighted the importance of energy and enzymes for maintaining life.  Students also used clickers to show their understanding of the material.  We will continue the review tomorrow, focusing more on the process of cellular respiration and what this metabolic process has to do with why the young man we are investigating became paralyzed.  Cellular respiration links digestion (previous unit) to gas exchange (next unit) and is one area students typically do not earn high marks on during the exam in May, so I strongly encourage you to stay focused, take notes and ask clarifying questions during the review.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. I mentioned this in class, but most of your IAs have been graded.  They are posted in the P drive if you want to see my comments and how you scored on the IB rubrics, but those scores have not been convereted to a THS grade and entered into IC yet.  My goal is to have you conduct 2 more labs before March in attempt to provide you with more opportunities to showcase what you know and are able to do (only the 2 highest grades will be submitted to IB).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(301, 'Today we finished reviewing the process of cellular respiration and the role genetically-inherited mutations can have on metabolic pathways by completing the clicker case study of the paralyzed young man.  In terms of studying cellular respiration, remember to focus on the main ideas of ea. stage (glycolysis, TCA cycle, oxidative phosphorylation) and the involvement of a few key molecules (e.g. glucose, acetyl CoA, pyruvate, citrate) as opposed to memorizing every last detail of the process.  I guarantee it will be a better use of your time and you will perform better on those specific test questions.\r<br />\r<br />Next, we compared the terms (cellular) respiration, gas exchange and ventilation by discussing these words as a class (this information was also in the first few paragraphs of the article that was due today).  We ended class by identifying the structures comprising the gas exchange (&quot;respiratory&quot;) system on a diagram.\r<br />\r<br />Test on digestion (topic 6.1) is still tomorrow!  Don''t forget to bring resources for notes and/or your Biozone book to class on Mon.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(302, 'Groups continued presenting their demonstrations today.  We made it through the 1st round of instruction and into the 2nd round.  If I was not able to listen to your presentation yesterday or today, you will need to present your lesson to the class on Mon. (I will not be in class tomorrow).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(303, 'Helpful hints on the QUIA quizzes (and thanks for the continued emails): 1) If a quiz is &quot;unavailable, try hitting ''refresh'' on your computer at least once. Seems a few people couldn''t get into quizzes that were still open. 2) To help with what is direct vs. indirect, use that ruler trick (order is P, T, V). Cover the constant and see what happens to one as you change the other. 3) Keep a copy of the Combined Gas Law formula in front of you as you work. Even I have accidentally set problems up incorrectly when going too fast.', 89, 1, 240, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(304, 'Helpful hints on the QUIA quizzes (and thanks for the continued emails): 1) If a quiz is &quot;unavailable, try hitting ''refresh'' on your computer at least once. Seems a few people couldn''t get into quizzes that were still open. 2) To help with what is direct vs. indirect, use that ruler trick (order is P, T, V). Cover the constant and see what happens to one as you change the other. 3) Keep a copy of the Combined Gas Law formula in front of you as you work. Even I have accidentally set problems up incorrectly when going too fast.', 89, 1, 241, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
