INSERT INTO `class_wall` (`comment_id`, `body`, `userID`, `level`, `classID`, `schoolID`, `date_posted`) VALUES
(306, 'Helpful hints on the QUIA quizzes (and thanks for the continued emails): 1) If a quiz is &quot;unavailable, try hitting ''refresh'' on your computer at least once. Seems a few people couldn''t get into quizzes that were still open. 2) To help with what is direct vs. indirect, use that ruler trick (order is P, T, V). Cover the constant and see what happens to one as you change the other. 3) Keep a copy of the Combined Gas Law formula in front of you as you work. Even I have accidentally set problems up incorrectly when going too fast.', 89, 1, 297, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(307, 'Last Fri, we took the test on topic 6.1 (digestion).\r<br />\r<br />Today, we reviewed the answers to the digestion test students took last Fri (this incl. looking at components of model responses).  After discussing responses, students used the remaining class time to take notes, write summaries, or complete their Biozone assignment for topic 6.4 (gas exchange).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(308, 'On Friday (there was a substitute teacher), students watched a video about forms of energy and energy transformations.  At the end of the period, students were asked to turn in the responses to the questions they chose to answer about the video.\r<br />\r<br />Today students performed demonstrations for the entire class.  During these demonstrations, students explained the different forms of energy and transformations of energy that their demonstrations illustrated.  We discussed how coal is formed and traced the flow of energy from the sun to coal and eventually from coal to electricity.  Students were divided into groups of 3 or 4 students and began constructing an energy flow diagram, which we''ll finish tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(309, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What is something you learned OR something you still don''t understand about the transformation of chemical energy in coal to electrical energy?&quot;  After discussing some responses, we then worked on constructing a model of energy flow and transformations by stringing together several different objects to create a web.  Once groups finished with their model and answered a few questions, they then began designing a (virtual) sustainable city on the computer.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. We also discussed the alternative assessment (energy brochure) that can be completed to replace the presentation grade.  This assignment is posted in Shared Content (look up and to the right).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(310, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;How could you measure the activity of an enzyme, knowing that they are too small to be seen with the naked-eye or a microscope?&quot;  We then discussed the objective for the next internal assessment (Design and conduct an experiment to investigate the activity of amylase and/or lipase) and some of the equipment available for conducting that experiment.  The remaining time was spent looking over some of the IA resources I posted in Shared Content (e.g. IAs, error info), performing preliminary research for the lab and/or brainstorming experimental questions.  Remember that I posted the user manuals for the colorimeter and pH probe in Shared Content.  You may want to refer to these for operation procedures, trouble shooting and/or error information.  Experimental designs for this IA should be completed on &quot;poster&quot; (butcher) paper by the beginning of class on Fri.  Due to several requests, you''ll have classtime to work on this tomorrow as well.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(311, 'sup peeps', 2287, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(312, 'hi, bye', 2285, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(313, 'Today we worked in our IA lab groups to continue researching, planning and designing an experiment to investigate the activity of an amylase and/or a lipase.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(314, 'Today, we either 1) worked in our groups to complete the energy flow model (activity involving yellow cards and yarn) or 2) began creating the virtual city.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(315, 'Ok for the Science Quiz what exactly is going to be on there and did we get the notes yet for gravity?', 2304, 1, 326, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(316, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What is something you learned or now realize about the flow and/or transformation of energy after constructiong your model of cards and yarn?&quot;  A couple of students shared their responses and then students who completed the energy flow model began working on the Enercities activity creating their own sustainable city.  Students who did not finish their model continued working on that model.\r<br />\r<br />Reminder, periods 1 and 8 will meet in a different classroom tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(317, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What questions do you have about the gas exchange system at this point?&quot;  We discussed a couple of questions and then students were broken up into groups to analyze data-based information relating to the gas exchange system.  After completing their analyses, students then shared what they learned with other members of their jig-saw group (people who worked on another data-based question).  You''ll probably have time tomorrow after the gallery walk to complete the written reflection.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(318, 'Today we evaluated experimental designs of different groups by performing a gallery walk.  Hopefully this feedback will result in improved designs and will equate to desired IA scores.  We were also fortunate to have had an impromptu guest speaker (former THS and IB grad Tyler Schelpat [''08]) share his insights about surviving senior year, IAs, G4, external assessments (May exams) and college life.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(319, 'Today we either (1) watched a video about the future of solar energy (periods 1 and 8) or (2) played Enercities.  Next week ,we''ll begin exploring kinetic and potential energy and the conservation of mechanical energy.\r<br />\r<br />Note: Mon. will be an important day because we''ll be learnig foundational knowledge for conducting labs later that week.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(320, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;List what you know about potential and kinetic energy.&quot;  After passing back some assignments, students shared what they wrote down and we recorded those ideas on the board.  Students should be able to identify both correct and incorrect responses on that list by the end of the week.  We then answered questions on a worksheet about potential energy, kinetic energy and total mechanical energy using the information in a physicsclassroom.com tutorial.  We''ll discuss the correct answers the next time we have class.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your day off tomorrow!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(321, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What is ''halitosis''?  What factors contribute to halitosis?&quot;  We discussed student responses to this question and then 12 students took a &quot;bad-breath test&quot;.  We discussed the results of the test and how the test worked and then began a lab investigating the amount of CO2 produced by different individuals using the technique of titration (some of you saw your G4 chem partners do this for their part of the G4 project).  This may be an avenue some of you might like to pursue as a group for an additional IA.  \r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your day off tomorrow and please remember that although we don''t have school tomorrow, G4 posters are still due on Thurs.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(322, 'I just posted a document (&quot;Poster checklist &amp; layout&quot;)  in Shared Content that may help you with your G4 poster that''s due Thurs.\r<br />\r<br />*This is the same one I gave you, Ferougg and Tue, Mon. afternoon.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(323, 'Today, we discussed the answers to the &quot;Energy&quot; worksheet we began working on Mon.  We will practice the calculations more in the future, but the information we reviewed is the foundation for the lab we will begin next week.  Turn the completed worksheet in as part of your portfolio, which is due the day of the test.\r<br />\r<br />See you Monday!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(324, 'Today we continued performing our titrations to explore the variation in the amount of carbon dioxide we each exhale.  Hopefully the class data, which is stored in Google docs, spurs some questions for you and you (and your group) can start brainstorming ideas for an IA.  During class, students also received 1) model answers for their Biozone worksheet questions, 2) a packet of how we can use a spirometer, oxygen and carbon dioxide sensor with our Vernier software to investigate the function of the respiratory system (another IA possibility) and 3) the notes and Biozone assignment for the next unit.  Please note that those of you taking the higher-level test have an additional assignment involving plants.  \r<br />\r<br />See you Monday!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(325, 'I just posted an article about energy (&quot;What is Energy?) to help you gain a better understanding of the concept of energy and the difference between kinetic and potential energies.  I also posted the pdf &quot;Calculating KE and PE&quot;, which you may find helpful for understanding how to calculate both kinetic and potential energies.  Both resources are posted in Shared Content.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(326, 'hello my name is joe and i love DES!', 1469, 1, 239, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(327, 'Today we watched 2 brief video clips about potential (PE) and kinetic (KE) energy and then completed a 20-question quiz to demonstrate our understanding about these two types of mechanical energy.  We then used dry-erase boards to practice performing calculations using energy equations.  Understanding KE and PE and being able to do these calculations is necessary for the next lab so once most of you show you have this understanding we''ll start that lab.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(328, 'Today''s warm-up was to list the adaptations of alveoli that help them perform their job.  We discussed these adaptations as a class and examined some pictures of alveoli to understand its structure in more detail (esp. the location and purpose of the basal lamina).  We then discussed the mechanism of ventilation and used models to elucidate this process in terms of volume and pressure changes.  We briefly talked about hemoglobin and then read a poem that ties the gas exchange (respiratory) system to the internal transport (cardiovascular) system.  When analyses of the poem were collected from each student, we continued our exploration of art and science by watching two music videos about the cardiovascular system.\r<br />\r<br />Note: The chapter for the next chinwag was also disseminated.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(329, 'During class today, we used the white boards to practice solving word problems involving the energy equations.  If you understand all of the energy calculations we''ve done to this point, you should have enough knowledge and practice to complete the calculations in the lab we''ll start tomorrow.  If you are still struggling with solving these problems, seek help from a classmate, ask me during class (when it''s appropirate) or arrange to come and see me outside of class.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(330, 'At the beginning of class, we decided to dedicate tomorrow''s period to planning the respiration lab (IA) and next Mon. to conducting the lab.  We also decided that you get to choose the groups for your lab.  We spent the next 25 min. learning about the structure of the heart by performing a virtual open-heart surgery.  I posted the link to this website in Shared Content. After the by-pass surgeries were completed, we continued to learn about the external and internal anatomy of the heart by dissecting a sheep''s heart.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(331, 'I just posted a PowerPoint file (NRG Practice Problems) in Shared Content.  We practiced and discussed solving these problems during class this past Mon. and Tues.  If you missed any of those days, or would just like some more practice, I would look at and practice solving these problems.  You could also turn in &quot;worked&quot; problems from this set in your portfolio as evidence of studying/learning.  (Remember, your portfolio must be turned in before the test and will be one factor in determining your grade).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(332, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What is the mass of an object traveling at 30 m/s if it has 33,750 J of energy?&quot;  After discussing how to solve this problem, we began a station lab to explain kinetic energy, potential energy and the conservation of mechanical energy.  We''ll continue this lab tomorrow.\r<br />\r<br />Note: This warm-up question, along with problems we practiced during class using whiteboards  on Mon. and Tues., is posted in Shared Content.  See the posting below for more info.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(333, 'Note: I just bookmarked several URLs in Shared Content (NIH: Cardiovascular System, ABPI: The Heart and Circulation, Get Body Smart and Interactive Physiology) that are good sources of information for taking notes and understanding the learning objectives for topic 6.2 (internal transport).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(334, 'For the warm-up question today, I asked you to come up with a few &quot;I wonders&quot; about the data in the respiration lab spreadsheet (Google docs).  After several students shared their responses, we broke off into lab groups and used some of the &quot;I wonders&quot; to begin designing an experiment investigating respiration.  A due date hasn''t been set for the lab report (IA) yet, but both this and the digestion lab must be completed before the 2nd week of March.  We will begin conducting this lab on Mon. during class.\r<br />\r<br />G4 presentations tomorrow!  Woo hoo!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(335, 'We began class today by converting mass and distance measurements from grams and centimeters to kilograms and meters, respectively.  This is important because whenever you calculate kinetic and potential energies, the units you use must be in meters and kilograms to arrive at an answer in Joules.  We then spent the reaminder of class working on our lab station, which we''ll resume on Mon. when I return.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(336, 'Today we presented our G4 projects.  You can now sigh a breath of sweet relief, but remember that the majority of your grade for this project will stem from your reflection and how well you worked with your group members.  You received the group-member evaluation form after the presentations today and will receive your reflection form tomorrow during class from Mrs. Robertson.  See you Mon!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(337, 'Today we continued working on our stations lab to investigate KE, PE and TME.  At this point, groups should have 4 stations completed and two more stations to finish tomorrow.  Remember to work on the calculations outside of class if you don''t finish them during class.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(338, 'On Fri., you had a substitute teacher.  Mrs. Robertson came in to discuss G4 projects and explain the reflection piece for G4.  This reflection is a significant aspect of your grade, should offer deep insights into your thinking and should be no less than 2 pgs.  The rest of the period was used to work on other class assignments (e.g. IAs, notes, Biozone).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(339, 'Last Fri. you had a substitute teacher. Your warm-up was as follows: &quot;What does a ''Joule'' have to do with beer? What does science have to do with a honeymoon?&quot; After discussing responses, students were given an article (a biography of James Joule) to read and several questions to answer regarding the reading. This article also revealed the answers to the warm-up question. After answering the questions, students received an opportunity to practice the KE and PE problems on a worksheet. The worksheet is posted in Shared Content as &quot;KE and PE problems&quot;, but you''ll need to get a hard-copy of the article from me.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(340, 'We began class today by turning in the G4 reflections and discussing any questions/concerns you had about G4 (that is, anything Mrs. Robertson didn''t address).  Please take time to thoughtfully reflect and evaluate what you learned from the G4 experience.  While more time could have been invested in the project to strengthen both the science and the quality of the posters (quality is a reflection of the quality and amount of effort placed into a project), you can still earn most of your points for this project by a well-written and thoughtful reflection--reflection on what you learned during this entire process, from working with groups, what you learned about yourself as a learner, the challenges in conducting science, etc.  If you would like your reflections back so you can revise them without penalty, please ask.\r<br />\r<br />We spent the rest of the class period working with our groups on the respiration/gas exchange IA.\r<br />\r<br />Note: Please remember that when discussing experimental results it is OK to say your results are inconclusive.  Many of the claims made on the G4 experiments were not justified with appropriate or sufficient evidence.  If you run into this for your IAs, it''s important for you to recognize that limitation and discuss that in your discussion.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(341, 'During class today, we finished the stations lab.  These labs should have been completed and turned in before leaving class.  If you were absent on any given day, you should schedule a time to come in (b/f school, after school, during lunch) and finish the stations you did not complete.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(342, 'The warm-up question today was to read the following comprehension questions:\r<br />1) What is the cultural and metaphorical significance of the heart?\r<br />2) What is the origin of the heart symbol?\r<br />3) Who is Hugh Montgomery and how did he contribute to our scientific understanding the heart?\r<br />4) Why can’t you literally experience a heartache?\r<br />5) In what unique way did a father assist in the open-heart surgery of his child?\r<br />6) What are the current challenges in perfecting an artificial heart?\r<br />We then listened to a NPR interview of 2 cardiologists who recently published the book &quot;The Sublime Engine: A Biography of the Human Heart&quot; (i''ve posted this link in Shared Content).  After listening and sharing thoughts about the video, we then began constructing a physical model of a fish''s circulatory system to understand the process of circulation and function of the structures within this organ system.  We''ll continue constructing and analyzing the model tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(343, 'We continued constructing the model of a fish''s circulatory system and then attempted to test that model by timing how long the &quot;oxygenated blood&quot; needed to travel through the entire system and how many ventricular pumps are required to move that blood throughout the entire system.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(344, 'I asked students to complete the following sentence stem for their warm-up: &quot;After completing the stations lab, I am still struggling to understand...because...&quot;  In order to learn and improve your understanding, it is important to identify the specific topics/processes you do not understand, determine the resources available that will help you learn that information and then take advantage of those resources so that you are successful.  \r<br />\r<br />Students used the remainder of the class period to work on the homework assignment received last Fri. and was due this past Mon.  You MUST complete this assignment and earn a minimum score of 10 out of 12 in order to move on to the next activity (a computer simulation that will help you understand how to represent the amount of KE and PE in graphs).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(345, 'If you''re struggling to understand the difference between potential and kinetic energy, check out the Eureka! video I posted in Shared Content.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(346, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: During class we''ve focused on potential energy due to gravity, which is a type of mechanical energy.  What are some objects that have potential energy that is NOT due to gravity?  How might we measure the the amount of energy stored in these objects?  We discussed responses to these questions and then students either 1) continued working on the homework problem set they received last Fri. until at least 10 of the 12 problems were correctly solved or 2) began working on the Phet simulation to understand how to interpret and predict shapes of energy graphs for objects.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(347, 'Today was very productive.  We began class by talking about the strengths and weaknesses of the fish cardiovascular system model we constructed during class and how that model could be improved.  If we have time, we''ll modify the model the existing model to create a simplified version of the human circulatory system.  We then watched a segment of &quot;Happy Days&quot; to understand the path of blood through the circulatory system and completed the lyrics to Fonzi &amp; Potsi''s &quot;Pump Your Blood&quot; song.  We then used these lyrics to diagram the path of blood.  Finally, we listened to the song &quot;Blood Mobile&quot; by They Might Be Giants to understand what materials are transported through the blood.  Links to the songs &amp; videos will be posted in Shared Content.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(348, 'The warm-up question today was to get out your &quot;homework&quot; and finish it so that you can move on to the computer simulation.  Another teacher wants to use our classroom next week, so today may be the only day to work on the computer simulation in class.  Whatever you don''t finish should be completed as homework.  The rest of the period looked like yesterday.  Students either 1) continued working on the homework problem set they received last Fri. until at least 10 of the 12 problems were correctly solved or 2) began working on the Phet simulation to understand how to interpret and predict shapes of energy graphs for objects.\r<br />\r<br />Note: I posted the computer simulation assignment in Shared Content.  It''s entitled &quot;Energy Skate Park&quot;.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(349, 'We began class by describing what we saw happening in an animation of an erythrocyte (red blood cell) making a complete circuit around our body.  We discussed different people''s observations and then practiced identifying the different parts of the heart using a drag-and-drop diagram.  After students were individually called up to help complete labeling the heart, we transitioned to our chinwag.\r<br />\r<br />Today''s chinwag took on a different format than before.  We began by individually writing the 4 key ideas from the text.  Next, we discussed our 4 key ideas with a partner, decided what the 2 main ideas were and wrote those down.  Finally, the each pair met with another pair to form a group of 4.  This group then discussed each of their 2 big ideas and the group eventually reached a consensus about the text''s big idea, which everyone also wrote down.  People shared what they noticed and what they were still wondering about from their discussions and then everyone did a free write about the text and their discussions.   I collected the 4-2-1 free write forms, gave everyone the next article, which is from the same book and still pertains to the cardiovascular system, and then reminded everyone about our plan for next Tues. (work on the digestion enzyme IA).\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy the 3-day weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(350, 'I failed to mention it, but for our next chinwag please read &quot;The Cholesterol Also Rises&quot;.  As you read, find and mark...\r<br />1) the sentence from the text that you found the most interesting,\r<br />2) a phrase from the text that you found to be valuable, and\r<br />3) one word from the text that best summarizes the reading.\r<br />Come prepared to discuss your sentence, phrase and word for the chinwag.\r<br />', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(351, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What does it mean to be ''efficient'' &quot;?  We discussed this as a class and wrote down a formal definition for efficiency.  We also discussed how, in reality, no energy transformation is 100% efficient.  We learned the equation for calculating efficiency and then practiced using this equation to find solutions to word problems on the white boards.  I posted the problems (plus some additional problems) in Shared Content.  Lab tomorrow!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(352, 'We used the period today to work on the digestive enzyme IA.  We''ll dedicate tomorrow to this lab as well.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(353, 'Like yesterday, we used the period today to work on the digestive enzyme IA.  I emailed ea. of you a Google doc for tomorrow''s chinwag.  Ignore it until class tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(354, 'The warm up today was to calculate the amount of energy required to raise the temperature of 100 ml of water 10&deg;C. The additional info. given was as follows: (1) Specific heat of H2O is about 4.186; (2) For H2O, 1 ml = 1 g; and (3) Q = mCp(delta)T, where Q = NRG required (J), m = mass of substance (g), Cp = specific heat (J/g/&deg;C) and (delta)T = change in temp. (&deg;C). You need to be able to do this calculation for the energy efficiency lab. I checked for correct responses to the warm-up question and then we practiced doing one more calculation like this to ensure everyone was comfortable using the equation. Students then chose their own groups (3 - 4 people) for the lab and completed a data table to record the info they gather during the lab. You may conduct the lab tomorrow after everyone in your group shows they have completed the data table. We will only have tomorrow to complete this lab.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(355, 'At the beginning of class today, we discussed IAs (rubrics, reasons for focusing on elements not in rubrics, option of completing IAs, etc.).  We then participated in a chinwag that involved documenting &quot;conversations&quot; (with a few exceptions, the &quot;conversations&quot; didn''t really involve productive or focused discussions) on a Google doc.  Technology glitches proved to be a little cumbersome at times so please complete the Google doc as a group by Mon.  \r<br />\r<br />Don''t forget to bring your calculators tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(356, 'Today''s warm-up was as follows: A speaker uses 5 watts (W) of power to produce sound for 1 hour.  How many Joules of energy did this speaker use during this time?  Like yesterday, I checked for correct responses, we solved the problem on the front white board to make sure everyone understood how to calculate the answer, and then we tried to calculate one more problem like this one for practice.   We then broke off into our lab groups and began conducting the lab, which was to measure the efficiency of different water-heating appliances.  While we won''t have access to the lab materials, you can finish the calculations tomorrow during class.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(357, 'The warm-up question today asked &quot;What type of NRG is associated w/ a mountain climber? What’s your evidence?&quot; In periods 1 and 4, we discusssed responses to begin practicing for the test. We also answered the same question for another object (fireworks). You should be able to predict the type of energy associated with objects for the test. We then participated in a rapid-fire review, where I asked students basic-knowledge questions about energy to begin reviewing for the test (e.g. What''s the definition of energy? List 2 forms of energy.) After reviewing like this for several minutes, students used computers to access The Physics Classroom website and take 2-column notes (What I read/Questions I have) on the definition of work, how to calculate work and examples of work. After finishing this, students continued solving the word problems on the Work 8.1 worksheet they received Fri. \r<br />\r<br />\r<br />February 25, 2011 \r<br />\r<br />We had a substitute teacher on Fri. Students were supposed to complete their calculations from the energy efficiency lab and then turn in that lab, take notes on the concept of work from the website &quot;The Physics Classroom&quot; and then practice solving word problems using the work equation (W = F * d). See today''s notes (above) for more detail.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(358, 'Today''s warm-up question was to identify and correct the errors made on a diagram showing the flow of blood through the cardiovascular system.  Students took turns making corrrections to the diagram and then we discussed the changes, the flow of blood through the heart and the structure, function and operation of the cardiac conduction system.  We also did a rapid-fire review of basic knowledge regarding the cardiovascular and respiratory systems. \r<br />\r<br />\r<br />February 25, 2011\r<br />\r<br />Today you had a substitute teacher.  Students practiced analyzing and interpreting data in tables and graphs, interpolating and extrapolating data based on those graphs and reviewing the cellular and non-cellular components of the blood.  This activity was NOT simply busy work, designed to keep you busy in my absence.  Instead, this knowledge AND these skills are essential for your tests in May.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(359, 'la usa en la computadora en la ciencas naturales', 1637, 1, 326, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(360, 'Today''s warm-up for periods 1 and 4 was &quot;What does the theta symbol represent in the work formula&quot;?  Period 8''s warm up was to identify the types of energy associated with fireworks and the evidence for those energy forms being present.  After discussing the responses, we discussed what theta actually means and talked about some special situations (e.g. when force and displacement are in the same direction, when force and displacement are in opposite directions, when force and displacement are in perpendicular directions).  We then practiced solving word problems using the work equation and the visual instruction plan we''ve been practicing in class. \r<br />\r<br />March 2, 2011\r<br />\r<br />Today, you had a substitute teacher.  You received an equation reference sheet, added equations to that sheet (you can use this sheet for the test) and then worked on your work and power problems.  We''ll check the solutions to these problems on Thurs.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(361, 'Today''s warm-up question was to complete some analogies involving the cardiovascular system and explain the relationship between the words you chose.  We discussed responses (non-evaluatively) as a class and then I highlighted some miscellaneous points concerning work, predicted grades and IAs.  We then did a little review, but time ran out before we discussed everything I would have liked to discuss.  Consequently, we''ll move the test to Fri.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. Don''t stress out over the difference in test formats.  While it may not be what you are used to, at least in terms of tests, your performance is still contingent upon your understanding of the learning objectives listed for Topics 6.2 and 6.4.  I want to see that you are able to demonstrate your knowledge in different ways, as many of you have already demonstrated a keen ability to play the common academic game of memorizing and regurgitating trivia on multiple choice, fill-in-the-blank and constructed response-based tests.   \r<br />\r<br />March 1, 2011\r<br />\r<br />Today you had a substitute teacher.  Students used microscopes to examine cross sections of arteries and veins and then sketch and label the structural components of those blood vessels.  You then reviewed for the test on the cardiovascular and respiratory systems by answering jeopardy-like questions (Bio Challenge Review), which is also stored as an Excel file on the P drive.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(362, 'We began class today by solving the following problem: A block is being dragged up a 20&deg; incline by a rope that acts at an angle of 15&deg; to the incline''s surface.  If 10 Newtons of force pulled the block a distance of 8 meters, how much work was accomplished?  We then checked to make sure that our equation sheets had all of the necessary formulas listed on them.  We reviewed some basic information about work, energy and power through a rapid-fire review and then played a competitive review &quot;game&quot;.\r<br />\r<br />Test is tomorrow.  Don''t forget to bring your portfolio.\r<br />', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(363, 'We began class to day by completing 2 different matching actvities to review the cardiovascular system.  These activities can be found at the following url''s: www.quia.com/jg/54523.html and www.quia.com/mc/251094.html.  We discussed 3 different models of blood vessels and ways to improve them so they were more accurate.  We then played a competitive review &quot;game&quot;.  Test tomorrow.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. Per requests, I posted some animations in Shared Content for review.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(364, 'Today, we took a test to show off how much we know about energy, work and power.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend and see you Monday.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(365, 'Today, we got our creative juices flowing while taking a test that showed off how much we know about the cardiovascular and respiratory systems. One day you''ll look back fondly on this experience and smile (or not, it really doesn''t matter).  Regardless, it could always be worse...just wait until the next test.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend and see you Monday.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(366, 'Bienvenue au site tout le monde.  J''esp&egrave;re que vous allez profiter de toutes les ressources que j''ai ajout&eacute;es ici pour vous aider &agrave; perfectionner votre fran&ccedil;ais.', 2125, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(367, 'Our warm-up question today was as follows: Read the statement below. 	\r<br />&quot;Examine, evaluate, question, and ethically use information from a variety of sources and media to investigate energy conservation and loss.&quot;\r<br />Explain what this statement means using your own words.\r<br />\r<br />After discussing different interpretations of this statement, we talked about the next project, which will entail creating a brief animated video to address the learning benchmark above.  We used the rest of the period to familiarze ourselves with the software program at xtranormal.com.  We will use this program to create the video for this project.\r<br />\r<br />CSAP and ACT academy will be held tomorrow through Thurs, so I guess I will see you Fri.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(368, 'Our warm-up question today was: What is an infectious disease?  \r<br />We discussed responses to this questions, cited some examples of infectious diseases and highlighted some diseases that have been in the spotlight during the last few years.  We watched a brief introductory video on infectious disease and then used the rest of the period to complete Mission 1 of Rice''s MedMyst game (medmyst.rice.edu) to familiarize ourselves with some key vocabulary terms pertaining to infectious diseases.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy the rest of your week and see you Fri.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(369, 'heeey!', 2379, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(370, 'heeey', 2369, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(371, 'Today''s (rhetorical) warm up question was &quot;When are your IA''s due?  How long do you have before they are due?&quot;  (I wanted to make sure everyone understood the importance of turning these in on time.)  I handed back G4 reflections and the internal transport/gas exchange exams and we talked about how they were scored.  I also handed out the text for our next chinwag and the notes and Biozone assignment for the current unit (Defense against infectious disease).  We spent the remaining classt time cleaning the Bio storeroom (the aftermath of IA activity resulted in a substantial mess).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(372, 'Today''s warm-up question was &quot;What questions do you have about registering for science classes next year?&quot;  We talked a little about next year and then I handed back the Energy, Work and Power tests.  We discussed the answers, talked about next week''s plans and the date for the test retake (next Fri.).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(373, 'La semaine de rel&acirc;che!!  Woot woot!  N''oubliez pas d''&eacute;couter la radio, de regarder des vid&eacute;os et de lire!!', 2125, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(374, 'http://www.kidsastronomy.com/solar_system.htm\r<br />\r<br />http://darkskyinstitute.org/astronomy.html\r<br />\r<br />astronomy websites', 2332, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(375, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;Explain why it is important to understand basic facts before you can critically think about a topc.&quot;  We established that basic knowledge is essential for understanding any concepts, and then discussed how an understanding of basic physics vocabulary is essential for performing well on the test.  We then spent the rest of the period taking 2-column notes (What I heard and saw/Questions I have) from the energy and work videos I posted in Shared Content.  We also worked on completing the energy and work vocabulary activity and Work (8.1) and Power (8.2) worksheets using the Excel spreadsheet &quot;Energy, Work and Power&quot;, which is also posted in Shared Content.\r<br />\r<br />Anyone who scored lower than a 71% MUST retake this test on Fri (I know you are capable of doing better).  Anyone who scored higher than a 71% may retake the test (it is optional), but highly recommended if the score you earned is below an 80%.  Remember, your grade is usually a reflection of the time and effort you invested in learning a concept.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(376, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What types of technology do you use to learn and/or complete your academic projects (disregarding Microsoft Office, Google docs, the &quot;internet&quot;, Facebook and Skype)?&quot;  A couple students shared some digital resources and I posted links to these, along with some others I recommend, in the Technology Tools folder in Shared Content.  We then discussed the next project (SpicyNodes vocab nodemap), which is due April 22nd.  I bookmarked a link to the SpicyNodes website and posted the assignment description and project rubric in Shared Content.  We used the remaining time to work on reading the text for tomorrow''s chinwag OR taking notes on our current topic (Defense against infectious disease, which should be topics 6.3 and 11.1).  Please note that the notes and Biozone worksheets are due the Tues. after spring break.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(377, 'When students arrived to class today, they picked up a handout that described the Energy Multimedia Project.  Students read the assignment description, including the rubric, and then wrote down clarifying questions they had about the project.  After discussing some of those questions, I discussed the TED website (a good place to being searching for topics) and demonstrated how to complete the note holder for this project.  We also looked at the deadlines for each piece of the project (note holder, storyboard, animation).  Students then worked on either their project or used the resources available to continue reviewing for Fri''s test retake.  All of the review material and project information is posted in Shared Content.  Deadlines for the project are listed in the class Calendar.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(378, 'Upon arriving to class, students titled a blank piece of paper &quot;Plague Proportions&quot; and then read a protocol for today''s chinwag (Teammates Consult).  I then opened the floor to address any clarifying questions about the procedure, of which there were none.  We spent the rest of the period discussing and writing answers to various questions about the article.  We will continue this activity tomorrow.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. During class, I did bring attention to the class calendar, which was recently updated to reflect events and due dates through May, and the fact that I posted notes and Biozone assignments for the remaining units in Shared Content in case anyone wanted to begin working on some of those assignments early.  You will have one more extended project due before exams, so please try to manage your time effectively to avoid unnecesssary stress or anxiety.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(379, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: I heard recently that “shame is our immune system against evil”.  Do you agree or disagree with this metaphor?  Why?  After giving some context about the statement, we dicussed several different perspectives of this statement.  We then reviewed possible answers to the chinwag questions that we worked on Tues. and Weds.  I then asked &quot;If you had 50 billion dollars, which of the world''s problems would you attempt to solve first and why?&quot;  We finished the period by watching a video where an economist, Bjorn Lomborg, discussed this very question from an economics perspective.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(380, 'Today we continued working on either the (1) NRG multimedia project OR (2) preparing for Friday''s test retake on energy, work and power.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(381, '<br />Today we continued our discussion around the &quot;DNA Detectives&quot; chapter &quot;Plague Proportions&quot;. \r<br />\r<br />Misc. Announcements \r<br />1) SL students can omit the terms &quot;clade&quot; and &quot;cladistics&quot; from the Spicy Nodes project. \r<br />2) Please check out the &quot;Immune Response&quot; and &quot;Immune System&quot; resources I posted in Shared Content. These are exceptional resources for taking notes and gaining a better understanding of the immune system. \r<br />3) Don''t forget to post your questions about this topic in the Class Forum as your input wil drive instruction (discussions and future activities).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(382, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What, exactly, is a storyboard?&quot;  We discussed responses to this question, looked at examples of storyboards and then talked about the criteria that make up a good storyboard.  Please note that I bookmarked 2 different websites if you would like more information about storyboards (see Shared Content).  I talked about the Opposing Viewpoints resource provided through our library, which is a great database for finding conflicing viewpoints on topics and, therefore, for completing your note holder for the energy multimedia project (see THS home page, go to libraries, Databases, Gale and you''ll see a yin yang symbol for the Opposing Viewpoints Resource Center).  We used the rest of the period to work on the (1) NRG multimedia project (note holder and/or storyboard) OR studying for tomorrow''s test retake on energy, work and power.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(383, 'Would anyone be interested in going to The Scientific Education and Research Institute on April 12th for a cadaver lab?  This may be a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for some of you and a great way to contextualize what we''ve been learning in class.  The cost is $15.  We will walk to the institute from school and will have an opportunity to use surgical tools to dissect a human torso, foot and spinal cord.  I need a head count of those interested ASAP.  I''ve bookmarked the site (SERI Bioskills Cadaver Lab) in Shared Content if you would like more information.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(384, 'Today, we had an opportunity to re-take the energy, work and power test.  If you did not come to school today, you can make up the test the Mon. or Tues. after spring break either before school, during period 5, or after school (Mon. only).  No other times will be available.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your break!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(385, 'Today''s warm up was to consider a series of questions regarding the Bjorn Lomborg video we watched at the end of class yesterday (e.g. Did you agree w/ Bjorn?  Why or why not?  What are the advantages and disadvantages of the economics approach for prioritizing solutions to global problems? What biases may Bjorn have?  What biases may you have?)  We discussed some people''s responses and then I highlighted that, regardless of your agreement status with Bjorn and the Copenhagen Consensus, 2 of the 4 global problems identified as being high priority were infectious diseases and the number 1 problem was HIV/AIDS.\r<br />\r<br />We then explored treatment strategies for HIV/AIDS and how natural selection can affect the treatment strategies for viral infections.  We accomplished this by reading some brief articles and completing a phylogeny from some data to examine how HIV can mutate in a single person during the course of an infection.  We then applied this knowledge to treatment strategies.\r<br />\r<br />To understand what it is like to be taking an antiretroviral therapy for HIV and to determine if some treatment strategies are easier than others, everyone received one of three drug regimens with &quot;medicine&quot; to take during the next 10 days.  Please be sure to log your fidelity to the treatment plan and we will discuss adherence to each treatment after break.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy the time off and don''t forget that your notes on Topics 6.3 and 11.1 are due the Tues. after we return.  Also note that I posted resources in Shared Content to help you with this assignment.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. I will plan on 20 people going on the SERI field trip April 12th (see below).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(386, 'bonjour Monsiuer, how do i fing the calendar that tells me when all of the tests are?', 2371, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(387, 'dear Mr kern this is me amber Jaime from your 4 period class n i was hoping when we get back to school on Monday if you wont mine helping me on the project that we are doing i did some or well most of it but i am kind stuck n don''t know where to find eny more info about the energy efficient vehicles so if u can help me that would be a big help.', 2402, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(388, 'Amber,\r<br />\r<br />I''d be happy to help you with the project when I see you.  Feel free to come in outside of class as well.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(389, 'Welcome back!\r<br />\r<br />The warm-up question today was to look at the upcoming due dates for the energy project and to write down any questions you had about those dates.  After reviewing the required number of sources (4) and types of media (3), we continued working on the note holder for the project that lists the arguments and counterarguments for the claim we made about enery conservation.  This note holder was turned in at the end of class (it was due today).  We''ll continue working on the project this week.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(390, 'Welcome back!\r<br />\r<br />Today, I used the questions/comments people had posted in the Class Forum to guide our discussion.  We talked about blood clottting (topic 11.1), the principle of challenge and response, clonal selection and memory cells as the basis of immunity (11.1.2) and antibody production (11.1.4).  This material is challenging and will take some dedicated study, review and practice to understand and remember.  If you have any clarifying questions, please use the websites I posted in Shared Content, each other and myself as resources.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(391, 'Today we began by considering the following question: As outlined in the project description, your animation MUST include an &quot;ethical&quot; use of information; but, what exactly is &quot;ethics&quot;?  We talked about the meaning of ethics, compared ethics to morality and then talked about what an &quot;ethical use of information&quot; may look like for the project.  After answering some project-related questions, we then used the rest of the class period to complete the project storyboards, which were due today, and to start constructing the animation, which is due Tues (4/5/11).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08');
INSERT INTO `class_wall` (`comment_id`, `body`, `userID`, `level`, `classID`, `schoolID`, `date_posted`) VALUES
(392, 'We began class today by discussing responses to the question &quot;How do HIV drugs work?&quot;  We compared antivirals to antibiotics, looked at a table describing classes of antiretroviral drugs, how those drugs worked and the classes to which our &quot;drugs&quot; belonged.  We then watched an animation of the HIV life cycle to review and gain a better understanding of how these drugs work.  We then used the rest of the period to finish calculating the cost of each drug treament (protcols 1, 2 and 3) and reflect on other factors that might influence adherence to drug treatment plans.  \r<br />\r<br />Please have your note holder about the AIDS claim completed by the beginning of class tomorrow.  Also, be prepared to present the arguments and your final conclusions.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(393, 'Today''s warm-up question was as follows: &quot;Which therapy do you think showed the BEST adherence among your classmates?  Why?&quot;  Note: All three protocols were posted for reference.  Some students shared their opinions and then we looked a graph that summarized the drug adherence results for our class.  We talked about the importance, and potential consequences, of not adhering to an antiviral drug regimen and brought up that cost may play a factor in adherence.  We then began to research the cost of each drug so that we could calculate the cost of each protocol and reflect on the role of money in treating HIV.  We will finish our research and calculations tomorrow during class.\r<br />\r<br />March 29, 2011\r<br />\r<br />Today you had a substitute teacher.  Students read articles to find arguments that supported and refuted a particular claim.  These arguments were recorded in a note holder along with a final position statement.  This note holder should be completed by the beginning of class on Fri. (4/1/11).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(394, 'As noted in class, the field trip to SERI for the human cadaver lab, was rescheduled for April 26th and the cost increased from $15 to $25, although the science department may be able to subsidize the cost and reduce it to $20.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(395, 'Today''s warm-up question was as follows: &quot;The American Physical Society, the largest organization of professional physicists in the U.S., recognized energy conservation and efficiency as a top national priority. Are you surprised by this? Why or why not?&quot;\r<br />\r<br />After discussing the question, which establishes the importance of the research project we are currently working on, we discussed questions the project is addressing and the organization for the storyboard. Students used the remainder of the period to work on their storyboards, which are due by the end of class tomorrow.\r<br />\r<br />March 29, 2011\r<br />\r<br />We had a substitute teacher today. Students worked on their storyboard for the energy conservation project.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(396, 'We worked on our animations for the Energy Multimedia Project all period.  Only 2 more class periods to work on them!\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(397, 'After turning in the cost analysis of the HIV drug treatments and responses to the reflection questions, we looked at a table that listed factors identified as affecting drug adherence.  I asked you to either choose a factor that surprised you or one that did not occur to you and then explain either why you were surprised by that factor or why you think this factor didn''t occur to you earlier.  Next, we broke off into groups to prepare and then present an HIV/AIDS claim, the arguments supporting and refuting that claim and the group''s final position.  Our last group will present on Mon.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(398, 'Like Fri., we worked on our animations all period.  These animations are due by the end of class tomorrow!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(399, 'why is class connect soo hard to figure out?!?!', 2285, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(400, 'i like pizza', 2289, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(401, 'Today we finished our animations during class so that they could be screened tomorrow during class.  Those of you who finished early either began or completed the project reflection.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(402, 'The period began by listening to our final group''s presentation about whether it is cost effective to continue pursuing the development of a vaccine for HIV. We then looked at a Gapminder graphic presentation and read an accompanying manuscript to learn more about the cause, transmission and social implications of HIV/AIDS. We finished the period by watching Kristen Ashburn''s presentation showing photos she took of AIDS victims in Africa. These resources are posted in shared content.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(403, 'Our warm-up question today was, &quot;What does it mean to say that we mount a polyclonal antibody attack on invading pathogens?&quot;  We followed this with a lecture/discussion about the production of monoclonal antibodies and their applications in diagnostics and treatments.  The presentation we viewed is posted in shared content.  We finished class by completing a semantic analysis grid to identify the components involved in non-specific immunity and specific immunity (both cell-mediated and antibody-mediated).  We then wrote a summary to compare each type of immunity.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(404, 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DuiQvPLWziQ&amp;feature=related\r<br />http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YyKvXX8iGE4&amp;NR=1&amp;feature=fvwp\r<br />Explanations for the seasons\r<br />', 2332, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(405, 'Today we enjoyed the first screenings of the animations made by your classmates about energy conservation and loss.  We also evaluated and provided feedback to the authors of those animations.  Overall, I was imressed with what I saw today and I look forward to seeing the rest of the animations tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(406, 'Today''s warm up was 1) Turn in your homework (the semantic analysis grid and summary) and 2) What questions do you have about the concepts we''ve discussed thus far?  After answering some questions, we then completed the semantic analysis grid as a class and students had the option to revise their responses.  After this, we graded pages from another student''s Biozone workbook and provided them with feedback about their answers.  We didn''t finish &quot;grading&quot; the workbook, but will continue on Fri. (ELISA lab tomorrow).\r<br />\r<br />P.S.  I also announced at the beginning of class that the tentative date for the immune system test will be next Thurs. and in order to take the test, a portfolio that includes notes for all the learning objectives, all completed Biozone worksheets and all of your completed assignments regarding the immune system MUST be turned in to me (preferably a day or two before the test).  This is to provide extra incentive for those of you who haven''t been completing these assignments and a way for me to ensure you have the resources available to be successful on the exams.  You''re welcome.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(407, 'Today, after swapping fluids, we used monoclonal antibodies in an ELISA test to diagnose who in the class was infected with HIV.  We''ll use the class results, which I''ll post tomorrow, to try and trace the spread of infection and identify the source(s).\r<br />\r<br />If you missed the lab today, come and see me ASAP and I will have you make up the experience through a virtual lab.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(408, 'We continued to watch everyone''s animations today during class.  When we are finished watching all of the animations, I will have you complete a brief reflection.  Then we will move on to our next topic (nuclear energy).  See you tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(409, 'wasssuuup yo?', 2394, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(410, 'Today, we watched a couple remaining animations in class and began working on a reflection for the animation project.  Remember, this reflection must be turned in before the grade for the animation project is entered into the gradebook.  After watching and evaluating these projects, we watched a brief presentation on nuclear energy to orientate ourselves with the next topic.  (This Prezi presentation is in Shared Content).  Since nuclear energy comes from atoms, we reviewed the structure of atoms by completing an internet tutorial about the components of an atom and completing a semantic analysis grid, which organized the characteristics of each atom, and a closed paragraph, which summarized the information within the tutorial.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend and see you on Monday.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(411, 'Today we recorded the results from our HIV transmission and ELISA lab.  On Mon., I would like you to turn in the following for the lab: 1) Claim of who was/were the original carrier(s) of HIV, 2) Your hypothesis (in graphic form) showing how HIV was transmitted throughout the class population, and 3)  the evidence supporting your claim &amp; hypothesis.\r<br />\r<br />After approximately 15 min., we then formed groups and acted out different immune events without talking.  Afterwards, we attempted to guess what concept each group was attempting to communicate.  Before leaving, everyone grabbed their Biozone books and an article for next Tuesday''s chinwag.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend and see you Mon.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. For those of you who missed the ELISA lab yesterday, I have a virtual lab posted for you in Molecular Workbench.  Please submit your lab report electronically when you finish.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(412, 'I''m up.... just added some flashcards to the Wordchamp site to help you study for Chapter 5.', 2125, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(413, 'Alexandra, to view the calendar, just click on FSF2D0B under &quot;My classes&quot;.  On the right hand side of the page you should see the icon for the calendar.', 2125, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(414, 'I''mmike and i think im are really cool', 2289, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(415, 'Heat and Temperature notes are not set to be visible to students', 2436, 1, 325, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(416, 'khf;hfieucbnsjkfnasfnsdjkbgfduigfy8awfw90fasfhsjkafhdajhf89we742398472304983238907777777eryowuroiwryo HEHEH YAAAH', 2023, 1, 326, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(417, 'o\r<br />- | -\r<br /> / \\', 1637, 1, 326, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(418, 'Today''s warm-up was to turn in your (1) animation project reflection and (2) semenatic analysis grid and closed paragraph from the online atom tutorial.  After this, we reviewed the structure of an atom (the source of nuclear energy).  First, we created accounts at ChemThink.com.  Then we completed the (a) atomic structure question set, (b) isotope tutorial and (c) isotope question set.  You must understand this basic information in order to understand the rest of nuclear physics.\r<br />\r<br />Note: Our code for ChemThink is 5986-1747-8241 and is good until 4/22/2011.  After that, you will need to ask me for a new code.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(419, 'We began today by reading an article about Maryland''s vaccine policy for students at public schools and writing a response to the question &quot;Do you agree with Maryland''s county officials?  Why or why not?&quot;  After sharing some opintoins, we then went on to the ethical dilemmas posed by this situation and rotated through 4 different stations to gather facts that would help in addressing the associated ethical questions, focusing mainly on the following:  Under what circumstances, if any, should a state grant exemptions to its school vaccination policy?.  We finished class by summarizing the main ideas of each station.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. Please turn in your HW for the HIV transmission and ELISA lab ASAP.  I''ve posted the class data in Shared Content.\r<br />\r<br />P.S.S. Discussion tomorrow on the articles you rec''d Fri.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(420, 'Today''s warm-up question was: Determine the number of 1) protons, 2) electrons and 3) neutrons for a neutral oxygen atom.  Hints: The atomic number of oxygen = 8; The atomic mass of oxygen = 16 amu.\r<br />\r<br />We discussed the answer to this problem, how the problem was solved, and then practiced another (similar) problem.  This is a skill you will need to show your understanding of radioactive decay.  Students then either worked on completing the tutorials and question sets (see yesterday''s post) or began the &quot;Peninsula of Nuclear Stability&quot; assignment.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(421, 'Today''s warm up was as follows: Are some reasons for wanting to opt out of vaccination more acceptable than others?  (e.g. Is refusing a vaccination b/c of fears about health risks as acceptable—or unacceptable—as refusing because of fears of needles?)  Why?  How do you make that distinction?\r<br />\r<br />Students shared their responses and then we watched an animation about vaccinations (see http://www.nhs.uk/Planners/vaccinations/Pages/sciencevaccinations.aspx).  Next, we looked at a simulation to understand the concept of herd (community) immunity (see http://science.education.nih.gov/supplements/nih1/diseases/activities/activity4-flash.htm\r<br />).  After discussing herd immunity, we watched the second animation on the web page previously posted.  In light of our new understanding of herd immunity, we then considered how fair it is for someone to benefit from the protective effect of community immunity if he or she has chosen not to assume any risks of vaccination.\r<br />\r<br />After this, we began our fishbowl discussion.  We''ll continue this discussion tomorrow, as we were only able to observe 1 group of fish.  The test on topics 6.3 and 11.1 will be moved to Monday, with all other due dates remaining the same.  Please try to turn in your completed portfolio before Monday. \r<br />', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(422, 'The warm-up question today was the same as yesterday''s, except the element was changd to chlorine, with an atomic number of 17 and an atomic mass of 36 amu.  We then worked on completing the ChemThink quizzes on atomic structure and isotopes and the &quot;Peninsula of Nuclear Stability&quot; assignment.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(423, 'The warm-up question today was something to the effect of &quot;What evidence suggests that someone has read and comprehended an article?&quot;  After debriefing, we then rotated through our remaining two groups for our fishbowl chinwag.  Great job today by the way.  The discussion flowed (didn''t require additional prompting), was focused, included specific references within the text, and several connections were explicitly made to both previous content and big ideas.  Kudos.\r<br />\r<br />P.S.  Our drama with SERI continues.  The organization that was going to provide us with a human cadaver lab on April 26th recently sent an email saying we could attend on the same date, but would need to go from 1:30 pm to 5 pm.  Are there still 20 interested people?  If so, please tell me or Mrs. Schreck ASAP so we can send back numbers.  Thanks.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(424, 'Monsieur, in the lexique, do we have to add the &quot;un, une, le etc..?&quot; Because when I go to alphabetize it, it alphabetizes based on that, not on the actual word itself. Is that ok?', 2384, 1, 340, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(425, 'April 15, 2011\r<br />\r<br />Today, you had a substitute teacher.  The warm-up question was &quot;What evidence will you leave class with today that will show Mr. Kern you were on-task and productive during class? &quot;  During class, students either finished the tutorials and the 2 quizzes/question sets (one on atomic structure and the other on isotopes) on the ChemThink website and/or completed the “Peninsula of Stability” assignment using the Phet simulation and/or completed vocab word cards for the following words: atomic number, atomic mass and isotope.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(426, 'Today''s warm up was to look at the list of classwork/homework we''ve completed during the last week.  Then answer the following: What do you still need to finish and when will you finish it?  *Note: There will be a quiz on this material Tues. (4/19/11).  We then discussed what &quot;stability&quot; means and used the &quot;Build an Atom&quot; Phet simulation to expore stabilities in atoms, while reviewing some essential vocabulary.  We looked at the &quot;peninsula of stability&quot; and then watched and discussed a brief video about the &quot;island of stability&quot;.  Before leaving, students completed an exit ticket describing their current comfort level with atomic structure.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend and see you Monday!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(427, 'April 13, 2011\r<br />\r<br />Today you had a substitute teacher.  As promised, you had a work day to study for your test on Monday, organize your portfolio, work on your notes for the next unit (Nerves, Muscles &amp; Movement; due Tues.), or work on your next Biozone assignment (also due next Tues.).', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(428, 'Hopefully everyone did well on their tests (in other classes) today.\r<br />\r<br />We began biology class today by completing a closed paragraph about immunity.  We reviewed the answers and then completed another closed paragraph about the causes and consequences of AIDS.  Students then had an opportunity to ask clarifying questions about the concepts in Topics 6.3 and 11.1.  After this, we moved on to the nervous system by constructing a model of the basic structural and functional unit of this system...the neuron.  Please show me when your models are complete so that I can record that into the gradebook.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend and see you Monday (test day).\r<br />\r<br />P.S. Don''t forget about the 2 immune system review games I posted in Shared Content.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(429, 'Unfortunately, our field trip to SERI has been cancelled.  Sorry.  I am as disappointed as you.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(430, 'Today, students had an opportunity to show off what they knew about the immune system (i.e. we took a test).  Woo hoo!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(431, 'The warm up today was &quot;What causes an atom to be ''unstable''?  What happens as a result of this instability?&quot;  We discussed this question and then reviewed the material from last week.  We then watched a brief video about radiation and talked about the sources of radiation, if we should be concerned with our exposure to radiation, where the radiation in our food comes from and how radiation is measured.  After this, students began analyzing a radiation dose chart to explore the everyday sources of radiation, compare the amounts of radiation absorbed from different sources and the effects of this radiation.  We''ll continue this tomorrow after the quiz.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(432, 'Today''s warm up was &quot;What questions do you have about atomic structure before we take the quiz?&quot;  As a class, we answered clarifying questions as a mini-review for the quiz and then took the quiz on atomic structure.  After finishing the quiz, students worked on the radiation dose chart assignment we began yesterday.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(433, 'Today''s warm-up question was to sketch a neuron and label ea. of the following parts: axon, axon (synaptic) terminal, cell body, and dendrite.  Jimena drew her response on the board.  Then, we used the University of Colorado''s Phet simulation to gain a better understanding of the events that occur when a nerve impulse travels along a non-myelinated nerve.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(434, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What, do you think, was the take-away message from the ''Radiation Dose Chart'' activity?&quot;  After walking through the &quot;Radioactive Dating Game&quot; Phet simulation, we began using this simulation to begin understanding the concepts of radioactive decay and half life.  We''ll continue this activity tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(435, 'After greeting someone we usually don''t acknowledge, we reviewed the answers to the immune test.  Then, we watched and discussed a couple animations about nerve impulse transmission.  We''ll discuss this more tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(436, 'At the beginning of class today, I handed back the quiz we took on Tuesday.  The warm up was to look over the questions you missed and prepare to ask questions about what you are still struggling to understand.  I reviewed the correct answers to the quiz, which are also posted in Shared Content) and discussed strategies for answering future questions.  We then worked on completing the radioactive decay simulations on the computer.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(437, 'The warm up today was to complete a cross word puzzle to review nervous system vocabulary.  We watched the brief animation that we started yesterday, but did not finish (the one about how nerve impulses travel along an axon) and then used a kit of materials to model each stage of an action potential.  During the last few minutes of class, we attempted to act out the process of an action potential, using ourselves as channels and pumps, but eventually ran out of time.  We will continue our performance tomorrow.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(438, 'The warm-up question today was as follows: What is 1... (a) question you have about the simulation you worked with yesterday?  OR  (b) observation that you found interesting?  After discussing responses, I highlighted some important details about concepts from the simulation and we completed 2 more vocab cards for the words &quot;radioisotope&quot; and &quot;half life&quot;.  We watched a brief video explanining how carbon-14 forms and then began the second part of the simulation to understand how half-lives are used to date fossils and rocks.\r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend!', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(439, 'The warm-up question today was to take 2 rubrics for evaluating the SpicyNodes projects. Each student was then given the names of 2 students whose projects they must evaluate by Mon., May 2nd. We then modeled the process of an action potential using ourselves, small, colored &quot;beads&quot; and candy and then formed 3 separate nerves and raced. Next, we cut out cards describing events that occur during an action potential and, in partners, arranged those cards into the correct sequence. Finally, we watched an animation from Harvard (see &quot;Action Potential Extended Tutorial&quot; in shared content) that shows what happens during synaptic transmission. Everyone received a handout (&quot;8 squares synaptic transmission&quot;) describing those events and then we folded those papers into 8 squares. The homework, which is due this coming Mon., was to illustrate each event in the appropriate square. \r<br />\r<br />Have a great weekend!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(440, 'We began class today by completing a &quot;Radiometic Dating of Fossils&quot; worksheet.  The purpose of this activity was to review and visualize how the amount of a radioactive substance changes over time.  We discussed the answers and then continued working on the &quot;Radioactive Decay and Dating - Day 2&quot; activity using the Phet simulation.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(441, 'We began class today by 1) turning in the 8-square illustrations of synaptic transmission (homework from Fri.) and 2) writing questions about the process of synaptic transmission.  I answered some questions about this process and then we compared the movement of the elbow, knee and hip joints and how antagonistic muscles are used for each movement.  We then focused more on the elbow by identifying the structures associated with this joint (specific bones, muscles, etc.) and dissecting a chicken wing, which is analogous in structure to the human elbow.  We''ll talk more about the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction tomorrow.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. Review session has been moved from today to Thurs. at 3:30 pm, per request of the majority.  \r<br />\r<br />P.S.S. I also handed out some diagrams as notes to help you understand the hierarchical arrangement of muscles and the structures you need to identify for the human reproduction system.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(442, 'The warm-up question today was to look at a picture of 3 different lithium atoms and then answer the following questions: (1) What is the name for the different types of lithium atoms being shown? and (2) Explain why the top number (atomic mass) is different for each atom, but the bottom number (atomic number) stays the same.  We discussed the answer and then I talked about what is meant by a &quot;parent&quot; isotope and &quot;daughter&quot; elements.  We then used the rest of the peroid to complete the vocab word cards, simulation activities or a brief lab that required you to sketch a decay curve on graph paper and use that decay curve to date 8 different objects (models) that contained samples of a radioisotope.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(443, 'Today''s warm-up question was to (1) take any of the coloring guides on the back table that interest you and to (2) describe (a) what was occuring in the looping animation being shown, (b) where it happens and (c) why it happens.  (Incidentally, the animation was of a sodium-potassium pump actively transporting potassium and sodium into and out of the axon of a neuron to restore that neuron''s resting potential).  We then watched an animation about the neuromuscular junction to understand how an action potential in a nerve stimulates the contraction of a muscle, noting that the process was very similar to the synaptic transmission we looked at previously, but acetylcholine was the specific neurotransmitter involved.  Next, we watched a series of animations to visualize the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction and concluded with an informal quiz on what we watched.  For homework, I recommend cutting out the events of muscle contraction on the heavyweight handout and placing them into the correct sequence (that is, the order they occur during muscle contraction).  If you bring these by Thurs., I can check them.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(444, 'Today, we reviewed for tomorrow''s quiz on radioactive decay and radiometric dating by using the clickers to respond to questions.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(445, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;What questions do you have about muscles or the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction?&quot;  After clarifying some questions, we used the laptop computers to review the structures of the human reproductive system and the hormones involved in menstruation.  This Excel spreadsheet can be found in Shared Content.\r<br />\r<br />P.S. The class decided to move the semester final to May 9th.  Failure to take this exam will result in a failing grade for the semester.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(446, 'Today we watched the first 5 chapters of &quot;Life''s Greatest Miracle&quot; and wrote brief summaries highlighting the key points discussed in the video.  The purpose of watching this video is to learn more about the process of human reproduction including gamete formation, fertilization, development and birth, as well as to review concepts such as gene structure and meiosis.  I posted a link to this website in shared content, but we will watch the remaining chapters on Mon.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(447, 'We took a quiz today on radioactive decay and radiometric dating.  We also graded the quiz so people knew how well they did before leaving for the weekend.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy the days off and see you Mon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(448, 'Unfortunately, I was not in class this past Mon. or Tues.  From my understanding, everyone was at testing on Tues.  On Mon., the substitute teacher finished screening &quot;Life''s Greatest Miracle&quot; and had you finish writing your chapter summaries.  After this, you should have watched a 3D animation of the process of in vitro fertilization and then wrote responses to questions about the ethical implications of this procedure (&quot;Attitudes on IVF&quot;).  I will post this in shared content in case you missed class that day as well.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(449, 'Unfortunately, I was absent Mon. and Tues. (May 2, 2011 and May 3, 2011).\r<br />\r<br />On Mon., students should have watched the video &quot;Zero Hour: Disaster at Chernobyl&quot; and wrote responses to questions on a related viewing guide.  The purpose of watching this video was to gain an appreciation and understanding for the amount of energy that is available from nuclear energy.  Chernobyl is still regarded as the worst nuclear accident in history, but the Fukishima power plant in Japan is rated as the second worst nuclear disaster. \r<br />\r<br />On Tues., students should have completed the Alpha and Beta decay activity (posted on the P drive) using the Phet simulations.  The purpose of this activity was for you to begin understanding what exactly happens when a radioisotope decays to become more stable (specifically, how and why the nucleus of the atoms change to produce energy).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(450, 'Today''s warm-up was &quot;Describe something you learned about alpha and beta decay from completing yesterday''s activity.&quot;  For students who were absent the previous day, I showed the alpha decay simulation to show this decay process.  We discussed observations that were recorded and I highlighted key vocabulary terms, how and why the atomic mass of the radioisotope changed during alpha decay, the types of radiation that are given off during alpha decay, and the components of an alpha particle.  We then wrote a few notes about alpha decay and used dry-erase boards to practice writing nuclear equations that show this process.  Next, we began discussing and writing a few notes about beta decay.  We''ll practice writing nuclear equations to show this process tomorrow and talk about gamma decay as well.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(451, 'We began class today by writing the nuclear equation for an alpha decay of bismuth-213.  We then reviewed how to write alpha decay equations, the concept of beta decay and how to write nuclear equations showing beta decay.  We used dry-erase boards to practice writing beta decay equations and then wrote a few notes to explain gamma decay.  Next, we completed a table comparing the 3 types of radiation (alpha, beta and gamma) and discussed why these types of radiation are relevant to our lives.  At the end of the period, we continued to practice reading and writing nuclear decay equations by completing a worksheet, which you will have time to finish tomorrow.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(452, 'When students came to class today, they took a couple of crossword puzzles and either n SL or HL test to help them review.  I made a few miscellaneous announcements (pay your $20 for Biozone so you can graduate, turn in your textbooks after the test, take a study guide if you so desire and will return it with your book, Ms. Burns will offer study sessions today and tomorrow from 3:15 - 4:15 pm).  We then broke off into groups and played a review game that was riddled with too many typos.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(453, 'Today'' s warm up was to take last year''s papers 1 and 2 exams.  The rest of the period was spent reviewing in small groups using the exams and resources in the Review folder.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(454, 'The warm-up question today was &quot;Predict the meaning of the word ''transmutation''&quot;.  We used the period to complete the nuclear decay equations worksheet we began yesterday.  Students also received an article (Discovery of Radioactivity) and anticipation guide to complete as homework.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(455, 'Today, we took our final exam.  Woohoo!', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(456, 'Today''s warm up was &quot;Please turn in your homework (anticipation guide from article &quot;Discovery of Radioactivity&quot;).  I highlighted the fact we have a quiz tomorrow on comparing the 3 types of radiation and writing nuclear equations and reviewed the checklist of items that should be in your portfolio.  We then began learning about nuclear fission using another Phet simulation.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(457, 'We began class today by describing the process of nuclear fission either based on hte simulation we used yesterday or the animation I projected.  We discussed this process and then watched a brief video to answer the following questions: (1) What is the principal (main) element used in nuclear fission? What special property does it have?, (2)  How are the products of nuclear fission transformed into household energy, such as electricity?, and (3)\r<br />Why, do you think, nuclear power is a controversial NRG source?  We discussed these answers at the end of the video, talked about the process of &quot;enrichment&quot; and looked at the nuclear equations that describe fission.  We finished the period by taking a quiz on radioactive decay and nuclear equations.  \r<br />', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(458, 'Congratulations!!!  See you at graduation.', 70, 1, 263, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(459, 'Today''s warm up was to say something nice to a senior (it was their last day of high school).  Seniors then took their final exam, while all other students worked on an assignment (&quot;What''s a Nuclear Meltdown?&quot;) to explain the events that occur during a nuclear meltdown and compare the nuclear accidents at Chernobyl and Fukushima.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(460, 'Today, we watched a brief BrainPOP video reviewing what we have learned about radioactivity and radiation.  We then reviewed the correct answers to the nuclear decay and equations quiz and identified important parts of a nuclear reactor and discussed their functions.  During the remaining time, we worked on completing yesterday''s assignment (&quot;What''s a Nuclear Meltdown?&quot;).', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(461, 'We warmed up our science thinking today with the following question: &quot;What, exactly, is a ''chain reaction''?  Describe an examle of a chain reaction (other than nuclear fission).&quot;  We discussed responses to the question and then watched 3 different video clips that illustrated chain reactions.  We linked this to what happens in fission reactions, defined the terms &quot;subcritical&quot;, &quot;critical&quot;, and &quot;supercritical&quot; and then tied those terms to fission reactions.  We discussed the consequences of detonating nuclear weapons and waste issues associated with nuclear power plants.  We then transitioned into talking about nuclear fusion and watched a couple of short videos explaining this process and why this particular nuclear reaction is important in our daily lives.\r<br />\r<br />Enjoy your weekend and see you Mon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(462, 'The warm-up question today asked you to explain how nuclear reactions have always warmed the Earth from the outside AND the inside.  We then reviewed the processes of nuclear fission and nuclear fusion, described how Einstein contributed to nuclear physics, and watched two brief video clips.  One clip explained the concept of the fusion (hydrogen/supe-) bomb and the other described the first test of this technology.  We then compared fission and fusion and practiced identifying and completing equations for fission and fusion reactions.  \r<br />\r<br />P.S. Quiz on nuclear reactions has been moved to Weds. and test on nuclear energy has been moved to Fri.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(463, 'At the beginning of class, I projected a visual instruction plan (V.I.P.) for helping you to solve nuclear equations.  The question I asked you about this V.I.P. was &quot;What are the strengths of this step-by-step procedure for solving nuclear equations?&quot;  and &quot;How might this V.I.P. be improved?&quot;  After discussing this strategy, we practiced completing both nuclear fission and nuclear fusion equations using dry erase boards.  Before leaving class, everyone received a brief article to read and note holder to complete about nuclear and chemical reactions.  The purpose of reading and completing the note holder is to compare both nuclear and chemical reactions, which will be a question on tomorrow''s quiz.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(464, 'We warmed up our scientific thinking today by comparing nuclear and chemical reactions, using examples of each type of reaction.  We discussed the differences and then 1st and 8th period took a quiz on nuclear reactions.  Period 4''s quiz was delayed until tomorrow, so they worked on either organizing their portfolio or familiarizing themselves with the SpicyNodes program, which we will use for the final project.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(465, 'Today''s warm up was &quot;What is your weakest area of knowledge regarding nuclear physics?  How do you plan to work on this area to improve?&quot;  Today was spent doing what we did yesterday (see yesterday''s posting).  \r<br />\r<br />P.S. We moved the portfolio due date and test to Mon. for everyone!  Woo hoo.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(466, 'Today, everyone received the 3 questions for the portfolio reflection, which is the last component of your portfolio on the checklist.  After answering questions about the reflection, we used the period to either 1) work on the portfolio or 2) complete the nodemap.\r<br />\r<br />Make sure to complete your portfolio and study for the test this weekend.  See you Mon.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(467, 'The warm-up today was two-fold.  (1) Please turn in your portfolio.  (2) What quetions do you have about nuclear physics before you take today''s test?\r<br />\r<br />We took the test on nuclear energy today and, when finished, worked either on completing the SpicyNodes nodemap OR preparing for the semester exam later this week.  Tomorrow you will also have time during class to work on either of these assignments.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(468, 'mr. Kern!! whats the difference between scalar and vector quantity?', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(469, 'nevermind Mr. ! I got it :)', 1355, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(470, 'At the beginning of class, I gave everyone a rubric that will be used to assess your final exam (essay question).  I answered questions about the exam and rubric and handed back tests and portfolios from yesterda.  For the rest of the period, we worked on either 1) preparing for the final exam or 2) completing the SpicyNodes project.', 70, 1, 261, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08'),
(471, 'when are we able to check answers on our ferp? can you put an answer key in the shared content folder?\r<br />', 1785, 1, 239, 0, '2011-06-10 23:58:08');
