(8, 6, 32, 13, 'How To Use The Pythagorean Theorum', '<p>In <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</a>, the <b>Pythagorean theorem</b> (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_English" title="American English">American English</a>) or <b>Pythagoras'' theorem</b> (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_English" title="British English">British English</a>) is a relation in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title="Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> among the three sides of a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle#Types_of_triangles" title="Triangle">right triangle</a>. The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theorem" title="Theorem">theorem</a> is usually written as an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equation" title="Equation">equation</a>:</p>\r\n<dl><dd><img class="tex" alt="a^2 + b^2 = c^2\\!\\," src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/4/5/1455314a78f39a594485adbaf74d63f9.png"></dd></dl>\r\n<p>where <i>c</i> represents the length of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypotenuse" title="Hypotenuse">hypotenuse</a>, and <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> represent the lengths of the other two sides. In words:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><i>The square of the hypotenuse of a right triangle is equal to the sum of the squares on the other two sides</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>The Pythagorean theorem is named after the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greeks" title="Greeks">Greek</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician" title="Mathematician">mathematician</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title="Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a>, who by tradition is credited with its discovery and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title="Mathematical proof">proof</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Heath.2C_Vol_I.2C_p._144_1-0" class="reference"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem#cite_note-Heath.2C_Vol_I.2C_p._144-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> although it is often argued that knowledge of the theory predates him. (There is much evidence that <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Babylonian_mathematics" title="Babylonian mathematics">Babylonian mathematicians</a> understood the principle, if not the mathematical significance).</p>', '', '', '', '', '2009-04-05 16:32:21'),
