(621, 279, 51, 0, '<P><BR>1.) Understanding plasma is important because when solar flares erupt, massive ejections of plasma can wipe out satellite systems and bring down power grids. Plasmas also offer clues to the workings of stars. </P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>2.)Mr. Watts is building a machine that is more than 18 feet that will hopefully help illuminate underlying solar flares. Mr. Gekelman&nbsp;built a machine that is 22 meters long that can produce a continuous volume of plasma about 56 feet long.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>3.)Understanding solar flares is important because when solar flares erupt, charged particles are &nbsp;flung out into space where they form the solar wind, then&nbsp;particles are flung back toward the Earth,&nbsp; and the solar wind distorts the magnetic field surrounding Earth.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>4.)When fossil fuels are depleted, one&nbsp;thing that might happen&nbsp;for large scale power production is nuclear fusion.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>5.) Yes, improving plasma knowledge is necessary because plasmas&nbsp;can also play a central role in meeting future energy needs, lightning is a plasma, and plasmas offer clues to the workings of stars. Plasmas impact everybody\\''s lives, whether they know it or not. If people had more knowledge and a better understanding of plasma, then we\\''ll be able to know how to protect ourselves from satellite wipe outs, etc. and maybe even predict when it might happen.</P><BR>', '2009-09-29 17:44:33'),
