(681, 354, 49, 0, '1. Plasma is important to the communications field because if a solar\r\nwind happened, it could wipe out a power grid, knock out satellites,\r\nand leave many people powerless. If we could predict when and how solar\r\nflare works, we could easily avoid a lot of this power failures.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n2. Mr. Gekelman and Watts both created machines to make plasma. Mr. Gekelman made a machine to capture Alven waves and watts wanted to know more about plasma.<br><br>3. If we could gain more information about solar flares, we could prevent future problems with our satellites and power grids.<br><br>4. Once our fossil fuels are depleted, the idea of nuclear fusion comes into play making it clean and easier to get energy.<br><br>5. I believe that improving plasma knowledge is definitely a necessity. It could help us understand how solar flares work and eventually give us a new cleaner power source compared to fossil fuels.<br>', '2009-10-04 19:31:44'),
(682, 331, 51, 0, '1. Understanding plasma is important in the communications field, because when solar flares erupt ejections of plasma can wipe our satellite systems and bring down power grids.  They would like to predict the eruptions to protect their items.<div>2. They have made machines to help illuminate the mechanisms about plasmas.  Gekelman\\''s machine being slightly larger then Mr. Watts, but both being for the same purpose.</div><div>3. Solar flares are important because when solar flares erupt charged particles are flung into space causing a solar wind, which when it rushes past the Earth, it distorts our magnetic field.</div><div>4.  If scientists are able to understand plasmas and how they work, there could be large scale fusion power plants to replace the fossil fuel energy.</div><div>5. Yes, I believe that improved plasma knowledge is necessary.  There is a possibility that eventually our fossil fuels will run out, what will we do to get our energy then? Understanding plasmas and nuclear fusion is the key.  Scientists have already begun developing machines to observe plasmas, and have already learned many things about this strange state of matter.  Why not keep up the research?  The effect of plasma could greatly help our economy and impact many lives.  If there is a will, there is a way.</div>', '2009-10-04 20:01:31'),
(683, 332, 51, 0, '1. when solar flares erupt, massive &nbsp;ejections of plasma known as solar wind can wipe out satellite systems. <br><br>2. Watts has been building a machine that he hopes will illuminate the underlying solar flares. Mr. Gekelman is trying to build a bigger and better machine than Mr. Watts.<br><br>3. it is important to understand because people can predict when the next solar flare will come making it easier to be able to be protected from it.<br><br>4. Plasma fuel is used frequently, and when normal gas is gone, plasma can be used to replace it.<br><br>5.Plasma is important because it makes up the stars and if we want to travel to them one day we need to understand them.<br>', '2009-10-04 20:21:40'),
(684, 382, 47, 0, '<P><BR>1. The understanding of plasma is important because when solar flares erupt, massive ejections of plasma can wipe out satellite systems and bring down power grids.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>2. The contributions&nbsp;that Mr. Watts and Mr.&nbsp;Gekelman&nbsp;made were building machines to understand plasma better.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>3. Understanding solar flares is important because if we understood them, then we could avoid the problems that they cause.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>4. When fossil fuels are depleted, plasma will probably be the next energy source.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>5. Well, plasma could save us money in the future and it could be our next big energy source so in my opinion improved plasma knowledge would be necessary.</P>', '2009-10-04 20:24:07'),
(685, 318, 47, 0, '<P><BR>1. Understanding plasma is important because when solar flares erupt, massive ejections of plasma known as the solar wind can wipe out satellite systems and bring down power grids.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>2. The contributions&nbsp;that Mr. Watts and Mr.&nbsp;Gekelman&nbsp;made were building machines to understand plasma better.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>3. The understanding of solar flares is important because if we understood them, then we could avoid any of the problems that might cause in the future.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>4. When fossil fuels are depleted, plasma&nbsp;could possibly&nbsp;be the next energy source.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>5. Yes, because it could be a valuable energy source and have knowledge to prevent problems it might cause.</P>', '2009-10-05 06:19:59'),
(686, 507, 54, 0, 'Cynthia Burrows of the University of Utah writes all about Chlorine. She feels that Chlorine is often looked over. Although it is used for many things such as photography, dietary hypertension, and even an antitumor drug called cisplatin, Cynthia feels that Chlorine is not given any credit for its role that it plays. Chlorine is found in the halogens section of the periodic table. Period 3 and Group 17. Chlorine right now is providing over 2 million people with jobs in the Chlorine Chemistry Council. As many do know it is not dangerous in normal quantities due to it being everywhere around you.&nbsp; It is produced by the electrolysis of seawater.', '2009-10-06 06:38:46'),
(687, 365, 56, 0, '<P align=center><FONT face=arial size=2>Nickel</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=arial size=2>1. David Hanson is the author, and he is writing this article to describe the benefits that nickel has brought us. </FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=arial size=2>2. Some of the uses of Nickel include: making stainless steel and many other corrosion-resistent alloys, used in rechargeable batteries, used in heating elements, and is used for making the coin which contains 25% nickel.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=arial size=2>3. The element is found in the section of transition metals on the periodic table, and it is found in row 4 group 10 and it is a metal.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2><FONT face=arial>4. Nickel was discovered in 1751 by Swedish chemist Axel F. Cronstedt in Niccolite. <FONT>As much as 70% of nickel goes to make stainless or other steel alloys. Nickel costs approximately $8,000.00 per ton. </FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2><FONT face=arial>5. There are several Nickel compounds that are dangerous and toxic if exposed to. <FONT>Another health issue is contact dermatitis from exposure to nickel. Reactions to nickel alloys in earrings used for pierced ears are the most frequent, but itchy rashes can occur on any body part that comes into prolonged contact with nickel.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=arial size=2>6. Found in the earth\\''s crust and believed to be more prevelant in the earth\\''s molten core.</FONT><BR><BR><BR></P>', '2009-10-06 08:15:04'),
(688, 297, 56, 0, '<BR>The essay was written by Judith Klinman on the element Hydrogen. Hydrogen is the first element on the periodic table, and it is also the lightest and most abundant of the elements. Klinman says that she is most interested in Hydrogen because of its two isotopes (Tritium and Deuterium), which were major contributing factors to the world of modern chemistry and biochemistry.&nbsp;Hydrogen is commonly used&nbsp;as an enzyme catalyst and in solution chemistry. This is the first element in the periodic&nbsp;table. It is found on row 1, group 1. It is normally found in the state of a Gas. Hydrogen is a non metal. Some interesting facts about Hydrogen are that it is the source of fuel for the stars, including our sun. This element is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities, it is actually quite harmless. This element is normally found in the air, and when combined with Oxygen in the form of H2O, it forms water.', '2009-10-06 08:28:36'),
(689, 297, 0, 688, 'Hydrogen', '2009-10-06 08:30:32'),
(690, 289, 56, 0, '<P><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT size=3>Magnesium</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;1. Gerald D. Cole wrote this essay and his interest is to explain and show how Magnesium has been useful to us.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2>&nbsp; 2.<FONT face=Arial>Magnesium\\''s first uses in flares, tracer bullets, incendiary bombs, fireworks, and flash photography were based on its significant chemical reactivity.</FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp; 3. Magnesium is in the alkiline earth metalssection and is in the 3rd row and 2nd group.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp; 4. Magnesium was <FONT face=Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular size=2>the influence of war that changed magnesium\\''s stature from a curiosity to an industrial material. And it was in Germany where the body of knowledge originated on how easily magnesium could be alloyed and formed. In fact, magnesium was referred to as \\"the German metal\\" well into the 20th century.</FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp; 5. Magnesium has valuable chemical uses: in reducing uranium and titanium from their ores, in eliminating sulfur from steel, and in producing high-strength cast iron. Magnesium oxides are also central to high-temperature refractories. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp; 6. Magnesium makes up about 2.5% of Earth\\''s surface. The element is concentrated in the minerals carnallite, magnesite, and dolomite.</P></FONT>', '2009-10-06 08:38:13'),
(691, 350, 56, 0, '<P align=center><BR><STRONG>Oxygen</STRONG></P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-06 08:44:17'),
(692, 250, 56, 0, '<P align=center>Aluminum</P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=verdana><FONT size=2>Gregory H. Robinson, a chemistry professor at the University of Georgia,&nbsp;wrote about the element Aluminum. Robinson is surprised by the inexpensive cost of an element that was once&nbsp;considered a&nbsp;\\"precious metal.\\" Also, Robinson is much intrigued by the perfect student-teacher&nbsp;relationship between Jewett and Hall. Aluminum can be found at the top of the Washington Monument. Aluminum is found in group 13, period 3. Aluminum is a solid at room temperature as is classified as a metal. Hans Christian Oersted was the first person to isolate Aluminum, but <FONT>Friedrich Wöhler was the first person to obtain a pure sample of Aluminum by using chemical reduction.Charles Hall and Paul Heroult are credited for allowing the use of Aluminum in an economical setting. Aluminum is not dangerous unless it is ingested. Aluminum is a naturally produced resource that is found in rocks. It is usually combined with silica and oxide.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=Verdana size=2></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=Verdana size=2>Elizabeth Grant</FONT></P>', '2009-10-06 08:44:33'),
(693, 342, 56, 0, '<BR>\r\n<P class=MsoNormal style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt\\"><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 14pt; mso-text-animation: sparkle\\"><FONT color=#000000><FONT face=\\"Times New Roman\\">CALCIUM<?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = \\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office\\" /><o:p></o:p></FONT></FONT></SPAN></P>\r\n<P class=MsoNormal style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt\\"><FONT color=#000000><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt\\"><FONT face=\\"Times New Roman\\">STURE FORSÉN.</FONT></SPAN><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial\\"> He became interested in Calcium when he had his graduate studies in1960s. He was involved with nucleic magnetic resonance sprectocopy of various nuclei. Calcium usually includes in milk, yogurt and etc products which helps your bones and teeth. The element found in the periodic table under alkaline earth metals, in 3<SUP>rd</SUP> row and 2<SUP>nd</SUP> group. Normally found in solid. It is metal. Calcium can be combined with other elements. No its not explosive. It is found in bones, milk and other products.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></FONT></P>', '2009-10-06 08:46:16'),
(694, 307, 56, 0, '<P align=center><STRONG><FONT face=georgia size=5>Silver</FONT></STRONG></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=georgia size=2><STRONG>1.</STRONG> The person who wrote this essay was Alan Shaw, and he was first drawn to the element\\''s \\"magic luster\\" when he was a child, standing in a British museum and gazing at a finely polished silver mirror. He claims that silver \\"represents true majesty among the elements\\", and that \\"if gold claims to be its king, silver must surely be its queen\\".</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT><FONT><FONT face=georgia><FONT size=2><STRONG>2.</STRONG> In the past, some of the uses of this element were to make swords or shields. Today, silver is u<FONT>sed to make photographic film, tooth filings, silverware, mirrors, batteries, photosensitive glass, and as an electrical conductor. Silver iodide is used for seeding clouds to produce rain.</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT><FONT face=georgia><FONT size=2><FONT><STRONG>3.</STRONG></FONT>&nbsp;The metal is&nbsp;found on the transition metal section of the periodic table in group 11 period 5. It is normally found in the solid state of matter.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=Georgia size=2><STRONG>4. </STRONG>In the 1800\\''s, babies who were fed with silver spoons were supposedly heatlhier than babies fed with spoons made of other metals. Silver pacifiers have had beneficial health effects, as well.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=Georgia size=2><STRONG>5. </STRONG>Silver is not very dangerous in normal exposure quantities.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=Georgia><FONT size=2><STRONG>6. </STRONG>Silver is <FONT face=georgia>normally found in<FONT> ores including argentite and horn silver and in conjunction with deposits of ores containing lead, copper, and gold.</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT><BR></P>', '2009-10-06 09:27:02'),
(695, 522, 57, 0, '<P>Hydrogen,</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>1. Judith Klinman, her interest is in the 2 long-lived isotopes.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>2. Used in the production of NH3, and to hydrogenate fats.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>3. It is the first element of the periodic table, Row 1, group 1.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>4.&nbsp;Has been created by scientists for years, but it was first recognized as an element in 1766, by&nbsp; Henry Cavendish.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>5. No</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>6. It was created by scientists.<BR></P>', '2009-10-06 09:32:49'),
(696, 485, 57, 0, '<P><FONT face=\\"comic sans ms\\" size=2>Carbon-</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"comic sans ms\\" size=2>1. George A. Olah, interested in carbocation</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2><FONT face=\\"comic sans ms\\">2. <FONT>Essential component of all organic molecules,&nbsp;used in graphite as lubricant, used as diamond as a abrasive, and carbon dioxide is used in refridgeration.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"Comic Sans MS\\" size=2>3. Period 2, family 14, nonmetal solid,</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"Comic Sans MS\\" size=2>4. If crushed with enormous force, can turn into diamond</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"Comic Sans MS\\" size=2>5. No, its safe in its regular state of matter&nbsp;by itself</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"Comic Sans MS\\" size=2>6. Found in diamonds and&nbsp;graphite</FONT></P>', '2009-10-06 09:35:40'),
(725, 124, 0, 721, 'Why?  do you miss me??  Ms. T', '2009-10-09 08:53:29'),
(698, 351, 54, 0, '<P><FONT size=2>Flourine</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=1>Nance Dicciani wrote an article about the element&nbsp;Flourine in which he&nbsp;discusses&nbsp;the many uses of Flourine. Flourine is used in dental products, air conditioning, and phamaceutical products. Flourine is the nineth element on the periodic table where it can be found in group seventeen and the second row. It is normally a gas and is a nonmetal. Flourine is the most reactive element and reacts with practically all substances. This element can be dangerous in normal exposure quantities. Flourine can be found in the Earth\\''s Crust. When flourine is combined with water it produces ozone.</FONT></P>', '2009-10-06 13:47:34'),
(699, 295, 57, 0, '<P align=center>Helium</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; My element is helium and Neil Bartlett wrote this article and his interest was about helium and what it does. Helium is used in balloons, blimps, and anything that floats in air. Helium is found in group 18 period 1. Helium\\''s atomic symbol is He.&nbsp; Helium is in the noble gasses.&nbsp; Some interesting facts about helium is, it is the lightest of the noble gases and the second lightest element. The most common isotope of helium is helium-4. Helium is harmless unless taken in&nbsp;by large amounts.&nbsp; In its normal state of matter helium is a gas.</P>\r\n<P>Molly Dennis<BR></P>', '2009-10-06 14:09:41'),
(700, 311, 54, 0, '<div style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"impact\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: large;\\">Potassium</span></font></div><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"impact\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: large; line-height: 27px;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></font></div>', '2009-10-06 14:30:18'),
(701, 362, 56, 0, '<P align=center>Sodium</P>\r\n<P align=left>1. Knut H. Schroder is writing this essay because he has an interest in protecting the envirornment and sodium, domestic and industrial uses, can be used to do just that especially in hot, humid regions.</P>\r\n<P align=left>2. There are many domestic and industrial uses for sodium. The most common domestic use is table salt. They are also found in salt ores.</P>\r\n<P align=left>3. It is found in group 1 and row 3. It is an alkali metal and is normally found as a solid. It is a metal.</P>\r\n<P align=left>4.Sodium reacts with water and oxygen in the air and in liquid ammonia it forms a blue solution.It is the seventh most abundant elements in rocks and the fifth most abundant metal.</P>\r\n<P align=left>5. The element sodium is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities.</P>\r\n<P align=left>6. Sodium can be found in rocks.<BR></P>', '2009-10-06 14:41:29'),
(702, 311, 54, 0, '<div style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"impact\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: large;\\">Potassium</span></font></div><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"impact\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: large; line-height: 27px;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: 27px; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"arial\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">This essay is written by Susan R. Morrissey. &nbsp;Her interest in potassium resulted from an experience with an odd pick up line. &nbsp;Potassium is found in high levels in many foods such as bananas, milk, and orange juice. &nbsp;It is very helpful towards one\\''s health. &nbsp;On the periodic table, Potassium is found in group 1, row 4. &nbsp;It is normally found in a solid state and is a metal. &nbsp;One interesting fact is that its symbol, K, derives from its Latin name-kalium. &nbsp;Obviously, if its found in everyday foods, then the element mustn\\''t be too risky. &nbsp;Pure potassium, however, reacts with water to form flames. &nbsp;It is normally found combined with other elements.</span></font></span></font></div>', '2009-10-06 14:43:59'),
(703, 276, 54, 0, '<div style=\\"text-align: center;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: large;\\">Gold</span></div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''times new roman\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: medium;\\">Alan Lightman from&nbsp;Massachusetts&nbsp;Institute of Technology wrote the article about Gold.&nbsp;Gold is&nbsp;</span></font><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: normal; -webkit-border-horizontal-spacing: 2px; -webkit-border-vertical-spacing: 2px; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''times new roman\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: medium;\\">Commonly used in jewelry, but gold is mostly used in conjunction with another metal to give it strength.Gold can be found on the 11th group and the 6th row and it is under the transition metals their fore it is a metal.&nbsp;Gold&nbsp;can be used to help shield spacecraft and skyscrapers from the sun\\''s heat.&nbsp;Gold is unaffected by air and most reagents. Gold is usually found in rock and has to be mined.</span></font></span></div>', '2009-10-06 15:26:25'),
(704, 335, 54, 0, '<P align=center><STRONG><FONT face=\\"comic sans ms\\" size=6>HELIUM</FONT></STRONG></P><STRONG><FONT face=\\"comic sans ms\\" size=6>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2><FONT face=arial>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Neil Bartlett wrote this article about helium. He was interested in helium because it was a shocking discovery because it was a new category of gas. Helium can be used for balloons or deep-sea diving. This element is found in the&nbsp;eighteenth group and first period. It is a noble gas and is usually found in the gas state. It is a nonmetal. Helium has the lowest boiling point of any element and is the only noble gas with two electrons in its outer shell: the rest have eight. Helium is not dangerous. <FONT face=arial>Helium comes from natural gas deposits within Earth and can be isolated from air. </FONT></FONT><BR></FONT></P></FONT></STRONG><BR>', '2009-10-06 16:53:56'),
(705, 350, 56, 0, '<FONT size=4></FONT>\r\n<P align=center><BR><FONT size=5>Oxygen</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3>1. The writer of the essay is Carl Djerassi and he thinks this element is very and gives all the credit of his work to the element.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3>2. Well obviously you need it to breathe lol :).</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3>3. Its found in the top right of the table and is in the 2nd period and 8th group. It is normally found in the gas state. it is a nonmetal.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3>4. No, an intresting fact is that oxygen is flammable that is why fire can exist on earth because it is actually burning the oxygen that is around.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3>5. No</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3>6. This element is normally foud in the atmosphere combined with other gases such as nitrogen and carbon dioxide.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=center><FONT size=5></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=3></FONT>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-06 17:00:27'),
(707, 309, 57, 0, '<br><div style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-weight: bold;\\">Gold<br></span><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><span style=\\"font-weight: bold;\\"></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The article is written by Alan Lightman. He is interested in the element because of its shininess. Some of the uses of this element is to beautify jewelry. This element is found in group 11 and row 6. It is solid in its normal state. It is a metal. Gold was found free in nature. Gold is the most malleable and ductile element. Gold is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities. This element is found in nature with quartz, pyrite, and other minerals.<br><span style=\\"font-weight: bold;\\"></span></div></div>', '2009-10-06 18:40:06'),
(708, 317, 58, 0, '<P align=center>PICK-AN-ELEMENT- Magnesium</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gerald D. Cole wrote an article on the element Magnesium.&nbsp; He is a senior technical advisor for the Australian Magnesium Corp., and is also the principle in LightWeightStrategies LLC.&nbsp; Gerald D. Cole was a Ford Motor Co. global lightweighting expert for 35 years until his retirement in 2001.&nbsp; Magnesium has many uses including: as a bulk metal, in lightweight alloys, as a \\"sacrificial\\" electrode, in flares, fireworks, and flash photography.&nbsp; Magnesium is found on the periodic table under the Alkaline Earth Metals.&nbsp; It is in the second row, and second group.&nbsp; It is normally found in a solid state, and is a metal.&nbsp; An interesting fact about magnesium is the influence of war changed magnesium\\''s stature from a curiousity to an industrial material. Germany is where the knowledge originated on how easiliy magnesium could be mixed with zinc or aluminum and formed.&nbsp; In the 20th century, magnesium was even referred to as \\"the German metal.\\"&nbsp; Also, magnesium was used in engine parts and wheels in WWII by the Messerschmitt and Stuka dive bombers.&nbsp; Magnesium is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities.&nbsp; In fact, it is commonly connected to nutritional and medicinal uses because it is important in both plant and animal life.&nbsp; This element is normally found alloyed with aluminum, zinc, and manganese.</P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-06 18:46:30'),
(709, 612, 0, 697, 'Thursday', '2009-10-06 18:48:15'),
(710, 612, 0, 706, 'The correct answer', '2009-10-06 18:49:26'),
(711, 372, 55, 0, '&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Fe(Iron)<br>The writter is Arthur B. Ellis. Ellis is interested in the element called Iron. He is fastinated about refrigerator magnets, the compound called magnetite(Fe304), and how iron appers in some unexpected places. For example, food. It says the reason iron is needed in our bodies is because iron is part of our physiology. For instance, iron-containing proteins are store and it transport the oxygen which keeps us alive. Iron is also used for steel. The element is founded in the transition metal. Also iron is in row 4 and group 8. Iron is a solid state.As a result, iron is a metal. A interesting fact about iron is iron was believed to have been first discovered by the Egyptians in 4000 BC. The widespread use of this element lead to the period in World History called the Iron Age. Iron oxide in normal exposure quantities would only irriate the nasal passages, throat, and lungs but not severe. Since 35% of the earth\\''s core is iron and 4% of the earth\\''s crust is iron.Iron can be mainly found around water such as creeks and the ocean. Iron can be found in mountain ranges. It is also common to find large deposits of iron ore in arid areas like deserts. <br>&nbsp;<br>', '2009-10-06 19:06:24');
