(716, 290, 54, 0, '<P align=center>&nbsp;Platinum</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Richard M. Grossn wrote the essay on platinum and he first started thinking about it after his mom dropped hers under the stairs.<STRONG> </STRONG>Platinum&nbsp;was used&nbsp;as the basis of important catalysts in industry--for the production of products such as sulfuric acid, nitric acid, and hydrogen cyanide. It is also used in jewelery. Platinum is found on row 6, column 10. It is found as a solid and is a metal.&nbsp; More then 90% of all platinum comes from South Africa and Russia, it\\''s extraordinarily rare, and more than 10 tons of ore has to be mined to produce a single ounce of platinum. The element is not dangerous. Platinum is found in ore.</FONT></P>', '2009-10-07 14:16:45'),
(717, 340, 56, 0, '<P align=center><BR><FONT size=4 face=arial>Nitrogen</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2 face=Arial>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Peter Nagler is the author of the essay discussing&nbsp;the element nitrogen. He is facinated with nitrogen because&nbsp;of its widespread presence in many different essential components of life on Earth. Nitrogen has many&nbsp;different uses. Liquid nitrogen is very useful in preserving biological specimens as well as freezing foods. Nitrogen in the gaseous state is used as a nonreactive \\"blanket gas\\" in the semiconductor industry as well as&nbsp;in&nbsp;welding. Nitrogen is found in period 2, group 15. It is normally found as a colorless and odorless gas and is a nonmetal. Nitrogen was discovered by Daniel Rutherford, a Scottish physician, in 1772.&nbsp;An interesting fact about nitrogen is that when it was first discovered, it was thought to be unreactive. However, scientists have found that it actually does have a few interesting chemical properties. For example, some elements such as magnesium and lithium can burn in nitrogen. Another interesting fact is that nitrogen is found in nucleic acids and DNA, the genetic instructions of life. This element is obviously not dangerous in normal exposure quantities because it makes up 78% of the air we breathe. However, an atmosphere composed of 100% nitrogen would be fatal. Nitrogen is found in our atmostphere (78.09%) along with oxygen (20.95%) and argon (1%).</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2 face=Georgia></FONT>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-07 16:48:52'),
(718, 521, 58, 0, '<font size=\\"2\\">E.J. Corey wrote about Boron. His intrest in this element is that </font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">boron\r\nnitride is as hard as diamond and similar in structure. Boric acid is\r\ncheap and useful. When dissolved in alcohol, it forms ethyl borate,\r\nwhich burns with a beautiful green flame (light emission from an\r\nelectronically excited state of BO<sub>2</sub>?). Boron-oxygen bonds\r\nare very strong. Compounds of boron with B–H and/or B–C bonds are\r\nhighly reactive and easily oxidized. Whereas hydrocarbons such as C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>6</sub> and C<sub>4</sub>H<sub>10</sub> are stable at 25 ºC in air, the boron equivalents B<sub>2</sub>H<sub>6</sub> and B<sub>4</sub>H<sub>10</sub> burn spontaneously, an obvious reason for nature to avoid such boron compounds in living systems.</font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\"> Some uses of boron is that it is an\r\nessential micronutrient for plants. Boric acid is used to make\r\nborosilicate glass, or Pyrex. Boron is used in fission-reactor control\r\nrods to capture neutrons and regulate the power produced. It is also\r\nused with silicon in making p-type semiconductors and eye disinfectant\r\nand in pyrotechnics to make a green color. It is found &nbsp;in group 13, row 2. It can be found in the Mohave Desert and in Turkey. Boron is a metalloid. It was found in&nbsp;</font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">1808 by British chemist Sir Humphry Davy and independently by French chemists Joseph-Louis Gay-Lussac and Louis-Jacques Thénard. It can be poisonous in extensive amounts. It is found in a labratory. It is found in nature, but not at its pure form. </font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\"></font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\"></font><table width=\\"760\\" border=\\"0\\" cellpadding=\\"0\\" cellspacing=\\"0\\"><tbody><tr valign=\\"top\\"><td width=\\"544\\" bgcolor=\\"white\\"><br></td></tr></tbody></table>', '2009-10-08 08:31:54'),
(719, 265, 56, 0, '<P align=center><FONT color=#ffff66 size=4><STRONG>&nbsp;Gold</STRONG></FONT><FONT size=+0><FONT size=4><FONT size=3></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\" size=2><STRONG>Alan Lightman wrote the essay on Gold which is a story about a young man who bought a gold necklace for the girl he likes. Lightman is interested in how precious Gold is, how malleable it is, and how it can be used to impress someone. Gold can be used as jewelry, used in a treatment for arthritis, in nanoarchitecture of new materials. Gold is on the transition medal section of the periodic table, in group 11, row 6. It\\''s normal state is solid and it\\''s a metal. Gold has been around since circa 4000 BC. The biggest gold nugget in existence today is called \\"The Hand of Faith\\" which weighs 61&nbsp;lbs. Kevin Hillier found this nugget with a metal detector and sold it for over a million dollars. This element is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities. 40 % of the gold found during this time period has been found in South Africa in The Precambrian Witwatersrand. Most gold is found in its metallic state of flakes, dust, and grains.&nbsp; The most common gold compounds are auri chloride and chlorauric acid. It is mostly found in seawater.</STRONG></FONT></P></FONT></FONT></FONT>', '2009-10-08 15:46:06'),
