margin-right:0in;\r\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:10.0pt;\r\n	mso-para-margin-left:0in;\r\n	line-height:115%;\r\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\r\n	font-size:11.0pt;\r\n	font-family:\\"Calibri\\",\\"sans-serif\\";\r\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;\r\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n	mso-fareast-font-family:\\"Times New Roman\\";\r\n	mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;\r\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;\r\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;}\r\n</style>\r\n<![endif]-->\r\n\r\n<p class=\\"MsoNormal\\">Richard M. Gross wrote the essay on PLATINUM. Some of the\r\nmost common uses for gold is the making of jewelry or the like, but it also has\r\nsome very practical uses, such as helping produce important products such as\r\nsulfuric acid, nitric acid,&nbsp;<span style=\\"font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\\">and hydrogen cyanide and can even help\r\nus build cleaner, more environment-friendly cars! It is found in the Periodic\r\nTable under group 10 and is listed in period 6, so it\\''s basically a transition\r\nmetal. Being as such, it usually is found in a solid state as a metal, it is\r\nvery study and rigid - not soft such as much more reactive metals like sodium.\r\nOne interesting thing is that Platinum is extremely rare - even more so than\r\ngold! - and it takes twice as much Platinum ore to produce an ounce of platinum\r\nthan with gold. Platinum has also been used since as early as 3,000 years ago\r\nin ancient Egypt! The Incas in South America also used platinum to adorn\r\nthings, but the (idiotic) Spanish Conquistadors said it was a \\"solver of\r\nless value,\\" dumped the platinum in the sea because they didn\\''t want it to\r\nbecome a cheap imitation of silver.&nbsp;To my knowledge, there is nothing\r\ndangerous about platinum unless someone hits you over the head with it. It is\r\nusually found with other, less valuable elements in the form of platinum ore,\r\nso they have to melt it down and extract it.&nbsp;</span><span style=\\"font-size: 14pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Kristen ITC&quot;;\\"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\"></font>', '2009-10-11 08:13:02'),
(737, 348, 58, 0, 'PICK-AN-ELEMENT: PLATINUM<br><br>Richard M. Gross wrote the essay on PLATINUM. Some of the\r\nmost common uses for gold is the making of jewelry or the like, but it also has\r\nsome very practical uses, such as helping produce important products such as\r\nsulfuric acid, nitric acid,&nbsp;<span style=\\"font-size: 10pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\\">and hydrogen cyanide and can even help\r\nus build cleaner, more environment-friendly cars! It is found in the Periodic\r\nTable under group 10 and is listed in period 6, so it\\''s basically a transition\r\nmetal. Being as such, it usually is found in a solid state as a metal, it is\r\nvery study and rigid - not soft such as much more reactive metals like sodium.\r\nOne interesting thing is that Platinum is extremely rare - even more so than\r\ngold! - and it takes twice as much Platinum ore to produce an ounce of platinum\r\nthan with gold. Platinum has also been used since as early as 3,000 years ago\r\nin ancient Egypt! The Incas in South America also used platinum to adorn\r\nthings, but the (idiotic) Spanish Conquistadors said it was a \\"solver of\r\nless value,\\" dumped the platinum in the sea because they didn\\''t want it to\r\nbecome a cheap imitation of silver.&nbsp;To my knowledge, there is nothing\r\ndangerous about platinum unless someone hits you over the head with it. It is\r\nusually found with other, less valuable elements in the form of platinum ore,\r\nso they have to melt it down and extract it. </span><br>', '2009-10-11 08:14:43'),
