(745, 381, 55, 0, 'jordan barr<div>hollis</div><div>chem. 2</div><div style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><b><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\">Carbon</span></b></div><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\">George Olah is a professor at USC he is who wrote this essay. &nbsp;Carbon is the basis of all life forms. &nbsp;It is also a major part of fossil fuels and the Earths atmosphere. &nbsp;Carbons most common isotopes are are commonly known as granite and diamonds. &nbsp;It is found in the 14th group and the second period. &nbsp;It is a non metal.Carbon is most commonly found in nature as a solid. &nbsp;It is not dangerous by itself but it can be when combined with other elements. &nbsp;It is commonly found bound with other elements because it combines with other elements very easily. &nbsp;</div>', '2009-10-11 14:18:56'),
(746, 293, 55, 0, '<P>Michael Grauvogl<BR>chem. 2</P>\r\n<P>11 october 2009</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=center>He(Helium)</P>\r\n<P align=left>This essay was written by Neil Bartlett of the University of Califorina. Helium is used in many different ways. One way it is used, is to fill up ballons with helium to make them fly. It is also used by deep sea divers to dillute the oxygen they breathe. Helium is found on the 18th group and the first period. It is normly found as a gas, and it is a nobel gas. Helium was discoverd by William Ramsay in 1895. Ramsay also found many other gases including xenon, krypton, and neon. If you inhale too much Helium it could kill you. To obtain helium you must extract it from the air.</P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-11 14:45:23'),
(747, 375, 54, 0, '<P><FONT size=5><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp;</FONT>Arsenic</FONT><BR></P>\r\n<P>M. Feroze Ahmed from the Bangladesh Universtiy of Engineering &amp; Technology wrote an article about arsenic&nbsp; because its role in poisoning water and the way it was used as a type of medicine in his childhood.&nbsp; In small doses, arsenic can be used to build up resistance to a common cold or asthma, but in larger lethal doses can be deadly to the human body and is not noticeable by sight, smell, or taste.&nbsp; Arsenic is located in Group 15, Period 4 on the periodic table.&nbsp; It is a main-group element.&nbsp; It is peculiar that arsenic can be so harmful in large doses, but at the same time quite helpful in minimal doses.&nbsp; It is found in nature and is widely distributed in air, water, soils, rocks, plants, and animals in variable concentrations.</P>', '2009-10-11 14:46:44'),
