(754, 331, 58, 0, '<div style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><b>Copper</b></div><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\">This essay was &nbsp;written by George Whitesides, because he was recommended to study copper by a professor for its unique characteristics in organic chemistry. &nbsp; &nbsp;Some of the uses of this element is pure copper can be used for ornamental objects or if it is mixed with tin it can be used for swords. &nbsp;Also, it used to be used in pennies and is stil used for roof sheets and copper wire. &nbsp;This element is found in the transition elements and in the 4th row and 11th column. &nbsp;It is normally found in the solid state. &nbsp;It is a metal that was known by many ancient civilizations. &nbsp;It is also one of the few metals that occur in large quantities in nature. &nbsp;This element is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities. &nbsp;This element is normally found in nature is Copper salts that are easily reduced to pure Copper metal.</div>', '2009-10-11 17:42:47'),
(755, 390, 57, 0, '<div style=\\"text-align: center;\\">Nickel</div><div><br></div>The article was written by David Hanson. There are many uses for nickel. One of the main uses is for stainless steel. Almost 70%of all<div>nickel is used to make stainless steel. Also nickel is used to make the nickel. About 25% of the coin nickel is actually made out of nickel.</div><div>It is located in the transition metals on the periodic table. It is in group ten and row for on the table. Nickel is usually found in a solid form,</div><div>but it can also be a liquid if heated. Nickel is a metal. Nickel was discovered in 1751 by a Swedish Chemist by the name of Axel F. Cronstedt.</div><div>An interesting fact about Nickel is that in most forms nickel is harmful to humans. Nickel is rarely found in the Earth\\''s crust, but experts</div><div>believe that it is abundant in the molten core.</div><div><br></div><div>Mitch Epley 4th period</div>', '2009-10-11 17:59:37'),
(756, 388, 56, 0, '<P align=center><FONT face=Verdana size=5>Boron</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=5><FONT face=Verdana>&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT size=+0><FONT size=+0><FONT size=3>The essay written about boron was written by E. J. Corey.&nbsp; Corey decided to do the essay on boron because he believes boron doesn\\''t appear enough in textbooks on biochemistrey.&nbsp; What fasinates Corey the about boron is the possibilities for catalytic asymmetric (enantioselective) synthesis when it is embedded in a suitable chiral molecular environment.&nbsp; Boron is an essential micronutrient for plants and boric acid is used to make borosilicate glass.&nbsp; Boron is found next to carbon on the periodic table in group 13, row 2.&nbsp; Is it normally found as a solid and is a metalliod.&nbsp; What everyone know about boron is that boron nitride is as hard as diamond and similar in structure. Also, when boric acid id dissolved in alcohol, it forms ethyl borate, which burns with a green flame.&nbsp; Excessive amounts of boric acid and borates are poisonous.&nbsp; Boron can not be found in a pure state in nature but occurs as orthoboric acid in certain volcanic spring waters and as borates in colemantie. </FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=center><BR>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-11 18:14:44'),
(757, 337, 57, 0, '<P><BR>Paul Basilone</P>\r\n<P align=center>Calcium</P>\r\n<P align=left>Sture forsen from lund university in sweden became fascinated with calcium during his graduate studies in the early 1960s. Calcium is used to keep bones and teeth strong. Calcium is found in the earth alkaline metal family in the 4th row and 2nd group. The form calcium is usually metal but it is rarely found in pure form because it is highly reactive. Calcium was discovered by the romans when they burned limestone. Calcium is not dangerous in normal cases but is highly reactive and can be dangerous if abused. Calcium is usually found in limestone, chalk, the human body, and other minerals.</P>', '2009-10-11 19:03:07'),
(758, 491, 58, 0, '<P align=center>PICK-AN-ELEMENT: <STRONG>PLUTONIUM</STRONG></P>\r\n<P align=left><BR>This essay on plutonium is written by Shenda M. Baker,&nbsp;a chemistry&nbsp;professor at&nbsp;Harvey Mudd college, she is writing about this element because she beliefs that plutonium is multifaceted. \\"It is&nbsp;<FONT size=2 face=\\"\\">feared as an impossibly long-lived waste dilemma, and equally denounced as an uncontrollable force.\\"</FONT><FONT size=2>&nbsp;Plutonium has a few major uses that include; can be use as a nuclear explosive, nuclear fuel, has enough heat energy to sustain economy with only a small amount of it, and \\"star flight\\".</FONT><FONT size=2>Plutonium is found in the actinide series and is a heavy metal an a normally a solid with a dull&nbsp;silvery gray color. </FONT><FONT size=2>Plutonium was descovered by Glenn T. Seaborg and colleagues in Berkeley, California in 1940. It is natural element, but in order to become military grade it must be enriched to 3% for use in nuclear bombs. Is named after the planet Pluto.</FONT><FONT size=2>Plutonium is highly radiotoxic and in&nbsp;a large amount can boil water.</FONT><FONT size=2>&nbsp;Plutonium is normally found in minute amount in&nbsp;uranium ores.</FONT></P>', '2009-10-11 19:04:23'),
(759, 404, 57, 0, '<P align=center><STRONG>Copper</STRONG></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; George M. Whitesides of Harvard University wrote this article on copper. He did not have a natural interest in copper though. He actually planned on doing gold organometallic chemistry. However, his research director suggested that he research copper rather than gold, as it is cheaper and would be far more interesting. After some research, George had already inherited a great interest in copper because of its strange and unknown attributes.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Copper is a crucial element in our lives. It is the most widely-used conductor of all of the elements, it is used in Sterling Silver and is one of the main components of bronze. It is also a commonly-used catalyst. </P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Copper is the 29th element on the periodic table. It\\''s an outer transition metal located in row 4, group 11. It is a solid in its natural state, and it is classified as a metal.&nbsp; Copper is one of few elements that are found in large quantities in nature. It tends to be fairly reactive and is often found in the form of salts. In its natural state, copper is not dangerous to humans. </P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Copper is often found as an ore, but it is typically not binded to other elements. Copper salts are easily separated into usable elements, so mining copper is a fairly simple task.<BR><BR></P>', '2009-10-11 19:40:40'),
(760, 402, 58, 0, '<P><BR><FONT size=2>PICK-AN-ELEMENT: BORON</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2>E.J. Corey of Harvard University wrote this essay on Boron. he feels it is an element of great versitility and individuality. that is why he took a particular interest in this element.&nbsp;Boron is&nbsp;<FONT face=\\"\\">An essential micronutrient for plants. Boric acid is used to make borosilicate glass, or Pyrex. Boron is used in fission-reactor control rods to capture neutrons and regulate the power produced. It is also used with silicon in making p-type semiconductors and eye disinfectant and in pyrotechnics to make a green color. It is found in group 13, period 2. it is a metalloid normally found as a solid.&nbsp;<FONT face=\\"\\"> Boron compounds have been known for years, but the pure form was not isolated until 1808 by British chemist Sir Humphry Davy and independently by French chemists Joseph-Louis Gay-Lussac and Louis-Jacques Thénard. Large<FONT face=\\"\\">&nbsp;amounts of boric acid and borates are poisonous, although they were once used in medicines.&nbsp;Boron<FONT><FONT face=\\"\\"><STRONG> </STRONG>Makes up 0.0003% of Earth\\''s crust by mass. It is never found in its pure form in nature, but occurs in certain volcanic spring waters and as borates in colemantie. Important sources of boron are the ores rasorite (kernite) and borax (tincal), which can be found in the Mohave Desert. Extensive borax deposits are also found in Turkey.</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></P>', '2009-10-11 19:51:43'),
