(763, 326, 57, 0, '<P align=center>Platinum<BR></P>\r\n<H1 dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\" align=left>\r\n<H1>\r\n<P><FONT face=arial>The interesting article written by L. V. Paganini is saying if Citicard\\''s Platinum or Chase Platinum is a zero percent card to choose.&nbsp;Some uses of Platinum include&nbsp;jewerly,producing sulfuric acid, the coating of missile nose cones, jet engine fuel nozzles and it acts as a catalyst in fuel cells andin antipollution devices for automobiles.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=Arial></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=Arial>Platinum is located at the transition metals section; group10 period 6. Some intresting facts about it include are that the coronation of the Queen mother was made made from platinum, platinum melting point is almost double that of goldand platinum is used in the hard disks of most PC\\''s to improve capacity and durability. yes platinum is dangerous in normal exposure quantities.&nbsp;Platinum can occur free in nature and is sometimes found in deposits of gold bearing sands, primarily those found in the Ural mountains, Columbia and the western United States.</FONT></P></H1></H1>\r\n<P dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\" align=left>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\" align=left>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\" align=left>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-12 12:10:37'),
(764, 391, 57, 0, '<P align=center>neon</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left>1<FONT size=2 face=\\"times new roman\\">. Neil Bartlett, Univeristy of California, Barkley</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2 face=\\"times new roman\\">2. Neon is used in Cryogenic Temperatures</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2 face=\\"times new roman\\">3. Neon is located in Group 12, Row 2</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2 face=\\"times new roman\\">4. <FONT>So the discovery of the unreactive monatomic gas argon by Lord Rayleigh and William Ramsay in 1895 came as a total surprise. James Dewar even indicated that the new gas could be an allotrope of nitrogen, N<SUB>3</SUB>, a suggestion seconded by Mendeleyev! Within three years, however, Ramsay (and coworker Morris Travers) had also discovered helium, neon, krypton, and xenon. They established their monatomic and unreactive nature.</FONT><BR>5. No</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT size=2 face=\\"Times New Roman\\">6. Can also be found with kryton and xenon.</FONT></P>', '2009-10-12 13:05:50'),
(765, 347, 55, 0, '<P align=left><BR>Stephanie Metzger</P>\r\n<P align=center>Silver (Ag)</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left>The writer who wrote this essay is Alan Shaw. His interest for silver began through admiration of Greek and Roman artifacts. Years of Alan studying silver, he found a relationship between man and this metal.&nbsp;Some uses of silver could be found almost everywhere because it seems to be so common in today life.&nbsp; For example, Jewelry, cameras, mirrors, and eating utensils.&nbsp;The element silver is found in the&nbsp;middle right&nbsp;row in group eleven and period five.&nbsp;Silver is normally found in the solid state and is also a metal.&nbsp;<FONT face=Arial size=2>There was a silver birch regarded as a tree of elegance, referred to in Europe&nbsp;as the \\"Queen of the Forest\\". The element silver does not seem to be poisonous, but some of the things that make up silver may be.&nbsp;The element silver is normally found in nature.</FONT></P>', '2009-10-12 14:08:14'),
(766, 373, 55, 0, '<P>Jordyn Herwig</P>\r\n<P>Chem 2nd</P>\r\n<P>10/12/09</P>\r\n<P align=center>Gold (Au)</P>\r\n<P align=left>Alan Lightman from Massachusetts Institution of Technology is writing this essay. Gold is commonly used in jewelry and gold alloys are also used to make decorative items, dental fillings, and coins.&nbsp;The element gold is found in the 11th group and 6th row. Gold is normally found as a metal. It is a soft, shiny yellow metal that can also appear black. purple or ruby when finely divided. <FONT><FONT size=2><FONT face=\\"\\">Gold is the most malleable and ductile metal. It is unaffected by air, and is a good conductor of heat and electricity. Gold is generally nontoxic. This element is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities. Gold is found free in nature.&nbsp;</FONT>&nbsp;<FONT face=\\"\\">Two-thirds of the world\\''s supply comes from South Africa, Gold is found in seawater, but no effective economic process has been designed yet to extract it from this source.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><BR></P>', '2009-10-12 14:14:34'),
(767, 389, 54, 0, '<P><BR><EM><U><FONT size=5>Silver</FONT></U></EM></P>\r\n<P><EM><U><FONT size=5></FONT></U></EM>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This essay was written by Alan Shaw, he became interested in this element when he was a child standing in the British Museum gazing at an elegant silver polished mirror, it is a metal.&nbsp;Uses for silver are silverware, coins, mirrors, photographic film, batteries, etc. Silver is found in Group 11, row 5, in the transition metal. Ancient civilizations such as the romans and greeks were astoinded by silver, for believing it to look like the moon, they would carve their coins from silver. Silver is a harmless element. Silver can be found all over the world. Silver is extracted from lead.</FONT></P>', '2009-10-12 14:33:15'),
(768, 359, 55, 0, '<P align=center>Cobalt</P>\r\n<P align=left>The writer of this essay is Ekkehard Schward. He is a research director at BASF in Germany and he researches heterogeneous catalysis and cobalt is an essential to important catalsis. Cobalt is used in the manufacture of cleaner fuels and is used in videotapes to help higher-density recording.&nbsp;Cobalt is found in the fourth period and the ninth group. it is usually fiound in a&nbsp;solid state and it is a metal. A young man in Schneeberg had been experimenting with the dead rock left by silver. Everyone thought that he was a wizard and they were going to have him arrested&nbsp;untill they saw what he had dound. Cobalt blue. No, cobalt is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities. Coblat is found mixed in with other elements and is also one of the human body\\''s essential trace element.</P>\r\n<P align=left><BR></P>', '2009-10-12 14:37:15'),
(769, 356, 57, 0, '<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <STRONG>Hydrogen<BR></STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG>1.Henry Cavendish </STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG>2. it is in the make up of water: H20 - hydrogen and oxygen;also use for blowing up balloons</STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG>3.Row 1 Column 1</STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG>4.Hydrogen is a chemical</STRONG>, <STRONG>and a&nbsp;colorless, highly flammable gaseous element, the lightest of all gases and the most abundant element in the universe.</STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG>5.No</STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG>6.Hydrogen is not found in free states because, it the smallest element with one valence electron and will bond to just about anything, theres no scenario in nature where hydrogen would not have another element around to bond to <!-- google_ad_section_end --><BR style=\\"DISPLAY: block; CLEAR: left\\"></STRONG></P>', '2009-10-12 15:31:23'),
(770, 328, 58, 0, '<BR>\r\n<P align=center>PICK-AN-ELEMENT: <STRONG>ALUMINUM</STRONG></P>\r\n<P align=left><BR><FONT size=2><FONT face=\\"\\">Gregory H. Robinson <FONT color=black>is&nbsp;writing this essay and he is a research professor of chemistry at the University of Georgia.<STRONG>&nbsp;</STRONG>H</FONT></FONT></FONT>e is writing about this element because he thinks that Aluminum is of utter contrasts. Aluminum is once highly valued as a \\"precious metal\\".The 1884 aluminum metal sits&nbsp;at the top of the washington monument. Its found in the group 13, row 2, and is non-metal.&nbsp;Its not dangerous in normal exposures. Its normally found in&nbsp;<FONT size=2 face=\\"\\">Copenhagen, Denmark.</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;</P>', '2009-10-12 15:45:12'),
(771, 244, 54, 0, '<P align=center><STRONG><FONT size=4>SILICON</FONT></STRONG></P>\r\n<P><STRONG><FONT size=4></FONT></STRONG>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left><STRONG><FONT face=georgia size=3></FONT></STRONG>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\" align=left><FONT><FONT size=3><FONT face=arial><FONT size=2>Roald Hoffmann from Cornell University is writing this essay because s</FONT><FONT><FONT size=2>imilarity and difference nourish the mind at play, his introduction to the periodic table actually came through a science story about silicon buried in the pages of a comic book&nbsp;he found lying around on the S.S. <I>Ernie Pyle,</I> the troop carrier that brought us to America in 1949. silicon is used to make clays, micas, zeolites, aerogels, amethyst and carnelian, lapis lazuli, asbestos, porcelain, and some types of glasses. silicon is found on the periodic tabke in group 16, row 3. silicon is a metalloid. unsaturation is strongly disfavored for silicon, as it is for other main-group elements below the first row. The abundance of silicon in Earth\\''s crust is second only to oxygen. Silicates are also essential for higher plants.</FONT> </FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT><BR></P>', '2009-10-12 16:02:56'),
(773, 401, 58, 0, '<BR>&nbsp;\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0in\\"><FONT face=\\"Arial, sans-serif\\"><B>PICK AN ELEMENT: NEON </B></FONT></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0in\\"><FONT face=\\"Arial, sans-serif\\"><B>Neil Bartlett from the University of California is writing because,the Periodic Table of the Elements, as set out by Dmitry Mendeleyev or Lother Meyer, had not allowed for the discovery of a group of elements between the highly electronegative halogens and the electro positive alkalis. Neon is used for lights. Neon is found in period 2 and group 18. It is normally a gas and it\\''s a nonmetal. Neon is rare to find on Earth and is a colorless gas. Neon is dangerous if exposed too. </B></FONT></P>', '2009-10-12 16:30:53'),
(774, 363, 54, 0, '<font style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 153);\\" size=\\"5\\"><span style=\\"font-family: georgia; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;\\">Xenon</span></font><span style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 153);\\"> <font size=\\"2\\">(Xe)</font></span><br><br><span style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 153);\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font size=\\"2\\"> Neil Bartlett of UC Berkeley writes this essay about the element xenon, one of the members of a breakthrough group, the noble gases. Xenon is used for many lighting purposes, including: flash cameras, strobe lights, headlights, and bactericidal lamps. It is found in period 5 and group 18 in the periodic table of the elements. Xenon is a nonmetal normally found in the gaseous state. It was discovered in 1898, and was one of the last noble gases to be isolated. Since xenon is an inert (nonreactive) gas, normal exposure is not considered to be dangerous. Xenon is generally found in compounds, usually combined with either fluorine or oxygen. </font></span><br>', '2009-10-12 17:05:55'),
(775, 339, 57, 0, '<P align=center><BR>Potassium</P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=\\"\\">Susan Morrissey wrote this essay and she seems more intrested in a boy she met at college, rather than Potassium.&nbsp; Some uses of Potassium are to <FONT size=2 face=\\"\\">regulate water balance in the body or its use in fireworks.&nbsp; Potassium is found in alkali metals, group one, row four, and&nbsp;is usually a solid, which is a metal.&nbsp; P<FONT face=\\"\\">otassium is an electrolyte mineral essential to maintaining good health, regulates cellular acid-base and fluid balance, blood pressure, and neuromuscular function.&nbsp; Potassium isn\\''t dangerous in normal exposure quantities.&nbsp; Potassium is found in many foods, such as meat, bananas, fish, and many fruits.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>', '2009-10-12 17:11:44'),
(776, 354, 56, 0, '&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Plutonium<br>1.Shenda M Baker made an essay on Plutonium and she thought about its destructive power it could bring and its possibly of space flights and rockets.<br>2. Nuclear Weapons and Power Generation<br>3. Its Period is 7 (actinoid) and its group is Actinoid. Its a Metal.<br>4. It was created by bombarding Deuteron and Uranium-238 together. They named it after Pluto and as a joke called its Atomic Symbol \\"Pu\\". It was also used in the Manhattan Project during WWII<br>5. YES it is Radioactive.<br>6. It is a man made element by using uranium-238 and deuteron to create this destructive element.<br>', '2009-10-12 17:31:24'),
(777, 345, 55, 0, '<P><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\">Thomas Olesko</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\">October 12 2009</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\"></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=center><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\">Mg&nbsp;(Magnesium)</FONT></P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\"></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\"></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT face=\\"times new roman\\"><FONT>The person writing this article is Gerald D. Cole.&nbsp; He </FONT><FONT size=2><FONT>is the principal in LightWeightStrategies LLC and is a senior technical adviser for the Australian Magnesium Corp. He was a Ford Motor Co. global lightweighting expert for 35 years until he retired in 2001.&nbsp; Magnesium <FONT>is used in some jet engine parts, rockets, missiles, and helicopter rotor housings.&nbsp; Magnesium is found on the third row and second group.&nbsp; Magnesium is a metal.&nbsp; Magnesium is the lightest industrial metal. Typing \\"magnesium\\" on google comes up with 1.5 million citations and 1.4 million of those are connected to nutritional and madical uses.&nbsp; Magnesium is not dangerous in normal exposure quantities and it is usually found in the solid state and it is usually combined to form alloys.</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></P>', '2009-10-12 18:15:41'),
(778, 304, 54, 0, '<font style=\\"font-family: impact;\\" size=\\"6\\">Carbon</font><br>George A. Olah wrote the essay that I read about Carbon because he seems to be fascinated with it\\''s many forms and places it can be found in nature. For example, Carbon can be found as a key component in many minerals and fossil fuels; it also plays a small, but important role in the atmosphere. On the periodic table, Carbon can be found in group 14, period 2, and at room temperature it is a solid, non metal. Interestingly enough, carbon is not credited with one discoverer, since it has been known of since ancient times (this information was not in the article). One interesting feature of carbon itself, though, is the ability bond with itself and form complex chains and structures. In usual exposure quantities, carbon is not harmful, but rather safe extremely useful in other materials. Usually, Carbon is found in Fossil fuels and in small quantities in the atmosphere, like I said earlier.<br>', '2009-10-12 18:47:33'),
(779, 418, 58, 0, 'PICK-AN-ELEMENT: Cesium<br><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard Kaner is writing this essay because of his interest in inorganic chemistry which he teaches. Its main use is to create ionic salts. It is on the left side of the periodic table in row 6, group 1. It is a solid in its normal state. It is an alkali metal. There aren\\''t any interesting facts behind cesium\\''s discovery. but one interesting fact is that it reacts violently with water. It can be dangerous in normal quantities if combined with water. This element is normally found <font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">as a hydrated aluminosilicate mineral and is mined in the Bernic Lake region of Manitoba. <br></font></div>', '2009-10-12 19:28:10'),
(780, 358, 54, 0, '<font size=\\"3\\"><font size=\\"4\\"><font size=\\"5\\">Osmium</font><br></font></font><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><br><font color=\\"black\\" face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">Ian Shott wrote this article because he discovered how common the element is in his everyday life.&nbsp; Working in the international pharmaceutical and fine chemicals industry, he has become more familiar with Osmium and understands what its primary uses are.&nbsp; Osmium can commonly be found in </font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">pen nibs and armor-piercing weapon shells and is the densest metal on the entire periodic table.&nbsp; Being a metal, this element can be found in row 6 group 8 and is most commonly found in its solid state.&nbsp; </font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">Osmium was discovered in 1803 by Smithson Tennant, an English chemist, in the residue left when crude platinum is dissolved by aqua regia.&nbsp; While the element itself is not toxic, its volatile oxide is.&nbsp; It can naturally be found in </font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">iridosule and in platinum-bearing river sands. </font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"1\\"><br></font></div>', '2009-10-12 19:58:48'),
(781, 369, 55, 0, '<P align=left><BR>David Cook</P>\r\n<P align=left>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=center>#19 Potassium (K)</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=center>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P align=left>Susan Morrissey is writing this essay on potassium because of a pickup line used by a man she met at a party her friend held.&nbsp; This element is used in the body to regulate the water balance in the body, to regulate neuromuscular function, along with the making of fireworks, fertilizers, match heads, soaps, glass, and detergents.&nbsp; Potassium is found in the first group, fourth period of the table.&nbsp; There is nothing interesting about the discovery of potassium.&nbsp; Potassium is not dangerous in normal quantities of exposure; on the contrary, it is quite helpful to the body in normal quantities.&nbsp; Potassium is the seventh most abundant metal, but does not occur freely in nature, but can be found in soil, bananas, meats, pultry, fish, potatoes, milk, orange juice, blueberries, cucumbers, carrots, onions, grapefruit, iceberg lettuce, and minerals of Germany, Spain, Canada, and the United States.</P>', '2009-10-12 20:00:52'),
(782, 368, 54, 0, '<font style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\" size=\\"6\\">Iron</font><br><br>The author of my article on iron, Arthur Ellis, is the director of the Division of Chemistry at the National Science foundation. He is the Meloche-Bascom Professor of Chemistry at the University of Wisconsin. Ellis chose to write about Iron because he feels its a good element to teach students about. An important use for iron is magnetism. We use magnets everyday, so iron is important. You can even find iron in food. Iron has an atomic number of 26 and is located in the transitional metals area, thus it being a metal. It is located at group 8 and period 4. Iron dates all the way back to prehistoric times. You can often find iron mixed with other elements.<span style=\\"font-weight: bold;\\"></span><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"2\\">\r\n									</font>\r\n									<p><font color=\\"black\\" face=\\"Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif\\" size=\\"2\\"><b><a name=\\"Anchor-Arthur-49730\\"></a></b></font></p>', '2009-10-13 04:45:17'),
