(786, 332, 58, 0, 'MERCURY<br><br>This essay was written by Rudy M. Baum and he is trying to tell people that mercury is the only metal that is a liquid. It is used in thermometers, medicine, disinfectants and is conductive with batteries, wires, and light bulbs. It is found on the 6th row and the 12th group. It is usually always in a liquid form even though it is a metal. Mercury is a metal. It is one of the handful of elements that have been known since antiquity. Alchemists are convinced that it held the key to transmuting base metals into gold. This element can be very toxic to people. It is usually found in its free state without being combined with other elements.<br>', '2009-10-13 14:14:55'),
(788, 346, 55, 0, '<P align=center>Sodium(Na)</P>\r\n<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\">\r\n<P dir=ltr style=\\"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px\\" align=left><FONT style=\\"BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffffff\\">This essay is written by Knut H. Schroder. The essay is about the different neccesities of Sodium. Sodium is used to make salt(NaCl), which is very important for the human body. Sodium is in group one and period three of the periodic table. Sodium is a alkali metal. It is the seventh most abundant element in rocks and the fifth most abundant in metals. Them element is mostly found as salt.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>', '2009-10-13 15:04:16'),
(789, 261, 55, 0, '<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center\\" align=left><STRONG><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\">Cesium</SPAN></STRONG><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\"><?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = \\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office\\" /><o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt\\"><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt\\"><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\">Richard Kaner teaches chemistry at the <?xml:namespace prefix = st1 ns = \\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:smarttags\\" /><st1:place w:st=\\"on\\"><st1:PlaceType w:st=\\"on\\">University</st1:PlaceType> of <st1:PlaceName w:st=\\"on\\">California</st1:PlaceName></st1:place>. Cesium is used in atomic clocks and in radiation monitoring equipment. Cesium is found among the alkali metals in the sixth period in the first&nbsp;group on the periodic table. At room temperature cesium is a silvery gold liquid. Cesium has the second lowest melting point relative to mercury. Discovered in 1860 by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff, cesium\\''s name comes from the Latin term <EM><SPAN style=\\"FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\">caesius</SPAN></EM> meaning heavenly blue, after the most prominent color in its spectrum. It is moderately poisonous and is most commonly found in the mineral pollucite.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>Megan Le Corre</P>\r\n<P>13 October 2009</P>', '2009-10-13 15:27:13'),
