(791, 580, 57, 0, '<BR>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"COLOR: #984806; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\"><FONT size=3><FONT face=\\"Times New Roman\\"><STRONG>Rutherfordium<?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = \\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office\\" /><o:p></o:p></STRONG></FONT></FONT></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><o:p><FONT color=#000000 size=3 face=\\"Times New Roman\\">&nbsp;</FONT></o:p><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #333333; FONT-SIZE: 8pt\\">1. Who is writing the essay and what is their interest in this particular element? <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">Michael Freemantle, C&amp;EN London; involved in International Politics and is also has been involved in the naming of new elements.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #333333; FONT-SIZE: 8pt\\">2. What are some uses of this element? <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">No uses; /No “commercial uses”.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #333333; FONT-SIZE: 8pt\\">3. Where is the element found on the periodic table? What row? What group? What state is it normally found in? Is it a metal, nonmetal, or metalloid? <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">Group- 4; Row- 7;<SPAN style=\\"mso-spacerun: yes\\">&nbsp; </SPAN>Artificially created in a laboratory;<SPAN style=\\"mso-spacerun: yes\\">&nbsp; </SPAN>very radioactive metal of no knowledgeable color.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #333333; FONT-SIZE: 8pt\\">4. Does this element have any interesting facts or stories behind its discovery? If not, add interesting facts about the element. <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">It was artificially produced by a team of Nuclear Researchers in Russia.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">Rutherfordium has also had many names.<SPAN style=\\"mso-spacerun: yes\\">&nbsp; </SPAN>For example: rutherfordium; kurchatovium; dubnium; unnilquadium; and element 104.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #333333; FONT-SIZE: 8pt\\">5. Is this element dangerous in normal exposure quantities? <o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">This element is “intensely radioactive\\".<SPAN style=\\"mso-spacerun: yes\\">&nbsp; </SPAN><o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #333333; FONT-SIZE: 8pt\\">6. Where is this element normally found...in the free state, combined with other elements and extracted<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><B style=\\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\\"><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Tahoma\\'',\\''sans-serif\\''; COLOR: #984806; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; mso-themecolor: accent6; mso-themeshade: 128\\">Is not \\"found\\" in a free state because it is artificially created.<o:p></o:p></SPAN></B></P>', '2009-10-13 16:09:15'),
(792, 623, 58, 0, '<meta http-equiv=\\"Content-Type\\" content=\\"text/html; charset=utf-8\\"><meta name=\\"ProgId\\" content=\\"Word.Document\\"><meta name=\\"Generator\\" content=\\"Microsoft Word 10\\"><meta name=\\"Originator\\" content=\\"Microsoft Word 10\\"><link rel=\\"File-List\\" href=\\"file:///C:%5CDOCUME%7E1%5CLUANJP%7E1.003%5CLOCALS%7E1%5CTemp%5Cmsohtml1%5C01%5Cclip_filelist.xml\\"><o:smarttagtype namespaceuri=\\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:smarttags\\" name=\\"country-region\\"></o:smarttagtype><o:smarttagtype namespaceuri=\\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:smarttags\\" name=\\"place\\"></o:smarttagtype><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <w:WordDocument>\r\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\r\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\r\n  <w:Compatibility>\r\n   <w:BreakWrappedTables/>\r\n   <w:SnapToGridInCell/>\r\n   <w:WrapTextWithPunct/>\r\n   <w:UseAsianBreakRules/>\r\n  </w:Compatibility>\r\n  <w:BrowserLevel>MicrosoftInternetExplorer4</w:BrowserLevel>\r\n </w:WordDocument>\r\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if !mso]><object\r\n classid=\\"clsid:38481807-CA0E-42D2-BF39-B33AF135CC4D\\" id=ieooui></object>\r\n<style>\r\nst1\\\\:*{behavior:url(#ieooui) }\r\n</style>\r\n<![endif]--><style>\r\n<!--\r\n /* Style Definitions */\r\n p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal\r\n	{mso-style-parent:\\"\\";\r\n	margin:0in;\r\n	margin-bottom:.0001pt;\r\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\r\n	font-size:12.0pt;\r\n	font-family:\\"Times New Roman\\";\r\n	mso-fareast-font-family:\\"Times New Roman\\";}\r\n@page Section1\r\n	{size:8.5in 11.0in;\r\n	margin:1.0in 1.25in 1.0in 1.25in;\r\n	mso-header-margin:.5in;\r\n	mso-footer-margin:.5in;\r\n	mso-paper-source:0;}\r\ndiv.Section1\r\n	{page:Section1;}\r\n-->\r\n</style><!--[if gte mso 10]>\r\n<style>\r\n /* Style Definitions */\r\n table.MsoNormalTable\r\n	{mso-style-name:\\"Table Normal\\";\r\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\r\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\r\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\r\n	mso-style-parent:\\"\\";\r\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\r\n	mso-para-margin:0in;\r\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;\r\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\r\n	font-size:10.0pt;\r\n	font-family:\\"Times New Roman\\";}\r\n</style>\r\n<![endif]-->\r\n\r\n<p class=\\"MsoNormal\\" style=\\"text-align: center; line-height: 200%; background-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\\" align=\\"center\\"><font size=\\"4\\">Pick\r\nAn Element: Gold</font></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\\"MsoNormal\\" style=\\"text-indent: 0.5in; line-height: 200%; background-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(255, 255, 0);\\"><font size=\\"4\\">Alan Lightman is\r\nwriting this essay and he is interested in sharing a story about a woman not\r\naccepting a gold necklace from a man. He also is interested in describing the\r\nproperties of gold. Gold is often used in jewelry, dental fillings, making\r\ncoins, and helping shield spacecrafts and skyscrapers from the sun’s heat. Gold\r\nis found in period six, group eleven and is a transition metal. It is most\r\nnormally found as a solid and it is a metal. Gold was commonly used in ancient\r\ncivilizations and two thirds of the world’s supply comes from <st1:country-region><st1:place>South\r\n  Africa</st1:place></st1:country-region>. It is generally non toxic and is\r\nknown as the most malleable and ductile of all metals. Thankfully, it is not\r\ndangerous in normal exposure quantities. Gold is found free in nature and is\r\nassociated with quartz, pyrite, and other minerals. It’s also found in sea\r\nwater, but no effective economic process has been designed yet to extract it\r\nfrom this source.</font></p>', '2009-10-13 16:30:19'),
(793, 336, 56, 0, '<BR>\r\n<P>Arsenic</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>1.&nbsp; M. Feroze Ahmed is writing about Arsenic because when he was a little boy, he used to take small doses of it to build a resistance against <FONT size=2 face=Arial>against the common cold, asthma, coughs, scabies and other illnesses.&nbsp; </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial>2.&nbsp; Some uses of this element are in small doses, it can help prevent the common cold and other common illnesses.&nbsp; In larger doses, it acts as a lethal poison.&nbsp; It is an essential trace element in animals, though not in plants. </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial>3.&nbsp; This element is found on the 15th group and the 4th period and is located in the middle right of the periodic table.&nbsp; It is normally found in the solid state, and it is a&nbsp;mattaloid.&nbsp; </FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial>4.&nbsp; No.&nbsp; Some interesting fact about it are in even lethal doses&nbsp;it is odorless, tasteless and virtually undetectable to consumers in food, in the air and in liquid, which is why it is so commonly used in homicides and suicides.&nbsp; It is also why it is such an issue in poorer counties without essential water purification because it causes serious illness and often times death.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial>5.&nbsp; This element is very dangerous and extremely lethal.</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial></FONT>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2 face=Arial>6.&nbsp; In nature, aresenic is normally found in the free state.&nbsp;</FONT></P>', '2009-10-13 16:36:17'),
(794, 261, 55, 0, '<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center\\" align=center><STRONG><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Arial\\">Beryllium (Be)</SPAN></STRONG><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\"><?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = \\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office\\" /><o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt\\"><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt\\"><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Arial\\">This article was written by Lee S. Newman. He is the head of the Division of Environmental &amp; Occupational Health Sciences at&nbsp;the&nbsp;National Jewish Medical &amp; Research Center. He has treated and taken care of hundreds of patients diagnosed with beryllium. Beryllium&nbsp;is&nbsp;one of the most toxic elements on the periodic table. Up to&nbsp;20% of people exposed to beryllium develop&nbsp;beryllium disease. Inhaling powdered compounds containing beryllium&nbsp;can lead&nbsp;to berylliosis, a disease of the lungs that&nbsp;is&nbsp;a painful and sometimes fatal. Beryllium is found among the alkaline earth metals in the second group in the second row of the periodic table. At room temperature beryllium is a solid. French chemist Nicholas L. Vauqulelin discovered beryllium in 1798. Beryllium is used as a structural material for spacecraft and high-speed aircraft. The alloy produced by combining beryllium with aluminum, copper, or nickel has excellent thermal and electrical conductivity properties. Beryllium is most commonly found&nbsp;combined with other elements.</SPAN><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\"><o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"BACKGROUND: white; MARGIN: 7.5pt 15pt\\"><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma\\">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P><SPAN style=\\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #333333; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-fareast-font-family: \\''Times New Roman\\''; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA\\">*Mrs.&nbsp;Hollis: Please grade this post instead of my first one about cesium. I didnt realize that there was already a summary on cesium</SPAN><BR>', '2009-10-13 16:52:49'),
(795, 516, 58, 0, '<font style=\\"font-family: verdana; color: rgb(255, 0, 204);\\" size=\\"3\\">Pick an element: Tungsten<br>This eassy is written by Rick Lowden, and he liked takning things apart as a child. Like incandescent light bulbs, and finding the tungsten filament in the center. It is used in light bulbs,&nbsp; cell phones, pagers, engine components, radiation shielding, and golf balls. It is located in the transition elements. In group 6 and row 6. It is a metal. Half a paint can of tungsten powder weighs about thirty-five pounds. The powder was used to make bullets and reinforced metal sheets in world war I. its not easy t process though, and bullets had to be cheap. it’s a soft metal, and that make casting impossible.&nbsp; </font><br>', '2009-10-13 16:53:22'),
(796, 413, 54, 0, '<P><STRONG><U><FONT size=3>Mercury</FONT></U></STRONG></P>\r\n<P>Rudy M Baum wrote this article because he once conducted and experiment with friends without his teacher\\''s approval in seventh grade&nbsp;because of his fascination and curiosity&nbsp;with mercury. His fascination continued throughout his life and now he is a chemist.&nbsp;Some uses of this element are: it is used in thermometers, barometers, diffusion pumps, and other instruments. The element is found on the periodic table in group 12 and&nbsp;period 6. The state that it is normally found in is a liquid and it is a metal. Some interesting facts about&nbsp;mercury are it is the only metal that is a liquid at room temperature and it alloys easily with most metals. Mercury is very dangerous because its vapors are toxic; it affects your central nervous system, mouth, gums, and teeth. Mercury is rare in Earth\\''s crust; it is primarily found in cinnabar ore.<BR></P>', '2009-10-13 17:52:08'),
(797, 376, 54, 0, '<P align=center><BR><STRONG>Phosphorus (P)</STRONG></P>\r\n<P align=left>C. Dale Poulter wrore the essay about phosphorus he loved chemistry ever since he was a kid but never in his classes did he really learn about it so he wanted to learn more about it. Some uses for this element are that its a component of living systems in things such as bones, nervous tissue, cell protoplasm and others. The element phosphorus is found in period 3 and group 15 it is a non-metal and at room temperature it is a waxy white solid. An interesting fact about it is that when it is exposed to damp air it glows in the dark. The element is not dangerous when it is in normal exposure quantities. The element is usually found in a free state. </P>', '2009-10-13 18:25:59'),
(798, 512, 54, 0, '<font size=\\"5\\"><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman; font-weight: bold;\\">Francium</span></font><br style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\">The article written on my element was very interesting. It was written by Luis A. Orozco. She is professor of physics at the State University of New York, Stony Brook. In the element Orozco states that she was interested in performing precision measurements of its spectroscopic properties to find out more about Francium. </span><br style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\">Francium is the heaviest of all alkali metals.</span><br style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\">Due to its scarcity and short half life, there are not many uses for francium other than scientific research. It has no behavioral use. On the periodic table it is located in very bottom far left hand corner. Group 1 , period 7 to be exact. Francium is most found in a solid state according to Orozco’s article, and is also a metal. Also Francium was named after France. It was discovered in 1939 by French chemist Marguerite Perey of the Curie Institute in Paris. A minute amount is estimated to exist in Earth\\''s crust, and according to the article Francium can be produced artificially by bombarding thorium with protons. This element is found in a science lab and cannot be found in everyday life. Therefore, it will not ever be exposed under normal conditions to be dangerous. </span><br style=\\"font-family: times new roman;\\"><br><br>', '2009-10-13 18:34:38'),
(799, 624, 56, 0, '<p><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: 19px; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Andrew Finnegan &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;PICK-AN-ELEMENT: Seaborgium.</span></font></span></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\"><br></span></font></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">This essay was written by Eric Seaborg of Charlottesville, VA. His father, Glen T. Seaborg, is the chemist that&nbsp;</span></font></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">discovered plutonium during WWII. His mission was to&nbsp;</span></font><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">develop a process to isolate plutonium so it could be&nbsp;</span></font></span></p><p><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">used in a theoretical weapon, the atomic bomb. It was not until the 1990\\''s that Seaborgium was discovered as the 106th&nbsp;</span></font></span></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" color=\\"#000000\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">element. This element is radioactive and artificially made, there are not any uses for it outside of research. It is found&nbsp;</span></font></span></font></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" color=\\"#000000\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">where period seven and group six meet, between Bohrium and Dubnium. &nbsp;It is, in its simplest form, a solid and is in the</span></font></span></font></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" color=\\"#000000\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;transition metals. At first, Seaborg was hesitant to accept the recognition of having an element named in his honor, but&nbsp;</span></font></span></font></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" color=\\"#000000\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">after consulting his wife, he accepted. This element is radioactive so yes, it is dangerous. It is not found naturally,</span></font></span></font></p><p><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" color=\\"#000000\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: normal; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;but artificially created.</span></font></span></font></p><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Sources are as follows:&nbsp;</span></font><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: normal; white-space: pre; \\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">http://pubs.acs.org/cen/80th/seaborgium.html</span></font></span></div><div style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" color=\\"#000000\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"line-height: normal; white-space: pre;\\"><font class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" face=\\"\\''comic sans ms\\''\\"><span class=\\"Apple-style-span\\" style=\\"font-size: small;\\">                                http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seaborgium</span></font></span></font></div>', '2009-10-13 18:46:39'),
(800, 284, 56, 0, '<span style=\\"font-family: georgia;\\"><font size=\\"2\\">POTASSIUM<br><br>1) Susan R. Morrissey wrote this article and her interest is this guy she met asked her her favorite element and she just blurted out tin, and the guy said potassium. He liked it because he liked bananas.<br>2) It regulates water balance in the body, its used in fireworks, it maintains a healthy health and regulates blood pressure.<br>3) It is an akali metal and it is in group one, period 4. And it is a solid.<br>4)It was found in 1807 by&nbsp; Sir Humphrey Davy.<br>5) No it is not dangerous.<br>6) It is found in most soils, and combined it is in soil, grass, and minerals. Extracted it is solid and silver.<span style=\\"font-style: italic;\\"><span style=\\"font-style: italic;\\"><span style=\\"font-style: italic;\\"></span></span></span><br></font></span>', '2009-10-13 18:50:24');
INSERT INTO `forum_replies` (`reply_id`, `uid`, `fid`, `rid`, `body`, `posted_at`) VALUES
(801, 382, 54, 0, '<BR>\r\n<P style=\\"TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal align=center><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-SIZE: 48pt\\"><FONT face=Calibri><FONT color=#000000><FONT size=6><U><STRONG>Nickel<?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = \\"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office\\" /><o:p></o:p></STRONG></U></FONT></FONT></FONT></SPAN></P>\r\n<P style=\\"MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt\\" class=MsoNormal><SPAN style=\\"LINE-HEIGHT: 115%; FONT-FAMILY: \\''Times New Roman\\'', \\''serif\\''; FONT-SIZE: 12pt\\"><FONT color=#000000><SPAN style=\\"mso-tab-count: 1\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The person who wrote this essay about nickel was David Hanson. David’s interest in this element is that it is used in human life very frequently. Nickel is used in everything like coins, vehicles, jewelry, paper clips, and many new uses that are still being invented. The one major use of nickel is stainless steel. Nickel is found in the transition metals and in period 4 of the periodic table. Some interesting facts about this element are that many nickel compounds are known human carcinogens. It is also an excellent catalyst for many chemical reactions. Without nickel we would not have half the things we have today, including, electronics, nanotechnology, and catalysis. This element can be dangerous to nickel refiners. It caused health issues in the past, but today exposures to nickel are lower. Health problems are still very cautious with nickel refinery dust and nickel sub sulfide. Itchy rashes and irritating piercings on the ear or on the body are often caused by nickel. This element is often combined with other elements.<o:p></o:p></FONT></SPAN></P>', '2009-10-13 19:04:20'),
(802, 378, 58, 0, '<P><FONT size=2>Pick-An-Element: potassium</FONT></P>\r\n<P><FONT size=2>Susan Morrissey wrote an article on potassium. When she met this good looking man at a college outing they starting talking about their favorite element and his was potassium.&nbsp;P<FONT face=\\"\\">otassium is used in foods, fertilizers, glass, soaps, and match heads. This element is found in the first column fourth row, usually found as a solid and is a metal. Potassium is the seventh most abundant metal and is never found free in nature. It occurs in many minerals mined in Germany, Spain, Canada, the U.S., and Italy. Usually potassium is found in soil and fertilizers in its free state.Potassium has&nbsp;a K as its symbol the reason for the was that it<FONT face=\\"\\">&nbsp;came from potassium\\''s Latin name <EM>kalium. </EM>Potassium is a great mineral for everyones health.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>', '2009-10-13 19:20:36'),
(803, 618, 58, 0, '<BR><SPAN lang=EN>\r\n<P>Pick-an-Element: Lithium</P>\r\n<P>Paul V. R. Schleyer of the University of Georgia wrote an article on the element lithium. He stated that it was his involvement with the highly peculiar structures of organolithium </P>\r\n<P>Compounds that initiated his interest in lithium in the 1970’s. Lithium is normally used as a battery anode material. It is alloyed with magnesium and aluminum for lightweight performance metals for aircraft. Lithium can be found in group one of the Periodic table, the Alkali Metals, and in the second period beside beryllium. Lithium is usually found in a silvery white, soft metallic state. Some interesting facts about lithium are that it is the lightest metal in the periodic table, and that it is a trace element in the human body. Lithium is not usually dangerous in normal exposure quantities, and is typically found in igneous rocks and in mineral spring waters. </P></SPAN>', '2009-10-13 19:47:19'),
(804, 621, 56, 0, '&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<font size=\\"5\\">&nbsp;LEAD</font><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bassam Z. Shakhashiri wrote an essay on lead discuss the interest in the element lead. His interest in studying lead was because he was always very interested in coins, and the coins always felt heavy so he wanted to know if lead was in coins. He soon learned alot more interesting facts about lead. Such as the romans used lead to make pipes, cookwear, and drinking glasses. Lead is found under the the metal elements,and is in group 14, row 6. A very interesting fact is lead is a poison, and its called lead poisoning. Lead can be found anywhere, in the bible it stated that they believed lead was the oldest metal. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br><h3><font><font face=\\"Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Swiss,SunSans-Regular\\" size=\\"1\\"><a href=\\"http://pubs.acs.org/cen/80th/lead.html#Anchor--Bass-8297\\"><au><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"font-weight: bold;\\"></span></span><br></au></a></font></font></h3>', '2009-10-13 19:49:14'),
(805, 306, 54, 0, '<H3><FONT size=4><FONT color=#3366cc><FONT color=#00ff66><FONT color=#000000>URANIUM<BR></FONT><AU><AU><FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></H3>\r\n<P><FONT size=2><FONT><FONT><FONT color=#3333cc>PETER EICHSTAEDT,&nbsp;WHO IS ON THE&nbsp;INTERNATIONAL RESEARCH &amp; EXCHANGE BOARD, WROTE THIS ESSAY. URANIUM CAN GIVE YOU LUNG CANCER IF YOU ARE EXPOSED TO IT FOR A LONG PERIOD OF TIME AND CAN BE FATAL. THIS ELEMENT IS FOUND IN THE INNERTRANSITION METALS SECTION ON THE PERIODIC TABLE OF ELEMENTS. IT DOES\\''T BELONG TO ANDY PARTICULAR GROUG OR ROW. URANIUM IS A METAL. URANIUM IS COMMONLY FOUND IN <FONT face=Arial><FONT>MANY ROCKS,&nbsp;LARGE AMOUNTS&nbsp;IN PITCHBLENDE&nbsp;AND CARNOTITE. URANIUM WAS DISCOVERD&nbsp;BY&nbsp;MARTIN KLAPROTH</FONT><FONT> IN1789 AND WAS NAMED AFTER THE PLANET URANUS.</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></P>', '2009-10-13 19:54:35'),
(806, 407, 58, 0, 'Pick-an-Element- Potassium<br><br>This essay about, potassium, is written by Susan Morrissey. She is very interested in potassium because it is an electrolyte mineral essential to maintaining good health. Potassium is responsible for the function of cells. It has also been shown to be effective at reducing blood pressure. In addition, it is responsible for the functions of muscles. Potassium is necessary for fluid balance in our body. Without potassium you will die. It is responsible for your heart beating and the movement of your muscles. Potassium is found in the first group and the fourth period on the periodic table. Potassium is a sold metal. It was first prepared in pure form in 1807 by English chemist Sir Humphry Davy. It is highly reactive when placed in water. Potassium is so active that it never occurs free in nature. It always occurs in compounds, combined with other elements.<br><br>', '2009-10-13 20:19:36'),
