(1634, 980, 0, 1628, 'Ethically I have a problem with almost every single one of those statements. If two parents are ugly, and they don’t want their child to face the same humiliation that they did, why shouldn’t they be allowed to do that for their child? Secondly, we’re talking about physical features- eye color, lips, nose, foot size, etc. We’re not talking about prenatal steroids. Also, in my opinion, it should be restricted to a couple’s own gene pool. There are almost limitless possibilities within a couple’s own gene pool, and any baby within those genetic possibilities is perfectly fine by my view. That child could have been their child even without genetic manipulation. \r\nAnd as for genetic disease elimination, I cannot help but saying, how cruel are you? First of all, fixing mutated children would not increase population, because if mutations are extreme enough to kill a child, the body will naturally abort the fetus. These mutated children will most likely be severely handicapped, mentally and physically. They will need expensive medical care, extensive personal care, and will never give anything back to society. The parent’s pain would be unimaginable, beyond unbearable. The parents have no choice but to care for their children for the rest of their lives, they will never again have a carefree day. They will never be able to enjoy themselves, and even after they retire they will worry about what will happen to their mentally handicapped child after they die. \r\nAnd to correct your last statement, you are living perfectly fine. And that’s great, for you. But there are other people in the world who aren’t so lucky. There are children who are severely deformed, who have lived there entire lives with kids pointing at them, people ridiculing them, and never being excepted by society. And they may look different, but inside they know they’re different, and it hurts. But if their parents can prevent that, they will be able to live happy lives. They will be able to make friends, go on dates, get a job, maybe one day get married. And why should we deny them that opportunity? \r\nAlso, the parents who have abortions don’t want kids. They’re not going to try again, because even if that was a perfectly healthy fetus, they didn’t want it. People who want kids will keep the baby, even if the baby is deformed. So why can’t we just make it so that the kid is not deformed. It’s not going to skyrocket the population, and even so, the population is skyrocketing already. As are the percentage of kids born with handicaps. And if we have the ability to change that, to give one person who wouldn’t really have a life, a life, why wouldn’t we? How can we conscientiously say  otherwise?', '2010-02-16 13:21:25'),
