(2008, 565, 168, 0, '<P>I think this movie makes a very convising argument about what will happen to earth in the future. I feel that if we don''t start changing our ways now that the predictions from the movie will come true or the events will be similar to those in the movie. We need to take action and make our resources last and become less dependent on oil and find different energy sources. We may have some in place but that is not enough. We need to be completely be off our use of coal,&nbsp;but move&nbsp;on to light and wind power. If we start making changes now we will be able to change the future. I believe that the predictions made are very fitting because of the way we are treating the earth. I say we need to take this movie as a warning and move on to a&nbsp;bigger and safer way of energy.</P>\r\n<P>-Kirstin</P>', '2010-08-23 17:53:42'),
(2009, 597, 168, 0, '<P>watching this video made me realize how much danger our planet really is in. In the video one of the poeple had said many times that because of the gradual change, people don''t notice and understand how vital the change is and how rapidly it is occuring. I would suggest that everyone should watch this video and leave from it comprehending the whole idea of this change. If the world could possibly become like that i wouldn''t want to have kids or anyone else to have kids because i wouldn''t want them to suffer through that kind of life. Is there a possible way to decrease population over time? Why is the population increasing as the environment and economy gets worse? What is happening in other countries, and the poor countries? Could they possibly be wiped out first? Since a lot of the ice caps are melting and there isn''t going to be any water is there any way to collect as much water as we can to survive a little longer with it? It feels as if too much is happening too fast and that there is not enough time to find the resources and technology to better things a bit. </P>', '2010-08-23 18:20:10'),
(2010, 1356, 168, 0, 'Watching this movie really got me thinking about what we''re doing to our world. The fact that we use so much energy and send off so many toxic chemicals into our Earth''s atmosphere is bad enough but not realizing our mistakes earlier is another. I feel that if we don''t do something about our Earth now, the predictions that were mentioned in the movie will come true. Watching this movie also made me realize how little we as the people living on Earth are doing. I really would feel horrible for the future children of Earth that will not witness all the great things we have right now due to our mistakes. If we start using more sun and wind power, it would make a huge difference and possibly save a lot that we have. What differences would the people of Earth be willing to make in order to save the planet? Why are we waiting til the last possible minute to try and save everything? Why are Americans being so stubborn to share the technology we have even though it could save our lives? What will happen to the people (i.e will the birth rate drop, will life expectancy drop) if we don''t do anything? Everything feels like it''s happening too fast and we''re not doing anything quickly about it to stop it even though it will save us.<br>', '2010-08-23 19:20:18'),
(2011, 1365, 168, 0, 'I think the scariest thing about this video is that most of it (at least\r\n up to where we''ve watched) takes place during our lifetime. When people\r\n talk about the harmful affects of our destructive actions, I feel like \r\nthey''re always still generations away-- maybe affecting the people two \r\ngenerations from me if we really don''t make any changes. But this movie \r\nshowed that the situation is much more dire than we believe it to be. \r\nAnd the fact that these results and this time line were predicted by \r\nleading scientists who know what they''re doing really drives the point \r\nhome, worst case scenario or not. This video has made me seriously look at my contribution to the destruction of our planet. <br>', '2010-08-24 00:31:42'),
(2022, 708, 168, 0, '<BR>The movie "2100" was very intriguing because it described the possible effects of our inaction as a society to genuine issues. While it is still only a possibiliity it is startiling at how much must be done in order to protect the earth, it shows just how unstable the bioshpere actually is, and what actions would be needed to avoid danger. The fact that the earth can be protected from this dangers is very enlightening but it is intriguing because as the movie shows the Earth is not as predictable as we would like to belive, so how can we know with any certainty how are actions will effect the earth in the long run. Regardless, the film was an eye opening experience into the problems effecting us and the interrelated effects of each issue, hopefully we can learn from this documentary and lead a more biologically friendly lifestyle.', '2010-08-29 20:36:46'),
(2013, 1361, 168, 0, 'The movie was very interesting and real to me. I have always wondered of what the worst things that could happen were and the movie cleared them up a little. We, as high school students, live in a very&nbsp;important&nbsp;and interesting time because we can see the fate of the future that can be very different&nbsp;depending&nbsp;on which direction people choose. I hope people today come to an agreement for restoring the balance of the Earth so the scenarios in the movie won''t happen, however I think that even if the world comes to a decision to regulate emissions, other problems involving the environment will still occur. In my opinion people have to act for the best and hope for the best, but still be prepared for bad and unexpected scenarios and&nbsp;occurrences.', '2010-08-24 18:24:30'),
(2014, 584, 168, 0, 'Although the events shown in this video were the worst-case scenario, many experts believe they are a valid possibility. People, especially in America, have become accustomed to a certain standard of living and although we know it is not possible to continue this infinitely, we choose not to consider the consequences of our actions. This movie served as a wake up call and shows what could happen to our planet in our lifetime, which increases the urgency for increased attention to this problem. People need to consciously realize that our resources are finite and need to begin living according to those means and, although this process will be slow, world leaders need to make this a priority and make productive use of global summits, unlike what occurred in Copenhagen. If no common ground is met, the scenario presented in the video is extremely likely.&nbsp; <br>', '2010-08-24 19:49:01'),
(2015, 587, 168, 0, 'To me, climate change is something that has always been in the back of my mind. However, I have &nbsp;not had the materials nor the incentive to really "live greenly" or to help limit my use of destructive materials or of resources. The movie, "Earth 2100" really hit home, in that it gave me the incentive. The movie showed us pretty much what leading scientists have predicted as the rest of our lives. It could be the "worst case scenario" but it is a scenario that we must consider in our everyday decisions. Therefore, I believe that it should be shown to all high school students, college students, even elementary and middle school students. We need to spread the incentive that we all felt after watching the movie, in order to increase the chance that our generation can fix things the best we can. However, that is a good plan but the movie showed things are moving alot faster than we thought. Is spreading the incentive going to be enough? Probably not, but its going to be a start. The key is going to be the politics in that the countries of the world need to put aside their differences and suspicions and work together to save Earth. The other thing is the private companies that own the technology to help the "developing" countries grow "greenly" need to hand that technology over, to better the world. Then it is up to the people to implement the measures such as growing their own food, collecting rain water, wind and solar energy collection etc. to finally save the world. And all this needs to start now.&nbsp;', '2010-08-24 19:50:52'),
(2016, 1358, 0, 2011, 'I completely agree with Juhi''s response. In the video, a huge turning point for the future was the year 2015. When we talk about our futures, we are full of hope, talking about what colleges we are planning on attending, and discussing our career paths. We''re completely oblivious to the fact that 2015 is the year that many of us will head off to grad schools, or take our college diplomas and head off to face the world. Every single one of us says, in four years, I''ll be done with undergrad. Nobody thinks, in four years, the future of the human race could be at stake. At this crucial turning point, we will be the world''s task force, and it will be up to us to make those big decisions of our leaders become a reality. Because while visionaries dream big, in the end it comes down to how united the general population of the world is if anything is to be achieved. In 4 short years, will we be too focused on creating our own futures to protect the one at risk?', '2010-08-24 22:01:21'),
(2017, 1366, 168, 0, 'It seems to me that the bottom line of this movie is that&nbsp;my generation will be responsible for former generations'', and our own generation''s, disrespect and over use of the earth''s natural and non-renewable resources. I think that the human race has a vast amount of potential to become great stewards of the Earth, and on the opposite end of the spectrum, we are our own worst enemy. I believe that because, as students, we have been bombarded by images of what the earth will become if we continue down the path that we are currently on, we will start our adult lives caring about the one thing we share with every other person on the planet, our home. By the time our children are born, living "green" will be the norm, and within a few generations, we will have developed the technology to continue a high standard of living while greatly reducing our impact on the environment. In order to begin/continue a global movement towards the reduction of pollution/waste, however, awareness must be spread to all corners of the world. Those living in "less developed" (sorry Mr. Kern) countries must also be aware of the problems facing the environment. No one can be left out. The potential for these countries economically speaking is also vast. The sun does not discriminate against poor/wealthy countries. Perhaps green technology is the way to bring under developed countried into the global economy. Our&nbsp;economy is still centered on making the most money in the fastest way possible without any thought to the future, but, as Michael Furdyk of TakingItGlobal.org says, "an economy that does not care about the future,&nbsp;has no future." So&nbsp;let''s begin preaching corporate responsibility in anything resembling a business class, so that as we and those around us grow older, we learn that the world does not revolve around us, and if we&nbsp;think it does,&nbsp;we&nbsp;don''t have&nbsp;a lot of time to enjoy it. &nbsp;<BR>', '2010-08-24 22:56:14'),
(2018, 589, 168, 0, 'The video "Earth 2011" showed that the destructive behaviors of the United States (and the growing destructive behaviors of the rest of the world) will eventually lead to humanity''s downfall. We all know that we need to "go green" and stop with these destructive behaviors, but this movie really is a wake up call to show us how destructive these behaviors really are and the possible effects that our lifestyles will have on the future. Even though this video was a fictional account of what is likely to happen, it is backed by information that really makes me really wonder why people are so resistant to changing their lifestyles even when it means that making little changes could save a potentially&nbsp;devastating&nbsp;future. I found it surprising that there needs to be four earths to support the lifestyle of the United States. How can the people of the United States accept the fact that we are being so ruthless with our resources? This video was really eye opening and showed me just how bad things are with the way we treat the world and that we need to fix what we''re doing before things become un-fixable.&nbsp;<div><br></div><div>~Chloe~</div>', '2010-08-24 23:01:15'),
(2019, 594, 168, 0, 'The most frightening thing about this video was that most of the events that were discussed happen during our own lifetime. It really hits home to think about the planet we''re inheriting and our crucial role in it''s future. I feel like I''ve always heard about our depleting resources and destructive lifestyle, but the problems seem lightyears away because we have grown accustomed to our way of living, because the problems don''t seem to be big enough and don''t seem to be affecting us personally yet. Sure, we hear about global warming and ice caps melting, but it seems so far away. I believe that until gas prices go up and we don''t have clean water anymore -- problems that directly affect us and make our lives different -- we won''t understand the severity of the situation. This video showed that the problems we often think so little of are much more extreme than we know. Although the video showed a "worst-case scenario," it is still a very real and very threatening possibility. If countries cannot collaborate and compromise, if the human race refuses to make sacrifices, then we are headed down a dismal path, and we will soon be past the point of no return. At home, I do things that many people do: recycle, reuse plastic bags, turn of the lights when I leave a room, conserve water as much as possible...and while these things may be helpful, they will be much more meaningful if more people do them. If we wait for a wake-up call, we might be too late. We need to somehow shake people out of their reveries, show them what''s happening, and find a way for the majority of us to help the environment and ultimately save the the earth, our planet, the only home we have. So many of us, especially in America, are used to a certain standard of living -- we often choose not to consider the effect we''re having on our planet, but the fact of the matter is that we cannot let ourselves continue down this road. Common ground must be met, solutions must be presented, and plans must be put into action. It is urgent that we respond to the situation -- it''s not far away or impossible. On the contrary, we are on the brink of truly collapsing under our own weight. ', '2010-08-24 23:05:12'),
(2020, 1400, 168, 0, '<P><BR>I accidentally posted this on the homepage originally. My bad.</P>\r\n<P>&nbsp;</P>\r\n<P>The first observation I would like to make about Earth 2100 is that I did not sleep during it. (I promise I have a point.) Which, considering I was in a dark room at the end of the day and am usually a pretty tough movie critic, is a fairly impressive feat for a made-for-television science fiction-esque piece. It certainly did its job and made me fear my own future, but it also made a green-aware impact on me. I am one of the most un-green people I know, so this, too, is pretty notable. In fact, I went upstairs a little while ago and unplugged my phone charger and stereos while they''re not in use. I''ve also put halogen bulbs on my shopping list for someone else to buy because I haven''t reached the ''spend my incredibly rare and precious teenage money on going green'' point. Maybe I''ll get there. Maybe I need to be freaked out some more. Who knows? But I certainly learned a lot on new renewable resource technology and how without it, we''re basically screwed. Yay humans!<BR></P>', '2010-08-25 12:37:14'),
(2021, 1360, 168, 0, '<P>The movie "Earth 2100" shows its viewers the big posssibility of a dark future, where civilization as we know today collapses completely. This is mainly due by we humans and our exesive use of our natural resources without thinking about the future,and the ecological damage we are making to it. According to Executive Producer Michael Bicks, "this program was developed to show the worst-case scenario for human civilization. The movie doesn''t&nbsp;leave the&nbsp;message that these events will happen rather, something&nbsp; possible to happen if we fail to seriously address the complex problems of climate change, resource depletion and overpopulation. I believe this movie serves as wake up call such that if we want to prevent this future we must change our life styles now.<BR></P>', '2010-08-25 17:55:55'),
(2023, 1405, 168, 0, '<BR>Ever since Project Citizen freshman year, I, along with many other students in my group (ahem especially Juhi)&nbsp;learned a lot about how humans are making a hell hole out of our earth. I was very disappointed in learning that so many people in the world are wasteful of their resources. I think the real disappointment, however, was when I realized I was one of those people. There are so many people that dicuss a green way of living, but there are few that follow through with it. The scary part of this movie was that we really are approaching the point of no return, and, I don''t know about anyone else, but I don''t exactly have faith in US citizens to clean up our act and start living green. The fact that we may still be alive while this happens scares me even more. This movie definately made an impact on me, and I know that in order to see a change, I must change as well. One person can make all the difference.', '2010-08-29 22:30:38'),
(2024, 1406, 168, 0, 'Personally, i thought this movie was intended to be a wake up call to the millions of people in the United States who are consuming disproportionate amounts of energy and producing pollutants on a large scale. I liked how the movie focused on the fact that while Americans might be able to live this way for a while, if India and China emulate our habits, it''s game over for all of us. I think it was mentioned that 4 earths would be required to sustain us? That was quite a shocker. While the problem is drastic, if we all do our part in consuming less energy, the disastrous future can be avoided, or at least delayed until we die. Relying on companies to solve our problems is probably not the best way to approach things because companies will always be invested in increasing profits, and as we''ve seen with logging and chemical companies, that doesn''t always work out well. The companies'' technologies will be private and won''t be available for mass consumption until they decide so. If governments, the private sector, and the people work together, we should be able to solve our problems just like we created them to begin with.&nbsp;', '2010-08-29 22:35:22'),
(2025, 1399, 168, 0, '<img alt="" src="http://http://sphotos.ak.fbcdn.net/hphotos-ak-snc3/hs066.snc3/13350_1314912995769_1319012140_30878780_3006971_n.jpg" align="none"><img style="width: 105px; height: 81px;" alt="" src="http://sphotos.ak.fbcdn.net/hphotos-ak-snc3/hs066.snc3/13350_1314912995769_1319012140_30878780_3006971_n.jpg" align="right"><span style="font-family: arial;">Well it seems to me that we''re all doomed, for the most part at least. No to sound like a pessimist, but it''s true. I agree with the one in the video who said that humans won''t act until tragedy of epic proportions strikes.</span> The reason I say this is because it is apparent in our culture, at least in the United States of America, that we are aware of the issues at hand, but because it does not impact our everyday lives yet, we continue using technologies that contribute to the human footprint on the planet. Our government has invested money on the development and distribution of greener technology, but it has not reached the point of mass distribution or affordability, nor has it reached the same popularity as more polluting technologies. For example, cleaner vehicles such as the Segway or the UNO have not reached popularity like their diesel and gasoline fueled counter parts have. The fact that relatively little has been invested in these alternative technologies enough to convert to the use of them is troublesome to me and it seems that a similar chain of events will unfold that parallel those in Earth 2100. When we collectively decide to take action, much irreversible damage will already have been done.<br><br>I didn''t know how to identify myself or how people put their names on their entries, so I just put a picture of me so you would know it was me, Armando Jauregui. I''m sure the writing of my name will be included in the next step making this picture essentially useless for identification purposes.<br>', '2010-08-29 22:42:12'),
