(2063, 1361, 170, 0, 'Asian Elephant (Elephas Maximus) In situ/Ex situ conservation<div>by Richard Rodriguez and Stefan Denev&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><p class="MsoHeader" style="tab-stops:.5in"><span style="font-size:14.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt"><!--[if !supportEmptyParas]-->&nbsp;<!--[endif]--><o:p></o:p></span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Which one is the best method for the conservation of the Asian Elephant; in situ or ex situ conservation?</span></p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">After some debating about it we came up with the argument in situ conservation is the best method for the restoration of the Asian Elephant. The reason being goes with the argument that Asian Elephants cannot reproduce in ex situ reserves, which defeats the purpose of these kinds of reserves to have a species that will not be restored in these reserves. Although research is being done to successfully produce offspring through artificial insemination, in the long run such expensive techniques will not lead to any positive outcome, in terms of the restoration of the species.</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">With in situ conservation, the Asian Elephants can be kept in their natural habitats such as: Tropical deciduous forests, Sub-Tropical deciduous forests and grasslands. If reserves are established near areas where the populations of the asian elephant are most abundant,such as Central Asia, then the animals will be able to live and flourish in their natural habitat, protected both both by the natural environment and humans. There will be limited contact with humans for the elephants and they will not be confined like in a zoo providing them with more freedom. the natural reserves will provide regulations to humans, preventing from the natural habitat of the elephas maximus to continue to dissapear. However, there still are challenges for the in situ conservation in the natural habitat of elephants. These challenges include: Gaining the trust and permission of the people that live there and possibly require the areas of the elephants for agricultural use, persuading the governments of the countries to allow the construction of reserve stations and parks, and recruiting people to enforce the protection of the boundaries of the reserves and the regulations within the reserves. Another inportant task would be to educate the local people about why the elephants are endangered by ivory poaching, illegal capture, loss of land to farming and palm oil planations and deforestation. The education of the people will play an important role of making them understand what is happening and what they can do to stop this. These people will be the ones that will influence the elephants the most since their actions will take effect the fastest and slowly thir actions will spread to others, making people attempt to help save the elephants right in the center of their remaining populations.</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; "></p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Nevertheless, it is possible to use both in situ and ex situ conservation to the recovery of the Asian Elephant. A possible use of an ex-situ conservation program could be to raise support for in-situ elephant conservation projects. As (Clements, 2004) says “Keeping elephants in zoos allows us to assist wild elephants by…</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">1) Raising and providing funds for elephant conservation in the wild</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">2) Raising community support and awareness for elephant conservation in the wild</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">3) Developing skills and expertise to assist future management of elephants in the wild”</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; "></p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Ultimately this will be the best way to go because a combination between ex situ and in situ conservation will provide more aid into the restoration of the species. The reason is because to some extent the restoration of this species will be supported at an international level. This will be a positive event as it will allow us as a species to solve a problem that has been previously caused by us.</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; "></p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Bibliography:</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Anonymous. “Asian Elephant Conservation.” Conservation GIS Projects. 2002. Smithsonian National Zoological Park. Oct 24, 2010. &lt; http://nationalzoo.si.edu/SCBI/ConservationGIS/projects/asian_elephants/default.cfm&gt;</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Clements, Darill. “ELEPHANTS and ZOOS-the BIG picture.” 2004.<http: www.angelfire.com="" ab5="" ozzoos="" elephantcomments.html=""></http:></p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Elephas maximus. (2010). Retrieved from http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/7140/0</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Wikramanayake, E. D. (2002). Terrestrial ecoregions of the indo-pacific: a conservation assessment. Retrieved from http://books.google.com/books?id=_VGRBWqIG2gC&amp;pg=PA93&amp;lpg=PA93&amp;dq=biomes+in+northern+myanmar&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=FQ49auxA6s&amp;sig=6fIZuZwk-b2c8wDp5OYnXduLfD4&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=G4nLTLqZGsP38AbF4IGHAQ&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=3&amp;ved=0CBgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&amp;q=biomes%20in%20northern%20myanmar&amp;f=false</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Conservation gis projects. (2010). Retrieved from http://nationalzoo.si.edu/scbi/conservationgis/projects/asian_elephants/default.cfm</p><p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Times New Roman''; line-height: normal; font-size: medium; ">Asian elephants. (2010). Retrieved from http://www.thewildones.org/Animals/elephant.html</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="letter-spacing: 2px;"><i><p class="MsoHeader" style="tab-stops:.5in"><span style="font-size:14.0pt;\r\nmso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt"><!--[if !supportEmptyParas]-->&nbsp;<!--[endif]--><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 27px; font-size: 19px; ">&nbsp;</span></p></i></span>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="letter-spacing: 2px;"><i><br></i></span></p></p></div>', '2010-11-01 00:04:44');
