(2304, 594, 198, 0, 'Can we please go over 11.1.2, especially Memory Cells and Clonal Selection?', '2011-03-26 17:17:37'),
(2305, 594, 0, 2304, 'This is what I understand about Memory:\r\n\r\nB-cells, after they are activated by helper T-cells, begins to clone itself and produce plasma cells and memory cells. \r\n\r\nThe plasma cells produce antibodies which bind to the antigen of the pathogen present in the body and fight against them.\r\n\r\nThe memory cells have a long life and can &quot;remember&quot; the pathogen/antigen. If the pathogen invades the body a second time, the memory cells recognize it and help the immune system to activate a response against the pathogen much faster. Because the immune system can respond faster, the amount of antibodies produced to combat the pathogen is large, and the disease is usually eradicated before an individual might even feel any symptoms of the disease. \r\n\r\nHowever, I still don''t quite grasp what Clonal Selection is.', '2011-03-26 20:24:16'),
(2306, 594, 0, 2304, 'Clonal Selection: A process by which only those B-cells with antibodies that respond to a specific antigen (most probably the antigen of the pathogen that is invading the body at the time) is chosen to be cloned/divided in order to produce more antibodies.\r\n\r\nIs that correct?\r\n\r\nAlso, when does clonal selection occur? Does it occur after a B-cell has been activated by a helper T-cell, and the B-cells begins to clone itself, while also producing plasma and memory cells?', '2011-03-26 20:36:30'),
(2307, 594, 198, 0, 'Can we please also go over 11.1.5 together? I don''t understand what monoclonal antibodies are, or how they are produced. From what I gather, I think they''re man-made antibodies that target a specific antigen and can be produced in mass amounts in order to fight the antigen/pathogen that has invaded the body.', '2011-03-26 20:38:36'),
